{"evaluate-stig":{"version":"1.2507.6"},"title":"Evaluate-STIG_XCP-ng_Dom0_RHEL7","id":"220f815f-0546-4919-a221-63b5b6a22e84","stigs":[{"evaluate-stig":{"time":"2026-03-14T04:47:16.4120512-04:00","module":{"name":"Scan-XCP-ng_Dom0_RHEL7_Checks","version":"1.2026.3.11"}},"stig_name":"Red Hat Enterprise Linux 7 Security Technical Implementation Guide","display_name":"Red Hat Enterprise Linux 7","stig_id":"RHEL_7_STIG","release_info":"Release: 15 Benchmark Date: 24 Jul 2024","version":"3","uuid":"aa379772-3679-4074-8a4e-5b09f41d3e8e","reference_identifier":"2899","size":12,"rules":[{"group_id_src":"V-204392","group_tree":[{"id":"V-204392","title":"SRG-OS-000257-GPOS-00098","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-204392","severity":"high","group_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must be configured so that the file permissions, ownership, and group membership of system files and commands match the vendor values.","rule_id_src":"SV-204392r991558_rule","rule_id":"SV-204392r991558","rule_version":"RHEL-07-010010","rule_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must be configured so that the file permissions, ownership, and group membership of system files and commands match the vendor values.","fix_text":"Run the following command to determine which package owns the file:\n\n     # rpm -qf <filename>\n\nReset the user and group ownership of files within a package with the following command:\n\n     # rpm --setugids <packagename>\n\n\nReset the permissions of files within a package with the following command:\n\n     # rpm --setperms <packagename>","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the file permissions, ownership, and group membership of system files and commands match the vendor values.\n\nCheck the default file permissions, ownership, and group membership of system files and commands with the following command:\n\n     # for i in `rpm -Va | grep -E '^.{1}M|^.{5}U|^.{6}G' | cut -d \" \" -f 4,5`;do for j in `rpm -qf $i`;do rpm -ql $j --dump | cut -d \" \" -f 1,5,6,7 | grep $i;done;done\n\n     /var/log/gdm 040755 root root\n     /etc/audisp/audisp-remote.conf 0100640 root root\n     /usr/bin/passwd 0104755 root root\n\nFor each file returned, verify the current permissions, ownership, and group membership:\n     # ls -la <filename>\n\n     -rw-------. 1 root root 2017 Nov 1 10:03 /etc/audisp/audisp-remote.conf\n\nIf the file is more permissive than the default permissions, this is a finding.\n\nIf the file is not owned by the default owner and is not documented with the Information System Security Officer (ISSO), this is a finding.\n\nIf the file is not a member of the default group and is not documented with the Information System Security Officer (ISSO), this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_7_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Discretionary access control is weakened if a user or group has access permissions to system files and directories greater than the default.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000257-GPOS-00098, SRG-OS-000278-GPOS-00108","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-86473","V-71849"],"ccis":["CCI-001494","CCI-001496","CCI-002165","CCI-002235"],"reference_identifier":"2899","uuid":"22da49ee-386c-4d6e-967a-24fde9e0ab60","stig_uuid":"aa379772-3679-4074-8a4e-5b09f41d3e8e","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_Dom0_RHEL7_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 2\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nThe automated check identified system files whose permissions, ownership, or group membership differ from vendor-provided RPM package values on this XCP-ng Dom0 (RHEL 7-based) system. The scan executed 'rpm -Va' and found deviations in the M (permissions), U (user), or G (group) attributes compared to the RPM database. Per RHEL 7 STIG requirement RHEL-07-010010, all system file attributes must match vendor values to prevent unauthorized modification of system binaries and configuration files. Remediation: (1) Identify the package for each affected file: rpm -qf [filename]. (2) Reset user and group ownership: rpm --setugids [packagename]. (3) Reset permissions: rpm --setperms [packagename]. (4) If changes were intentional and documented, obtain ISSO/ISSM approval and document the deviation in the POA&M. The system administrator must investigate each mismatch to determine if unauthorized modification occurred.\n        \n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_Dom0_RHEL7_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: 4C3E4BF5F07BE819A00C564294AF9BA620E2A5A6\n~~~~~\nV-204392 - File Permissions/Ownership Match Vendor Values\n============================================================\n\nCommand: rpm -Va | grep permission/ownership/group changes\n----------------------------------------\nFAIL: The following files have permissions, ownership, or group\nmembership that differ from vendor RPM defaults:\n\n.M.......  c /boot/grub/grub.cfg\n.M.......  g /etc/lvm/cache/.cache\n.M.......  g /var/lock/iscsi\n.M.......  g /var/lock/iscsi/lock\n.M.......  g /boot/initrd-4.19.0+1.img\n.M.......    /etc/dhcp/dhclient.d/chrony.sh\n.M.......  c /etc/machine-id\n.M.......  g /etc/udev/hwdb.bin\n.M.......  g /var/lib/systemd/random-seed\n\nRemediation: rpm --setugids and rpm --setperms for affected packages.\n"},{"group_id_src":"V-204393","group_tree":[{"id":"V-204393","title":"SRG-OS-000023-GPOS-00006","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-204393","severity":"medium","group_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must display the Standard Mandatory DoD Notice and Consent Banner before granting local or remote access to the system via a graphical user logon.","rule_id_src":"SV-204393r958390_rule","rule_id":"SV-204393r958390","rule_version":"RHEL-07-010030","rule_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must display the Standard Mandatory DoD Notice and Consent Banner before granting local or remote access to the system via a graphical user logon.","fix_text":"Configure the operating system to display the Standard Mandatory DoD Notice and Consent Banner before granting access to the system.\n\nNote: If the system does not have GNOME installed, this requirement is Not Applicable.\n\nCreate a database to contain the system-wide graphical user logon settings (if it does not already exist) with the following command:\n\n# touch /etc/dconf/db/local.d/01-banner-message\n\nAdd the following line to the [org/gnome/login-screen] section of the \"/etc/dconf/db/local.d/01-banner-message\":\n\n[org/gnome/login-screen]\nbanner-message-enable=true\n\nUpdate the system databases:\n\n# dconf update\n\nUsers must log out and back in again before the system-wide settings take effect.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the operating system displays the Standard Mandatory DoD Notice and Consent Banner before granting access to the operating system via a graphical user logon.\n\nNote: If the system does not have GNOME installed, this requirement is Not Applicable. \n\nCheck to see if the operating system displays a banner at the logon screen with the following command:\n\n# grep banner-message-enable /etc/dconf/db/local.d/*\nbanner-message-enable=true\n\nIf \"banner-message-enable\" is set to \"false\" or is missing, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_7_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Display of a standardized and approved use notification before granting access to the operating system ensures privacy and security notification verbiage used is consistent with applicable federal laws, Executive Orders, directives, policies, regulations, standards, and guidance.\n\nSystem use notifications are required only for access via logon interfaces with human users and are not required when such human interfaces do not exist.\n\nThe banner must be formatted in accordance with applicable DoD policy. Use the following verbiage for operating systems that can accommodate banners of 1300 characters:\n\n\"You are accessing a U.S. Government (USG) Information System (IS) that is provided for USG-authorized use only.\n\nBy using this IS (which includes any device attached to this IS), you consent to the following conditions:\n\n-The USG routinely intercepts and monitors communications on this IS for purposes including, but not limited to, penetration testing, COMSEC monitoring, network operations and defense, personnel misconduct (PM), law enforcement (LE), and counterintelligence (CI) investigations.\n\n-At any time, the USG may inspect and seize data stored on this IS.\n\n-Communications using, or data stored on, this IS are not private, are subject to routine monitoring, interception, and search, and may be disclosed or used for any USG-authorized purpose.\n\n-This IS includes security measures (e.g., authentication and access controls) to protect USG interests--not for your personal benefit or privacy.\n\n-Notwithstanding the above, using this IS does not constitute consent to PM, LE or CI investigative searching or monitoring of the content of privileged communications, or work product, related to personal representation or services by attorneys, psychotherapists, or clergy, and their assistants. Such communications and work product are private and confidential. See User Agreement for details.\"\n\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000023-GPOS-00006, SRG-OS-000024-GPOS-00007, SRG-OS-000228-GPOS-00088","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-86483","V-71859"],"ccis":["CCI-000048"],"reference_identifier":"2899","uuid":"54302f77-989d-4ac4-9c4b-0f17e9a983e1","stig_uuid":"aa379772-3679-4074-8a4e-5b09f41d3e8e","status":"not_applicable","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_Dom0_RHEL7_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 1\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nThe automated check verified that GNOME desktop environment is not installed on this XCP-ng Dom0 (RHEL 7-based) system. XCP-ng Dom0 is a headless hypervisor host that operates exclusively via command line and remote management interfaces (SSH, XenCenter, Xen Orchestra). Without a graphical user interface installed, this STIG requirement does not apply. The check confirmed that the gnome-desktop3 RPM package is not present on the system. Finding: Not Applicable.\n        \n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_Dom0_RHEL7_Checks) found this to be NOT APPLICABLE on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: EFB134313657C49C4AD406D79721FE5BFD86A6B3\n~~~~~\nV-204393 - DoD Notice Banner via Graphical Logon\n============================================================\n\nCommand: rpm -q gnome-desktop3\nResult: package gnome-desktop3 is not installed\n\nNOT APPLICABLE: GNOME is not installed on XCP-ng Dom0.\nThis check applies only to systems with a graphical user interface.\n"},{"group_id_src":"V-204394","group_tree":[{"id":"V-204394","title":"SRG-OS-000023-GPOS-00006","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-204394","severity":"medium","group_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must display the approved Standard Mandatory DoD Notice and Consent Banner before granting local or remote access to the system via a graphical user logon.","rule_id_src":"SV-204394r958390_rule","rule_id":"SV-204394r958390","rule_version":"RHEL-07-010040","rule_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must display the approved Standard Mandatory DoD Notice and Consent Banner before granting local or remote access to the system via a graphical user logon.","fix_text":"Configure the operating system to display the approved Standard Mandatory DoD Notice and Consent Banner before granting access to the system.\r\n\r\nNote: If the system does not have a Graphical User Interface installed, this requirement is Not Applicable.\r\n\r\nCreate a database to contain the system-wide graphical user logon settings (if it does not already exist) with the following command:\r\n\r\n# touch /etc/dconf/db/local.d/01-banner-message\r\n\r\nAdd the following line to the [org/gnome/login-screen] section of the \"/etc/dconf/db/local.d/01-banner-message\":\r\n\r\n[org/gnome/login-screen]\r\n\r\nbanner-message-enable=true\r\n\r\nbanner-message-text='You are accessing a U.S. Government (USG) Information System (IS) that is provided for USG-authorized use only.\\nBy using this IS (which includes any device attached to this IS), you consent to the following conditions:\\n-The USG routinely intercepts and monitors communications on this IS for purposes including, but not limited to, penetration testing, COMSEC monitoring, network operations and defense, personnel misconduct (PM), law enforcement (LE), and counterintelligence (CI) investigations.\\n-At any time, the USG may inspect and seize data stored on this IS.\\n-Communications using, or data stored on, this IS are not private, are subject to routine monitoring, interception, and search, and may be disclosed or used for any USG-authorized purpose.\\n-This IS includes security measures (e.g., authentication and access controls) to protect USG interests--not for your personal benefit or privacy.\\n-Notwithstanding the above, using this IS does not constitute consent to PM, LE or CI investigative searching or monitoring of the content of privileged communications, or work product, related to personal representation or services by attorneys, psychotherapists, or clergy, and their assistants. Such communications and work product are private and confidential. See User Agreement for details. '\r\n\r\nNote: The \"\\n \" characters are for formatting only. They will not be displayed on the Graphical User Interface.\r\n\r\nRun the following command to update the database:\r\n# dconf update","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the operating system displays the approved Standard Mandatory DoD Notice and Consent Banner before granting access to the operating system via a graphical user logon.\r\n\r\nNote: If the system does not have a Graphical User Interface installed, this requirement is Not Applicable.\r\n\r\nCheck that the operating system displays the exact approved Standard Mandatory DoD Notice and Consent Banner text with the command:\r\n\r\n# grep banner-message-text /etc/dconf/db/local.d/*\r\nbanner-message-text=\r\n'You are accessing a U.S. Government (USG) Information System (IS) that is provided for USG-authorized use only.\\nBy using this IS (which includes any device attached to this IS), you consent to the following conditions:\\n-The USG routinely intercepts and monitors communications on this IS for purposes including, but not limited to, penetration testing, COMSEC monitoring, network operations and defense, personnel misconduct (PM), law enforcement (LE), and counterintelligence (CI) investigations.\\n-At any time, the USG may inspect and seize data stored on this IS.\\n-Communications using, or data stored on, this IS are not private, are subject to routine monitoring, interception, and search, and may be disclosed or used for any USG-authorized purpose.\\n-This IS includes security measures (e.g., authentication and access controls) to protect USG interests--not for your personal benefit or privacy.\\n-Notwithstanding the above, using this IS does not constitute consent to PM, LE or CI investigative searching or monitoring of the content of privileged communications, or work product, related to personal representation or services by attorneys, psychotherapists, or clergy, and their assistants. Such communications and work product are private and confidential. See User Agreement for details. '\r\n\r\nNote: The \"\\n \" characters are for formatting only. They will not be displayed on the Graphical User Interface.\r\n\r\nIf the banner does not match the approved Standard Mandatory DoD Notice and Consent Banner, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_7_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Display of a standardized and approved use notification before granting access to the operating system ensures privacy and security notification verbiage used is consistent with applicable federal laws, Executive Orders, directives, policies, regulations, standards, and guidance.\r\n\r\nSystem use notifications are required only for access via logon interfaces with human users and are not required when such human interfaces do not exist.\r\n\r\nThe banner must be formatted in accordance with applicable DoD policy.\r\n\r\n\"You are accessing a U.S. Government (USG) Information System (IS) that is provided for USG-authorized use only.\r\n\r\nBy using this IS (which includes any device attached to this IS), you consent to the following conditions:\r\n\r\n-The USG routinely intercepts and monitors communications on this IS for purposes including, but not limited to, penetration testing, COMSEC monitoring, network operations and defense, personnel misconduct (PM), law enforcement (LE), and counterintelligence (CI) investigations.\r\n\r\n-At any time, the USG may inspect and seize data stored on this IS.\r\n\r\n-Communications using, or data stored on, this IS are not private, are subject to routine monitoring, interception, and search, and may be disclosed or used for any USG-authorized purpose.\r\n\r\n-This IS includes security measures (e.g., authentication and access controls) to protect USG interests--not for your personal benefit or privacy.\r\n\r\n-Notwithstanding the above, using this IS does not constitute consent to PM, LE or CI investigative searching or monitoring of the content of privileged communications, or work product, related to personal representation or services by attorneys, psychotherapists, or clergy, and their assistants. Such communications and work product are private and confidential. See User Agreement for details.\"\r\n\r\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000023-GPOS-00006, SRG-OS-000024-GPOS-00007, SRG-OS-000228-GPOS-00088","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-86485","V-71861"],"ccis":["CCI-000048"],"reference_identifier":"2899","uuid":"31033db8-7c5f-43a3-804c-0e591ee95c9e","stig_uuid":"aa379772-3679-4074-8a4e-5b09f41d3e8e","status":"not_applicable","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_Dom0_RHEL7_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 1\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nThe automated check verified that GNOME desktop environment is not installed on this XCP-ng Dom0 (RHEL 7-based) system. XCP-ng Dom0 is a headless hypervisor host that operates exclusively via command line and remote management interfaces (SSH, XenCenter, Xen Orchestra). Without a graphical user interface installed, this STIG requirement does not apply. The check confirmed that the gnome-desktop3 RPM package is not present on the system. Finding: Not Applicable.\n        \n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_Dom0_RHEL7_Checks) found this to be NOT APPLICABLE on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: D4B229F2E705E8BAE46EF84F29EEDC766AF4CDC1\n~~~~~\nV-204394 - Approved DoD Banner Text via Graphical Logon\n============================================================\n\nCommand: rpm -q gnome-desktop3\nResult: package gnome-desktop3 is not installed\n\nNOT APPLICABLE: GNOME is not installed on XCP-ng Dom0.\nThis check applies only to systems with a graphical user interface.\n"},{"group_id_src":"V-204395","group_tree":[{"id":"V-204395","title":"SRG-OS-000023-GPOS-00006","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-204395","severity":"medium","group_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must display the Standard Mandatory DoD Notice and Consent Banner before granting local or remote access to the system via a command line user logon.","rule_id_src":"SV-204395r958390_rule","rule_id":"SV-204395r958390","rule_version":"RHEL-07-010050","rule_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must display the Standard Mandatory DoD Notice and Consent Banner before granting local or remote access to the system via a command line user logon.","fix_text":"Configure the operating system to display the Standard Mandatory DoD Notice and Consent Banner before granting access to the system via the command line by editing the \"/etc/issue\" file.\n\nReplace the default text with the Standard Mandatory DoD Notice and Consent Banner. The DoD required text is:\n\"You are accessing a U.S. Government (USG) Information System (IS) that is provided for USG-authorized use only.\n\nBy using this IS (which includes any device attached to this IS), you consent to the following conditions:\n\n-The USG routinely intercepts and monitors communications on this IS for purposes including, but not limited to, penetration testing, COMSEC monitoring, network operations and defense, personnel misconduct (PM), law enforcement (LE), and counterintelligence (CI) investigations.\n\n-At any time, the USG may inspect and seize data stored on this IS.\n\n-Communications using, or data stored on, this IS are not private, are subject to routine monitoring, interception, and search, and may be disclosed or used for any USG-authorized purpose.\n\n-This IS includes security measures (e.g., authentication and access controls) to protect USG interests--not for your personal benefit or privacy.\n\n-Notwithstanding the above, using this IS does not constitute consent to PM, LE or CI investigative searching or monitoring of the content of privileged communications, or work product, related to personal representation or services by attorneys, psychotherapists, or clergy, and their assistants.  Such communications and work product are private and confidential.  See User Agreement for details.\"","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the operating system displays the Standard Mandatory DoD Notice and Consent Banner before granting access to the operating system via a command line user logon.\n\nCheck to see if the operating system displays a banner at the command line logon screen with the following command:\n\n# more /etc/issue\n\nThe command should return the following text:\n\"You are accessing a U.S. Government (USG) Information System (IS) that is provided for USG-authorized use only.\n\nBy using this IS (which includes any device attached to this IS), you consent to the following conditions:\n\n-The USG routinely intercepts and monitors communications on this IS for purposes including, but not limited to, penetration testing, COMSEC monitoring, network operations and defense, personnel misconduct (PM), law enforcement (LE), and counterintelligence (CI) investigations.\n\n-At any time, the USG may inspect and seize data stored on this IS.\n\n-Communications using, or data stored on, this IS are not private, are subject to routine monitoring, interception, and search, and may be disclosed or used for any USG-authorized purpose.\n\n-This IS includes security measures (e.g., authentication and access controls) to protect USG interests--not for your personal benefit or privacy.\n\n-Notwithstanding the above, using this IS does not constitute consent to PM, LE or CI investigative searching or monitoring of the content of privileged communications, or work product, related to personal representation or services by attorneys, psychotherapists, or clergy, and their assistants. Such communications and work product are private and confidential. See User Agreement for details.\"\n\nIf the operating system does not display a graphical logon banner or the banner does not match the Standard Mandatory DoD Notice and Consent Banner, this is a finding.\n\nIf the text in the \"/etc/issue\" file does not match the Standard Mandatory DoD Notice and Consent Banner, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_7_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Display of a standardized and approved use notification before granting access to the operating system ensures privacy and security notification verbiage used is consistent with applicable federal laws, Executive Orders, directives, policies, regulations, standards, and guidance.\n\nSystem use notifications are required only for access via logon interfaces with human users and are not required when such human interfaces do not exist.\n\nThe banner must be formatted in accordance with applicable DoD policy. Use the following verbiage for operating systems that can accommodate banners of 1300 characters:\n\n\"You are accessing a U.S. Government (USG) Information System (IS) that is provided for USG-authorized use only.\n\nBy using this IS (which includes any device attached to this IS), you consent to the following conditions:\n\n-The USG routinely intercepts and monitors communications on this IS for purposes including, but not limited to, penetration testing, COMSEC monitoring, network operations and defense, personnel misconduct (PM), law enforcement (LE), and counterintelligence (CI) investigations.\n\n-At any time, the USG may inspect and seize data stored on this IS.\n\n-Communications using, or data stored on, this IS are not private, are subject to routine monitoring, interception, and search, and may be disclosed or used for any USG-authorized purpose.\n\n-This IS includes security measures (e.g., authentication and access controls) to protect USG interests--not for your personal benefit or privacy.\n\n-Notwithstanding the above, using this IS does not constitute consent to PM, LE or CI investigative searching or monitoring of the content of privileged communications, or work product, related to personal representation or services by attorneys, psychotherapists, or clergy, and their assistants. Such communications and work product are private and confidential. See User Agreement for details.\"\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000023-GPOS-00006, SRG-OS-000024-GPOS-00007","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-86487","V-71863"],"ccis":["CCI-000048"],"reference_identifier":"2899","uuid":"69ee4d49-3d03-4a98-977b-bf943ac73e91","stig_uuid":"aa379772-3679-4074-8a4e-5b09f41d3e8e","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_Dom0_RHEL7_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 2\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nThe automated check found that /etc/issue on this XCP-ng Dom0 (RHEL 7-based) system does not contain the required Standard Mandatory DoD Notice and Consent Banner or is missing key required phrases. Per RHEL 7 STIG requirement RHEL-07-010050, the operating system must display the DoD banner before granting command line access. Remediation: Update /etc/issue with the full Standard Mandatory DoD Notice and Consent Banner text as specified in the STIG check guidance. The banner must include all required elements: USG authorization notice, consent conditions, monitoring disclosure, data seizure rights, privacy limitations, and privileged communications exception. Finding: Open.\n        \n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_Dom0_RHEL7_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: F100FAD1CF9CF16AAE0071AF3AE113688CB9E530\n~~~~~\nV-204395 - DoD Notice Banner via Command Line Logon\n============================================================\n\nCommand: cat /etc/issue\nResult:\nXCP-ng 8.3\n\nSystem Booted: 2026-03-02 15:48\n\nYour XCP-ng host has now finished booting. \nTo manage this server please use Xen Orchestra.\nYou can install Xen Orchestra from https://xen-orchestra.com.\n\nYou can connect to this system using one of the following network\naddresses:\n\n10.0.10.23\n\nXCP-ng host TLS certificate SHA1 fingerprint:\nAE:F2:AE:B8:C7:DA:F2:47:F3:92:B4:14:AD:EE:FD:63:35:E9:B9:A8\n\nXCP-ng host TLS certificate SHA256 fingerprint:\n66:AA:26:BB:27:63:8C:D6:2A:D3:45:B5:67:B0:81:A5:55:0A:48:A4:08:F5:9F:A5:73:81:7B:E3:C5:F7:04:34\n\nBanner Key Phrases Found: 0 of 5\n\nFAIL: The /etc/issue file does not contain the required DoD banner.\nRemediation: Update /etc/issue with the Standard Mandatory DoD Notice and Consent Banner.\n"},{"group_id_src":"V-204396","group_tree":[{"id":"V-204396","title":"SRG-OS-000028-GPOS-00009","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-204396","severity":"medium","group_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must enable a user session lock until that user re-establishes access using established identification and authentication procedures.","rule_id_src":"SV-204396r958400_rule","rule_id":"SV-204396r958400","rule_version":"RHEL-07-010060","rule_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must enable a user session lock until that user re-establishes access using established identification and authentication procedures.","fix_text":"Configure the operating system to enable a user's session lock until that user re-establishes access using established identification and authentication procedures.\n\nCreate a database to contain the system-wide screensaver settings (if it does not already exist) with the following example:\n\n     # touch /etc/dconf/db/local.d/00-screensaver\n\nEdit the \"[org/gnome/desktop/screensaver]\" section of the database file and add or update the following lines:\n\n     # Set this to true to lock the screen when the screensaver activates\n     lock-enabled=true\n\nUpdate the system databases:\n\n     # dconf update\n\nUsers must log out and back in again before the system-wide settings take effect.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the operating system enables a user's session lock until that user re-establishes access using established identification and authentication procedures.\n\nNote: If the system does not have GNOME installed, this requirement is Not Applicable.\n\nCheck to see if the screen lock is enabled with the following command:\n\n     # grep -ir lock-enabled /etc/dconf/db/local.d/ | grep -v locks\n     lock-enabled=true\n\nIf the \"lock-enabled\" setting is missing or is not set to \"true\", this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_7_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"A session lock is a temporary action taken when a user stops work and moves away from the immediate physical vicinity of the information system but does not want to log out because of the temporary nature of the absence.\n\nThe session lock is implemented at the point where session activity can be determined.\n\nRegardless of where the session lock is determined and implemented, once invoked, the session lock must remain in place until the user reauthenticates. No other activity aside from reauthentication must unlock the system.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000028-GPOS-00009, SRG-OS-000030-GPOS-00011","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-86515","V-71891"],"ccis":["CCI-000056"],"reference_identifier":"2899","uuid":"bc26e6b0-35e4-4fa6-98fc-b43037c86743","stig_uuid":"aa379772-3679-4074-8a4e-5b09f41d3e8e","status":"not_applicable","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_Dom0_RHEL7_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 1\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nThe automated check verified that GNOME desktop environment is not installed on this XCP-ng Dom0 (RHEL 7-based) system. XCP-ng Dom0 is a headless hypervisor host that operates exclusively via command line and remote management interfaces (SSH, XenCenter, Xen Orchestra). Without a graphical user interface installed, this STIG requirement does not apply. The check confirmed that the gnome-desktop3 RPM package is not present on the system. Finding: Not Applicable.\n        \n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_Dom0_RHEL7_Checks) found this to be NOT APPLICABLE on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: 4FB7F43105CF2E88AF512C846F79B56FE6880FA0\n~~~~~\nV-204396 - Session Lock Until Re-authentication (GNOME)\n============================================================\n\nCommand: rpm -q gnome-desktop3\nResult: package gnome-desktop3 is not installed\n\nNOT APPLICABLE: GNOME is not installed on XCP-ng Dom0.\nThis check applies only to systems with a graphical user interface.\n"},{"group_id_src":"V-204397","group_tree":[{"id":"V-204397","title":"SRG-OS-000375-GPOS-00160","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-204397","severity":"medium","group_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must uniquely identify and must authenticate users using multifactor authentication via a graphical user logon.","rule_id_src":"SV-204397r982216_rule","rule_id":"SV-204397r982216","rule_version":"RHEL-07-010061","rule_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must uniquely identify and must authenticate users using multifactor authentication via a graphical user logon.","fix_text":"Configure the operating system to uniquely identify and authenticate users using multifactor authentication via a graphical user logon.\n\nNote: If the system does not have GNOME installed, this requirement is Not Applicable.\n\nCreate a database to contain the system-wide screensaver settings (if it does not already exist) with the following command: \n\nNote: The example is using the database local for the system, so if the system is using another database in \"/etc/dconf/profile/user\", the file should be created under the appropriate subdirectory.\n\n# touch /etc/dconf/db/local.d/00-defaults\n\nEdit \"[org/gnome/login-screen]\" and add or update the following line:\nenable-smartcard-authentication=true   \n\nUpdate the system databases:\n# dconf update","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the operating system uniquely identifies and authenticates users using multifactor authentication via a graphical user logon.\n\nNote: If the system does not have GNOME installed, this requirement is Not Applicable. \n\nDetermine which profile the system database is using with the following command:\n\n# grep system-db /etc/dconf/profile/user\n\nsystem-db:local\n\nNote: The example is using the database local for the system, so the path is \"/etc/dconf/db/local.d\". This path must be modified if a database other than local is being used.\n\n# grep enable-smartcard-authentication /etc/dconf/db/local.d/*\n\nenable-smartcard-authentication=true\n\nIf \"enable-smartcard-authentication\" is set to \"false\" or the keyword is missing, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_7_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"To assure accountability and prevent unauthenticated access, users must be identified and authenticated to prevent potential misuse and compromise of the system.\n\nMultifactor solutions that require devices separate from information systems gaining access include, for example, hardware tokens providing time-based or challenge-response authenticators and smart cards such as the U.S. Government Personal Identity Verification card and the DoD Common Access Card.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000375-GPOS-00161,SRG-OS-000375-GPOS-00162","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-92515","V-77819"],"ccis":["CCI-001948","CCI-001953","CCI-001954"],"reference_identifier":"2899","uuid":"b516bd91-fd17-4e4e-ab79-dd502e72f877","stig_uuid":"aa379772-3679-4074-8a4e-5b09f41d3e8e","status":"not_applicable","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_Dom0_RHEL7_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 1\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nThe automated check verified that GNOME desktop environment is not installed on this XCP-ng Dom0 (RHEL 7-based) system. XCP-ng Dom0 is a headless hypervisor host that operates exclusively via command line and remote management interfaces (SSH, XenCenter, Xen Orchestra). Without a graphical user interface installed, this STIG requirement does not apply. The check confirmed that the gnome-desktop3 RPM package is not present on the system. Finding: Not Applicable.\n        \n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_Dom0_RHEL7_Checks) found this to be NOT APPLICABLE on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: 29B613BAA664C28EBB39B6C1E80CC0961D84CA5B\n~~~~~\nV-204397 - MFA via Graphical User Logon (GNOME)\n============================================================\n\nCommand: rpm -q gnome-desktop3\nResult: package gnome-desktop3 is not installed\n\nNOT APPLICABLE: GNOME is not installed on XCP-ng Dom0.\nThis check applies only to systems with a graphical user interface.\n"},{"group_id_src":"V-204398","group_tree":[{"id":"V-204398","title":"SRG-OS-000029-GPOS-00010","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-204398","severity":"medium","group_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must initiate a screensaver after a 15-minute period of inactivity for graphical user interfaces.","rule_id_src":"SV-204398r958402_rule","rule_id":"SV-204398r958402","rule_version":"RHEL-07-010070","rule_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must initiate a screensaver after a 15-minute period of inactivity for graphical user interfaces.","fix_text":"Configure the operating system to initiate a screensaver after a 15-minute period of inactivity for graphical user interfaces.\n\nCreate a database to contain the system-wide screensaver settings (if it does not already exist) with the following command:\n\n     # touch /etc/dconf/db/local.d/00-screensaver\n\nEdit /etc/dconf/db/local.d/00-screensaver and add or update the following lines:\n\n     [org/gnome/desktop/session]\n     # Set the lock time out to 900 seconds before the session is considered idle\n     idle-delay=uint32 900\n\nYou must include the \"uint32\" along with the integer key values as shown.\n\nUpdate the system databases:\n\n     # dconf update\n\nUsers must log out and back in again before the system-wide settings take effect.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the operating system initiates a screensaver after a 15-minute period of inactivity for graphical user interfaces.\n\nNote: If the system does not have GNOME installed, this requirement is Not Applicable.\n\nCheck to see if GNOME is configured to display a screensaver after a 15 minute delay with the following command:\n\n     # grep -i idle-delay /etc/dconf/db/local.d/*\n     idle-delay=uint32 900\n\nIf the \"idle-delay\" setting is missing or is not set to \"900\" or less, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_7_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"A session time-out lock is a temporary action taken when a user stops work and moves away from the immediate physical vicinity of the information system but does not log out because of the temporary nature of the absence. Rather than relying on the user to manually lock their operating system session prior to vacating the vicinity, operating systems need to be able to identify when a user's session has idled and take action to initiate the session lock.\n\nThe session lock is implemented at the point where session activity can be determined and/or controlled.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-86517","V-71893"],"ccis":["CCI-000057"],"reference_identifier":"2899","uuid":"bf555f74-8124-4d75-958a-f05e292b4cf7","stig_uuid":"aa379772-3679-4074-8a4e-5b09f41d3e8e","status":"not_applicable","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_Dom0_RHEL7_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 1\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nThe automated check verified that GNOME desktop environment is not installed on this XCP-ng Dom0 (RHEL 7-based) system. XCP-ng Dom0 is a headless hypervisor host that operates exclusively via command line and remote management interfaces (SSH, XenCenter, Xen Orchestra). Without a graphical user interface installed, this STIG requirement does not apply. The check confirmed that the gnome-desktop3 RPM package is not present on the system. Finding: Not Applicable.\n        \n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_Dom0_RHEL7_Checks) found this to be NOT APPLICABLE on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: 7A4123BB51D5AD5998ECF29F5E223B50DDE9BF61\n~~~~~\nV-204398 - Screensaver After 15-min Inactivity (GNOME)\n============================================================\n\nCommand: rpm -q gnome-desktop3\nResult: package gnome-desktop3 is not installed\n\nNOT APPLICABLE: GNOME is not installed on XCP-ng Dom0.\nThis check applies only to systems with a graphical user interface.\n"},{"group_id_src":"V-204399","group_tree":[{"id":"V-204399","title":"SRG-OS-000029-GPOS-00010","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-204399","severity":"medium","group_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must prevent a user from overriding the screensaver lock-delay setting for the graphical user interface.","rule_id_src":"SV-204399r958402_rule","rule_id":"SV-204399r958402","rule_version":"RHEL-07-010081","rule_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must prevent a user from overriding the screensaver lock-delay setting for the graphical user interface.","fix_text":"Configure the operating system to prevent a user from overriding a screensaver lock after a 15-minute period of inactivity for graphical user interfaces.\n\nCreate a database to contain the system-wide screensaver settings (if it does not already exist) with the following command: \n\nNote: The example below is using the database \"local\" for the system, so if the system is using another database in \"/etc/dconf/profile/user\", the file should be created under the appropriate subdirectory.\n\n     # touch /etc/dconf/db/local.d/locks/session\n\nAdd the setting to lock the screensaver lock delay:\n\n     /org/gnome/desktop/screensaver/lock-delay","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the operating system prevents a user from overriding a screensaver lock after a 15-minute period of inactivity for graphical user interfaces. \n\nNote: If the system does not have GNOME installed, this requirement is Not Applicable.\n\nDetermine which profile the system database is using with the following command:\n     # grep system-db /etc/dconf/profile/user\n     system-db:local\n\nCheck for the lock delay setting with the following command:\n\nNote: The example below is using the database \"local\" for the system, so the path is \"/etc/dconf/db/local.d\". This path must be modified if a database other than \"local\" is being used.\n\n     # grep -i lock-delay /etc/dconf/db/local.d/locks/*\n     /org/gnome/desktop/screensaver/lock-delay\n\nIf the command does not return a result, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_7_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"A session time-out lock is a temporary action taken when a user stops work and moves away from the immediate physical vicinity of the information system but does not log out because of the temporary nature of the absence. Rather than relying on the user to manually lock their operating system session prior to vacating the vicinity, operating systems need to be able to identify when a user's session has idled and take action to initiate the session lock.\n\nThe session lock is implemented at the point where session activity can be determined and/or controlled.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-87807","V-73155"],"ccis":["CCI-000057"],"reference_identifier":"2899","uuid":"1e319bfc-74e2-4bc2-9a22-81b5a29736bb","stig_uuid":"aa379772-3679-4074-8a4e-5b09f41d3e8e","status":"not_applicable","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_Dom0_RHEL7_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 1\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nThe automated check verified that GNOME desktop environment is not installed on this XCP-ng Dom0 (RHEL 7-based) system. XCP-ng Dom0 is a headless hypervisor host that operates exclusively via command line and remote management interfaces (SSH, XenCenter, Xen Orchestra). Without a graphical user interface installed, this STIG requirement does not apply. The check confirmed that the gnome-desktop3 RPM package is not present on the system. Finding: Not Applicable.\n        \n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_Dom0_RHEL7_Checks) found this to be NOT APPLICABLE on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: 4E271D462F8B2F2DD181D7D561CED6933CD73F4E\n~~~~~\nV-204399 - Prevent Override of Screensaver Lock (GNOME)\n============================================================\n\nCommand: rpm -q gnome-desktop3\nResult: package gnome-desktop3 is not installed\n\nNOT APPLICABLE: GNOME is not installed on XCP-ng Dom0.\nThis check applies only to systems with a graphical user interface.\n"},{"group_id_src":"V-204400","group_tree":[{"id":"V-204400","title":"SRG-OS-000029-GPOS-00010","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-204400","severity":"medium","group_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must prevent a user from overriding the session idle-delay setting for the graphical user interface.","rule_id_src":"SV-204400r958402_rule","rule_id":"SV-204400r958402","rule_version":"RHEL-07-010082","rule_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must prevent a user from overriding the session idle-delay setting for the graphical user interface.","fix_text":"Configure the operating system to prevent a user from overriding a session lock after a 15-minute period of inactivity for graphical user interfaces.\n\nCreate a database to contain the system-wide screensaver settings (if it does not already exist) with the following command: \n\nNote: The example below is using the database \"local\" for the system, so if the system is using another database in /etc/dconf/profile/user, the file should be created under the appropriate subdirectory.\n\n     # touch /etc/dconf/db/local.d/locks/session\n\nAdd the setting to lock the session idle delay:\n\n     /org/gnome/desktop/session/idle-delay","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the operating system prevents a user from overriding session idle delay after a 15-minute period of inactivity for graphical user interfaces. \n\nNote: If the system does not have GNOME installed, this requirement is Not Applicable.\n\nDetermine which profile the system database is using with the following command:\n     # grep system-db /etc/dconf/profile/user\n     system-db:local\n\nCheck for the session idle delay setting with the following command:\n\nNote: The example below is using the database \"local\" for the system, so the path is \"/etc/dconf/db/local.d\". This path must be modified if a database other than \"local\" is being used.\n\n     # grep -i idle-delay /etc/dconf/db/local.d/locks/*\n     /org/gnome/desktop/session/idle-delay\n\nIf the command does not return a result, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_7_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"A session time-out lock is a temporary action taken when a user stops work and moves away from the immediate physical vicinity of the information system but does not log out because of the temporary nature of the absence. Rather than relying on the user to manually lock their operating system session prior to vacating the vicinity, operating systems need to be able to identify when a user's session has idled and take action to initiate the session lock.\n\nThe session lock is implemented at the point where session activity can be determined and/or controlled.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-87809","V-73157"],"ccis":["CCI-000057"],"reference_identifier":"2899","uuid":"2f531c48-6b3c-405f-bf56-01fd5da5091e","stig_uuid":"aa379772-3679-4074-8a4e-5b09f41d3e8e","status":"not_applicable","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_Dom0_RHEL7_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 1\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nThe automated check verified that GNOME desktop environment is not installed on this XCP-ng Dom0 (RHEL 7-based) system. XCP-ng Dom0 is a headless hypervisor host that operates exclusively via command line and remote management interfaces (SSH, XenCenter, Xen Orchestra). Without a graphical user interface installed, this STIG requirement does not apply. The check confirmed that the gnome-desktop3 RPM package is not present on the system. Finding: Not Applicable.\n        \n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_Dom0_RHEL7_Checks) found this to be NOT APPLICABLE on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: 8F389429816401909CF75C850E05FEC7DBDC6029\n~~~~~\nV-204400 - Prevent Override of Session Idle-Delay (GNOME)\n============================================================\n\nCommand: rpm -q gnome-desktop3\nResult: package gnome-desktop3 is not installed\n\nNOT APPLICABLE: GNOME is not installed on XCP-ng Dom0.\nThis check applies only to systems with a graphical user interface.\n"},{"group_id_src":"V-204402","group_tree":[{"id":"V-204402","title":"SRG-OS-000029-GPOS-00010","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-204402","severity":"medium","group_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must initiate a session lock for the screensaver after a period of inactivity for graphical user interfaces.","rule_id_src":"SV-204402r958402_rule","rule_id":"SV-204402r958402","rule_version":"RHEL-07-010100","rule_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must initiate a session lock for the screensaver after a period of inactivity for graphical user interfaces.","fix_text":"Configure the operating system to initiate a session lock after a 15-minute period of inactivity for graphical user interfaces.\n\nCreate a database to contain the system-wide screensaver settings (if it does not already exist) with the following command: \n\n     # touch /etc/dconf/db/local.d/00-screensaver\n\nAdd the setting to enable screensaver locking after 15 minutes of inactivity:\n\n     [org/gnome/desktop/screensaver]\n\n     idle-activation-enabled=true\n\nUpdate the system databases:\n\n     # dconf update\n\nUsers must log out and back in again before the system-wide settings take effect.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the operating system initiates a session lock after a 15-minute period of inactivity for graphical user interfaces.\n\nNote: If the system does not have a GNOME installed, this requirement is Not Applicable.\n\nCheck for the session lock settings with the following commands:\n\n     # grep -i idle-activation-enabled /etc/dconf/db/local.d/*\n     idle-activation-enabled=true\n\nIf \"idle-activation-enabled\" is not set to \"true\", this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_7_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"A session time-out lock is a temporary action taken when a user stops work and moves away from the immediate physical vicinity of the information system but does not log out because of the temporary nature of the absence. Rather than relying on the user to manually lock their operating system session prior to vacating the vicinity, operating systems need to be able to identify when a user's session has idled and take action to initiate the session lock.\n\nThe session lock is implemented at the point where session activity can be determined and/or controlled.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-86523","V-71899"],"ccis":["CCI-000057"],"reference_identifier":"2899","uuid":"f5c038d2-28d0-4bf5-83bf-fa3b9101d8b0","stig_uuid":"aa379772-3679-4074-8a4e-5b09f41d3e8e","status":"not_applicable","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_Dom0_RHEL7_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 1\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nThe automated check verified that GNOME desktop environment is not installed on this XCP-ng Dom0 (RHEL 7-based) system. XCP-ng Dom0 is a headless hypervisor host that operates exclusively via command line and remote management interfaces (SSH, XenCenter, Xen Orchestra). Without a graphical user interface installed, this STIG requirement does not apply. The check confirmed that the gnome-desktop3 RPM package is not present on the system. Finding: Not Applicable.\n        \n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_Dom0_RHEL7_Checks) found this to be NOT APPLICABLE on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: FB0B1072A33DCA31B2CA8CA683BA3112F36AD43F\n~~~~~\nV-204402 - Session Lock via idle-activation-enabled (GNOME)\n============================================================\n\nCommand: rpm -q gnome-desktop3\nResult: package gnome-desktop3 is not installed\n\nNOT APPLICABLE: GNOME is not installed on XCP-ng Dom0.\nThis check applies only to systems with a graphical user interface.\n"},{"group_id_src":"V-204403","group_tree":[{"id":"V-204403","title":"SRG-OS-000029-GPOS-00010","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-204403","severity":"medium","group_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must prevent a user from overriding the screensaver idle-activation-enabled setting for the graphical user interface.","rule_id_src":"SV-204403r958402_rule","rule_id":"SV-204403r958402","rule_version":"RHEL-07-010101","rule_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must prevent a user from overriding the screensaver idle-activation-enabled setting for the graphical user interface.","fix_text":"Configure the operating system to prevent a user from overriding a screensaver lock after a 15-minute period of inactivity for graphical user interfaces.\n\nCreate a database to contain the system-wide screensaver settings (if it does not already exist) with the following command: \n\nNote: The example below is using the database \"local\" for the system, so if the system is using another database in \"/etc/dconf/profile/user\", the file should be created under the appropriate subdirectory.\n\n     # touch /etc/dconf/db/local.d/locks/session\n\nAdd the setting to lock the screensaver idle-activation-enabled setting:\n\n     /org/gnome/desktop/screensaver/idle-activation-enabled","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the operating system prevents a user from overriding the screensaver idle-activation-enabled setting for the graphical user interface. \n\nNote: If the system does not have GNOME installed, this requirement is Not Applicable.\n\nDetermine which profile the system database is using with the following command:\n     # grep system-db /etc/dconf/profile/user\n\n     system-db:local\n\nCheck for the idle-activation-enabled setting with the following command:\n\nNote: The example below is using the database \"local\" for the system, so the path is \"/etc/dconf/db/local.d\". This path must be modified if a database other than \"local\" is being used.\n\n     # grep -i idle-activation-enabled /etc/dconf/db/local.d/locks/*\n\n     /org/gnome/desktop/screensaver/idle-activation-enabled\n\nIf the command does not return a result, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_7_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"A session lock is a temporary action taken when a user stops work and moves away from the immediate physical vicinity of the information system but does not want to log out because of the temporary nature of the absence.\n\nThe session lock is implemented at the point where session activity can be determined.\n\nThe ability to enable/disable a session lock is given to the user by default. Disabling the user's ability to disengage the graphical user interface session lock provides the assurance that all sessions will lock after the specified period of time.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-93703","V-78997"],"ccis":["CCI-000057"],"reference_identifier":"2899","uuid":"92263138-b2eb-408b-85c1-4ad9626ef9c1","stig_uuid":"aa379772-3679-4074-8a4e-5b09f41d3e8e","status":"not_applicable","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_Dom0_RHEL7_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 1\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nThe automated check verified that GNOME desktop environment is not installed on this XCP-ng Dom0 (RHEL 7-based) system. XCP-ng Dom0 is a headless hypervisor host that operates exclusively via command line and remote management interfaces (SSH, XenCenter, Xen Orchestra). Without a graphical user interface installed, this STIG requirement does not apply. The check confirmed that the gnome-desktop3 RPM package is not present on the system. Finding: Not Applicable.\n        \n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_Dom0_RHEL7_Checks) found this to be NOT APPLICABLE on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: 026FA80870707D7E9CC512FAA349452FCF4AE2CC\n~~~~~\nV-204403 - Prevent Override of idle-activation-enabled (GNOME)\n============================================================\n\nCommand: rpm -q gnome-desktop3\nResult: package gnome-desktop3 is not installed\n\nNOT APPLICABLE: GNOME is not installed on XCP-ng Dom0.\nThis check applies only to systems with a graphical user interface.\n"},{"group_id_src":"V-204404","group_tree":[{"id":"V-204404","title":"SRG-OS-000029-GPOS-00010","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-204404","severity":"medium","group_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must initiate a session lock for graphical user interfaces when the screensaver is activated.","rule_id_src":"SV-204404r958402_rule","rule_id":"SV-204404r958402","rule_version":"RHEL-07-010110","rule_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must initiate a session lock for graphical user interfaces when the screensaver is activated.","fix_text":"Configure the operating system to initiate a session lock for graphical user interfaces when a screensaver is activated.\n\nCreate a database to contain the system-wide screensaver settings (if it does not already exist) with the following command: \n\n     # touch /etc/dconf/db/local.d/00-screensaver\n\nAdd the setting to enable session locking when a screensaver is activated:\n\n     [org/gnome/desktop/screensaver]\n     lock-delay=uint32 5\n\nThe \"uint32\" must be included along with the integer key values as shown.\n\nUpdate the system databases:\n\n     # dconf update\n\nUsers must log out and back in again before the system-wide settings take effect.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the operating system initiates a session lock a for graphical user interfaces when the screensaver is activated. \n\nNote: If the system does not have GNOME installed, this requirement is Not Applicable.\n\nIf GNOME is installed, check to see a session lock occurs when the screensaver is activated with the following command:\n\n     # grep -i lock-delay /etc/dconf/db/local.d/*\n     lock-delay=uint32 5\n\nIf the \"lock-delay\" setting is missing, or is not set to \"5\" or less, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_7_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"A session time-out lock is a temporary action taken when a user stops work and moves away from the immediate physical vicinity of the information system but does not log out because of the temporary nature of the absence. Rather than relying on the user to manually lock their operating system session prior to vacating the vicinity, operating systems need to be able to identify when a user's session has idled and take action to initiate the session lock.\n\nThe session lock is implemented at the point where session activity can be determined and/or controlled.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-86525","V-71901"],"ccis":["CCI-000057"],"reference_identifier":"2899","uuid":"202073d0-c130-4b92-90f1-5d3206bed2d5","stig_uuid":"aa379772-3679-4074-8a4e-5b09f41d3e8e","status":"not_applicable","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_Dom0_RHEL7_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 1\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nThe automated check verified that GNOME desktop environment is not installed on this XCP-ng Dom0 (RHEL 7-based) system. XCP-ng Dom0 is a headless hypervisor host that operates exclusively via command line and remote management interfaces (SSH, XenCenter, Xen Orchestra). Without a graphical user interface installed, this STIG requirement does not apply. The check confirmed that the gnome-desktop3 RPM package is not present on the system. Finding: Not Applicable.\n        \n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_Dom0_RHEL7_Checks) found this to be NOT APPLICABLE on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: 09E8C1E3389AA164FCA89D335AE87445AF84A7A4\n~~~~~\nV-204404 - Session Lock When Screensaver Activated (GNOME)\n============================================================\n\nCommand: rpm -q gnome-desktop3\nResult: package gnome-desktop3 is not installed\n\nNOT APPLICABLE: GNOME is not installed on XCP-ng Dom0.\nThis check applies only to systems with a graphical user interface.\n"},{"group_id_src":"V-204405","group_tree":[{"id":"V-204405","title":"SRG-OS-000069-GPOS-00037","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-204405","severity":"medium","group_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must be configured so that /etc/pam.d/passwd implements /etc/pam.d/system-auth when changing passwords.","rule_id_src":"SV-204405r982195_rule","rule_id":"SV-204405r982195","rule_version":"RHEL-07-010118","rule_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must be configured so that /etc/pam.d/passwd implements /etc/pam.d/system-auth when changing passwords.","fix_text":"Configure PAM to utilize /etc/pam.d/system-auth when changing passwords.\n\nAdd the following line to \"/etc/pam.d/passwd\" (or modify the line to have the required value):\n\npassword     substack    system-auth","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that /etc/pam.d/passwd is configured to use /etc/pam.d/system-auth when changing passwords:\n\n# cat /etc/pam.d/passwd | grep -i substack | grep -i system-auth\npassword     substack     system-auth\n\nIf no results are returned, the line is commented out, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_7_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Pluggable authentication modules (PAM) allow for a modular approach to integrating authentication methods. PAM operates in a top-down processing model and if the modules are not listed in the correct order, an important security function could be bypassed if stack entries are not centralized.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-95715","V-81003"],"ccis":["CCI-000192"],"reference_identifier":"2899","uuid":"6ba408a9-6c08-4e1c-864a-6b759210f4bc","stig_uuid":"aa379772-3679-4074-8a4e-5b09f41d3e8e","status":"not_a_finding","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_Dom0_RHEL7_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 1\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nThe automated check verified that /etc/pam.d/passwd on this XCP-ng Dom0 (RHEL 7-based) system includes a substack reference to system-auth. This ensures that password changes go through the centralized PAM authentication stack defined in /etc/pam.d/system-auth, providing consistent password policy enforcement including complexity requirements (pam_pwquality), account lockout (pam_faillock), and password history (pam_pwhistory). Finding: Not a Finding.\n        \n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_Dom0_RHEL7_Checks) found this to be NOT A FINDING on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: 472FF3BFAC01CF41DE507CDE7646B3C6BC202A94\n~~~~~\nV-204405 - /etc/pam.d/passwd Must Use system-auth Substack\n============================================================\n\nCommand: cat /etc/pam.d/passwd\nResult:\n#%PAM-1.0\nauth       include\tsystem-auth\naccount    include\tsystem-auth\npassword   substack\tsystem-auth\n-password   optional\tpam_gnome_keyring.so use_authtok\npassword   substack\tpostlogin\n\nCommand: grep -i substack /etc/pam.d/passwd\nResult: password   substack\tsystem-auth\npassword   substack\tpostlogin\n\nPASS: /etc/pam.d/passwd uses system-auth substack for password changes.\n"},{"group_id_src":"V-204406","group_tree":[{"id":"V-204406","title":"SRG-OS-000069-GPOS-00037","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-204406","severity":"medium","group_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must be configured so that when passwords are changed or new passwords are established, pwquality must be used.","rule_id_src":"SV-204406r982195_rule","rule_id":"SV-204406r982195","rule_version":"RHEL-07-010119","rule_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must be configured so that when passwords are changed or new passwords are established, pwquality must be used.","fix_text":"Configure the operating system to use \"pwquality\" to enforce password complexity rules.\n\nAdd the following line to \"/etc/pam.d/system-auth\" (or modify the line to have the required value):\n\n     password requisite pam_pwquality.so retry=3\n\nNote: The value of \"retry\" should be between \"1\" and \"3\".","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the operating system uses \"pwquality\" to enforce the password complexity rules. \n\nCheck for the use of \"pwquality\" with the following command:\n\n     # cat /etc/pam.d/system-auth | grep pam_pwquality\n\n     password requisite pam_pwquality.so retry=3\n\nIf the command does not return an uncommented line containing the value \"pam_pwquality.so\" as shown, this is a finding.\n\nIf the value of \"retry\" is set to \"0\" or greater than \"3\", this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_7_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Use of a complex password helps to increase the time and resources required to compromise the password. Password complexity, or strength, is a measure of the effectiveness of a password in resisting attempts at guessing and brute-force attacks. \"pwquality\" enforces complex password construction configuration and has the ability to limit brute-force attacks on the system.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-87811","V-73159"],"ccis":["CCI-000192"],"reference_identifier":"2899","uuid":"bb514b08-9548-477d-8950-dadee8a95b60","stig_uuid":"aa379772-3679-4074-8a4e-5b09f41d3e8e","status":"not_a_finding","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_Dom0_RHEL7_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 1\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nThe automated check verified that /etc/pam.d/system-auth on this XCP-ng Dom0 (RHEL 7-based) system includes pam_pwquality.so with an appropriate retry value (between 1 and 3). This ensures password quality enforcement is active through the PAM stack, requiring new passwords to meet complexity standards before acceptance. The retry parameter limits the number of attempts a user has to provide an acceptable password. Finding: Not a Finding.\n        \n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_Dom0_RHEL7_Checks) found this to be NOT A FINDING on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: 6FCF2D682832F53E47AC47E56FF77C8F546F02A7\n~~~~~\nV-204406 - system-auth Must Use pam_pwquality.so\n============================================================\n\nCommand: grep pam_pwquality /etc/pam.d/system-auth\nResult: password    requisite     pam_pwquality.so try_first_pass local_users_only retry=3 authtok_type=\n\nRetry value: 3\n\nPASS: pam_pwquality.so is configured with retry=3.\n"},{"group_id_src":"V-204407","group_tree":[{"id":"V-204407","title":"SRG-OS-000069-GPOS-00037","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-204407","severity":"medium","group_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must be configured so that when passwords are changed or new passwords are established, the new password must contain at least one upper-case character.","rule_id_src":"SV-204407r982195_rule","rule_id":"SV-204407r982195","rule_version":"RHEL-07-010120","rule_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must be configured so that when passwords are changed or new passwords are established, the new password must contain at least one upper-case character.","fix_text":"Configure the operating system to enforce password complexity by requiring that at least one upper-case character be used by setting the \"ucredit\" option.\n\nAdd the following line to \"/etc/security/pwquality.conf\" (or modify the line to have the required value):\n\nucredit = -1","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Note: The value to require a number of upper-case characters to be set is expressed as a negative number in \"/etc/security/pwquality.conf\".\n\nCheck the value for \"ucredit\" in \"/etc/security/pwquality.conf\" with the following command:\n\n# grep ucredit /etc/security/pwquality.conf \nucredit = -1\n\nIf the value of \"ucredit\" is not set to a negative value, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_7_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Use of a complex password helps to increase the time and resources required to compromise the password. Password complexity, or strength, is a measure of the effectiveness of a password in resisting attempts at guessing and brute-force attacks.\n\nPassword complexity is one factor of several that determines how long it takes to crack a password. The more complex the password, the greater the number of possible combinations that need to be tested before the password is compromised.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-86527","V-71903"],"ccis":["CCI-000192"],"reference_identifier":"2899","uuid":"4337460f-578a-4d85-8a59-7ad4511e5de2","stig_uuid":"aa379772-3679-4074-8a4e-5b09f41d3e8e","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_Dom0_RHEL7_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 2\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nThe automated check found that ucredit is either not configured or not set to a negative value in /etc/security/pwquality.conf on this XCP-ng Dom0 (RHEL 7-based) system. Without this setting, password changes may not require upper-case characters, reducing password complexity and making passwords more susceptible to brute-force attacks. Remediation: Add or modify the following line in /etc/security/pwquality.conf: ucredit = -1. This requires at least one upper-case character in new passwords. Finding: Open.\n        \n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_Dom0_RHEL7_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: CF1DF0CC3723E4337335F7867EF63463DFBFD1DF\n~~~~~\nV-204407 - Password Must Require Upper-case Character (ucredit)\n============================================================\n\nCommand: grep ucredit /etc/security/pwquality.conf\nResult: # ucredit = 1\n\nFAIL: ucredit is not configured in /etc/security/pwquality.conf.\nRemediation: Add to /etc/security/pwquality.conf:\n  ucredit = -1\n"},{"group_id_src":"V-204408","group_tree":[{"id":"V-204408","title":"SRG-OS-000070-GPOS-00038","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-204408","severity":"medium","group_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must be configured so that when passwords are changed or new passwords are established, the new password must contain at least one lower-case character.","rule_id_src":"SV-204408r982196_rule","rule_id":"SV-204408r982196","rule_version":"RHEL-07-010130","rule_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must be configured so that when passwords are changed or new passwords are established, the new password must contain at least one lower-case character.","fix_text":"Configure the system to require at least one lower-case character when creating or changing a password.\n\nAdd or modify the following line \nin \"/etc/security/pwquality.conf\":\n\nlcredit = -1","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Note: The value to require a number of lower-case characters to be set is expressed as a negative number in \"/etc/security/pwquality.conf\".\n\nCheck the value for \"lcredit\" in \"/etc/security/pwquality.conf\" with the following command:\n\n# grep lcredit /etc/security/pwquality.conf \nlcredit = -1 \n\nIf the value of \"lcredit\" is not set to a negative value, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_7_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Use of a complex password helps to increase the time and resources required to compromise the password. Password complexity, or strength, is a measure of the effectiveness of a password in resisting attempts at guessing and brute-force attacks.\n\nPassword complexity is one factor of several that determines how long it takes to crack a password. The more complex the password, the greater the number of possible combinations that need to be tested before the password is compromised.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-86529","V-71905"],"ccis":["CCI-000193"],"reference_identifier":"2899","uuid":"76b6b0cf-1acd-4944-a43d-182ad433a453","stig_uuid":"aa379772-3679-4074-8a4e-5b09f41d3e8e","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_Dom0_RHEL7_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 2\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nThe automated check found that lcredit is either not configured or not set to a negative value in /etc/security/pwquality.conf on this XCP-ng Dom0 (RHEL 7-based) system. Without this setting, password changes may not require lower-case characters, reducing password complexity and making passwords more susceptible to brute-force attacks. Remediation: Add or modify the following line in /etc/security/pwquality.conf: lcredit = -1. This requires at least one lower-case character in new passwords. Finding: Open.\n        \n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_Dom0_RHEL7_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: 5778B3142DC9E0BA902CA1ED6BE556218BA8CFF9\n~~~~~\nV-204408 - Password Must Require Lower-case Character (lcredit)\n============================================================\n\nCommand: grep lcredit /etc/security/pwquality.conf\nResult: # lcredit = 1\n\nFAIL: lcredit is not configured in /etc/security/pwquality.conf.\nRemediation: Add to /etc/security/pwquality.conf:\n  lcredit = -1\n"},{"group_id_src":"V-204409","group_tree":[{"id":"V-204409","title":"SRG-OS-000071-GPOS-00039","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-204409","severity":"medium","group_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must be configured so that when passwords are changed or new passwords are assigned, the new password must contain at least one numeric character.","rule_id_src":"SV-204409r982197_rule","rule_id":"SV-204409r982197","rule_version":"RHEL-07-010140","rule_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must be configured so that when passwords are changed or new passwords are assigned, the new password must contain at least one numeric character.","fix_text":"Configure the operating system to enforce password complexity by requiring that at least one numeric character be used by setting the \"dcredit\" option.\n\nAdd the following line to /etc/security/pwquality.conf (or modify the line to have the required value):\n\ndcredit = -1","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Note: The value to require a number of numeric characters to be set is expressed as a negative number in \"/etc/security/pwquality.conf\".\n\nCheck the value for \"dcredit\" in \"/etc/security/pwquality.conf\" with the following command:\n\n# grep dcredit /etc/security/pwquality.conf \ndcredit = -1 \n\nIf the value of \"dcredit\" is not set to a negative value, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_7_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Use of a complex password helps to increase the time and resources required to compromise the password. Password complexity, or strength, is a measure of the effectiveness of a password in resisting attempts at guessing and brute-force attacks.\n\nPassword complexity is one factor of several that determines how long it takes to crack a password. The more complex the password, the greater the number of possible combinations that need to be tested before the password is compromised.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-86531","V-71907"],"ccis":["CCI-000194"],"reference_identifier":"2899","uuid":"8c5e5605-6a7c-4fda-99aa-4b2658bfcae8","stig_uuid":"aa379772-3679-4074-8a4e-5b09f41d3e8e","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_Dom0_RHEL7_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 2\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nThe automated check found that dcredit is not configured or not set to a negative value in /etc/security/pwquality.conf. Remediation: Set dcredit = -1 in /etc/security/pwquality.conf. Finding: Open.\n        \n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_Dom0_RHEL7_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: 3C40D5D676288F8E725D6BBD563A64D205CFFEB7\n~~~~~\nV-204409 - Password Must Require Numeric Character (dcredit)\n============================================================\n\nCommand: grep dcredit /etc/security/pwquality.conf\nResult: # dcredit = 1\n\nFAIL: dcredit is not configured in /etc/security/pwquality.conf.\nRemediation: Add to /etc/security/pwquality.conf:\n  dcredit = -1\n"},{"group_id_src":"V-204410","group_tree":[{"id":"V-204410","title":"SRG-OS-000266-GPOS-00101","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-204410","severity":"medium","group_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must be configured so that when passwords are changed or new passwords are established, the new password must contain at least one special character.","rule_id_src":"SV-204410r991561_rule","rule_id":"SV-204410r991561","rule_version":"RHEL-07-010150","rule_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must be configured so that when passwords are changed or new passwords are established, the new password must contain at least one special character.","fix_text":"Configure the operating system to enforce password complexity by requiring that at least one special character be used by setting the \"ocredit\" option.\n\nAdd the following line to \"/etc/security/pwquality.conf\" (or modify the line to have the required value):\n\nocredit = -1","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the operating system enforces password complexity by requiring that at least one special character be used.\n\nNote: The value to require a number of special characters to be set is expressed as a negative number in \"/etc/security/pwquality.conf\".\n\nCheck the value for \"ocredit\" in \"/etc/security/pwquality.conf\" with the following command:\n\n# grep ocredit /etc/security/pwquality.conf \nocredit=-1\n\nIf the value of \"ocredit\" is not set to a negative value, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_7_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Use of a complex password helps to increase the time and resources required to compromise the password. Password complexity, or strength, is a measure of the effectiveness of a password in resisting attempts at guessing and brute-force attacks.\n\nPassword complexity is one factor of several that determines how long it takes to crack a password. The more complex the password, the greater the number of possible combinations that need to be tested before the password is compromised.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-86533","V-71909"],"ccis":["CCI-001619"],"reference_identifier":"2899","uuid":"c2e814c1-b2b3-411a-8d2f-29a1a308bae6","stig_uuid":"aa379772-3679-4074-8a4e-5b09f41d3e8e","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_Dom0_RHEL7_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 2\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nThe automated check found that ocredit is not configured or not set to a negative value in /etc/security/pwquality.conf. Remediation: Set ocredit = -1 in /etc/security/pwquality.conf. Finding: Open.\n        \n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_Dom0_RHEL7_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: 98D525333E2C5BA1961C359B7FF3E49557C19C7C\n~~~~~\nV-204410 - Password Must Require Special Character (ocredit)\n============================================================\n\nCommand: grep ocredit /etc/security/pwquality.conf\nResult: # ocredit = 1\n\nFAIL: ocredit is not configured in /etc/security/pwquality.conf.\nRemediation: Add to /etc/security/pwquality.conf:\n  ocredit = -1\n"},{"group_id_src":"V-204411","group_tree":[{"id":"V-204411","title":"SRG-OS-000072-GPOS-00040","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-204411","severity":"medium","group_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must be configured so that when passwords are changed a minimum of eight of the total number of characters must be changed.","rule_id_src":"SV-204411r982198_rule","rule_id":"SV-204411r982198","rule_version":"RHEL-07-010160","rule_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must be configured so that when passwords are changed a minimum of eight of the total number of characters must be changed.","fix_text":"Configure the operating system to require the change of at least eight of the total number of characters when passwords are changed by setting the \"difok\" option.\n\nAdd the following line to \"/etc/security/pwquality.conf\" (or modify the line to have the required value):\n\ndifok = 8","weight":"10.0","check_content":"The \"difok\" option sets the number of characters in a password that must not be present in the old password.\n\nCheck for the value of the \"difok\" option in \"/etc/security/pwquality.conf\" with the following command:\n\n# grep difok /etc/security/pwquality.conf \ndifok = 8\n\nIf the value of \"difok\" is set to less than \"8\", this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_7_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Use of a complex password helps to increase the time and resources required to compromise the password. Password complexity, or strength, is a measure of the effectiveness of a password in resisting attempts at guessing and brute-force attacks.\n\nPassword complexity is one factor of several that determines how long it takes to crack a password. The more complex the password, the greater the number of possible combinations that need to be tested before the password is compromised.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-86535","V-71911"],"ccis":["CCI-000195"],"reference_identifier":"2899","uuid":"7253c9d8-4df9-4a83-bb5c-41d883b07fb7","stig_uuid":"aa379772-3679-4074-8a4e-5b09f41d3e8e","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_Dom0_RHEL7_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 2\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nThe automated check found that difok is not configured or set below 8 in /etc/security/pwquality.conf. Remediation: Set difok = 8 in /etc/security/pwquality.conf. Finding: Open.\n        \n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_Dom0_RHEL7_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: 0B3DE8EC320C34DF3DF9C8E31C9CADCA4C0A5328\n~~~~~\nV-204411 - Password Must Differ by 8 Characters (difok)\n============================================================\n\nCommand: grep difok /etc/security/pwquality.conf\nResult: # difok = 5\n\nFAIL: difok is not configured in /etc/security/pwquality.conf.\nRemediation: Add to /etc/security/pwquality.conf:\n  difok = 8\n"},{"group_id_src":"V-204412","group_tree":[{"id":"V-204412","title":"SRG-OS-000072-GPOS-00040","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-204412","severity":"medium","group_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must be configured so that when passwords are changed a minimum of four character classes must be changed.","rule_id_src":"SV-204412r982198_rule","rule_id":"SV-204412r982198","rule_version":"RHEL-07-010170","rule_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must be configured so that when passwords are changed a minimum of four character classes must be changed.","fix_text":"Configure the operating system to require the change of at least four character classes when passwords are changed by setting the \"minclass\" option.\n\nAdd the following line to \"/etc/security/pwquality.conf conf\" (or modify the line to have the required value):\n\nminclass = 4","weight":"10.0","check_content":"The \"minclass\" option sets the minimum number of required classes of characters for the new password (digits, upper-case, lower-case, others).\n\nCheck for the value of the \"minclass\" option in \"/etc/security/pwquality.conf\" with the following command:\n\n# grep minclass /etc/security/pwquality.conf \nminclass = 4\n\nIf the value of \"minclass\" is set to less than \"4\", this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_7_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Use of a complex password helps to increase the time and resources required to compromise the password. Password complexity, or strength, is a measure of the effectiveness of a password in resisting attempts at guessing and brute-force attacks.\n\nPassword complexity is one factor of several that determines how long it takes to crack a password. The more complex the password, the greater the number of possible combinations that need to be tested before the password is compromised.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-86537","V-71913"],"ccis":["CCI-000195"],"reference_identifier":"2899","uuid":"00dedb45-dc37-4709-83ef-52d0c8e9e336","stig_uuid":"aa379772-3679-4074-8a4e-5b09f41d3e8e","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_Dom0_RHEL7_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 2\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nThe automated check found that minclass is not configured or set below 4 in /etc/security/pwquality.conf. Remediation: Set minclass = 4 in /etc/security/pwquality.conf. Finding: Open.\n        \n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_Dom0_RHEL7_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: 1221448DC55D1EA2C1110492377B6657131BC926\n~~~~~\nV-204412 - Password Must Use 4 Character Classes (minclass)\n============================================================\n\nCommand: grep minclass /etc/security/pwquality.conf\nResult: # minclass = 0\n\nFAIL: minclass is not configured in /etc/security/pwquality.conf.\nRemediation: Add to /etc/security/pwquality.conf:\n  minclass = 4\n"},{"group_id_src":"V-204413","group_tree":[{"id":"V-204413","title":"SRG-OS-000072-GPOS-00040","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-204413","severity":"medium","group_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must be configured so that when passwords are changed the number of repeating consecutive characters must not be more than three characters.","rule_id_src":"SV-204413r982198_rule","rule_id":"SV-204413r982198","rule_version":"RHEL-07-010180","rule_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must be configured so that when passwords are changed the number of repeating consecutive characters must not be more than three characters.","fix_text":"Configure the operating system to require the change of the number of repeating consecutive characters when passwords are changed by setting the \"maxrepeat\" option.\n\nAdd the following line to \"/etc/security/pwquality.conf conf\" (or modify the line to have the required value):\n\nmaxrepeat = 3","weight":"10.0","check_content":"The \"maxrepeat\" option sets the maximum number of allowed same consecutive characters in a new password.\n\nCheck for the value of the \"maxrepeat\" option in \"/etc/security/pwquality.conf\" with the following command:\n\n# grep maxrepeat /etc/security/pwquality.conf \nmaxrepeat = 3\n\nIf the value of \"maxrepeat\" is set to more than \"3\", this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_7_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Use of a complex password helps to increase the time and resources required to compromise the password. Password complexity, or strength, is a measure of the effectiveness of a password in resisting attempts at guessing and brute-force attacks.\n\nPassword complexity is one factor of several that determines how long it takes to crack a password. The more complex the password, the greater the number of possible combinations that need to be tested before the password is compromised.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-86539","V-71915"],"ccis":["CCI-000195"],"reference_identifier":"2899","uuid":"ad489ac1-e9e3-437d-8701-abbdea797d52","stig_uuid":"aa379772-3679-4074-8a4e-5b09f41d3e8e","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_Dom0_RHEL7_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 2\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nThe automated check found that maxrepeat is not configured or set above 3 in /etc/security/pwquality.conf. Remediation: Set maxrepeat = 3 in /etc/security/pwquality.conf. Finding: Open.\n        \n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_Dom0_RHEL7_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: 8D96BE8254C054C7320CB0B227CC465162D96117\n~~~~~\nV-204413 - Password Max Consecutive Repeating Characters (maxrepeat)\n============================================================\n\nCommand: grep maxrepeat /etc/security/pwquality.conf\nResult: # maxrepeat = 0\n\nFAIL: maxrepeat is not configured in /etc/security/pwquality.conf.\nRemediation: Add to /etc/security/pwquality.conf:\n  maxrepeat = 3\n"},{"group_id_src":"V-204414","group_tree":[{"id":"V-204414","title":"SRG-OS-000072-GPOS-00040","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-204414","severity":"medium","group_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must be configured so that when passwords are changed the number of repeating characters of the same character class must not be more than four characters.","rule_id_src":"SV-204414r982198_rule","rule_id":"SV-204414r982198","rule_version":"RHEL-07-010190","rule_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must be configured so that when passwords are changed the number of repeating characters of the same character class must not be more than four characters.","fix_text":"Configure the operating system to require the change of the number of repeating characters of the same character class when passwords are changed by setting the \"maxclassrepeat\" option.\n\nAdd the following line to \"/etc/security/pwquality.conf\" conf (or modify the line to have the required value):\n\nmaxclassrepeat = 4","weight":"10.0","check_content":"The \"maxclassrepeat\" option sets the maximum number of allowed same consecutive characters in the same class in the new password.\n\nCheck for the value of the \"maxclassrepeat\" option in \"/etc/security/pwquality.conf\" with the following command:\n\n$ sudo grep maxclassrepeat /etc/security/pwquality.conf \nmaxclassrepeat = 4\n\nIf the value of \"maxclassrepeat\" is set to \"0\", more than \"4\" or is commented out, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_7_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Use of a complex password helps to increase the time and resources required to compromise the password. Password complexity, or strength, is a measure of the effectiveness of a password in resisting attempts at guessing and brute-force attacks.\n\nPassword complexity is one factor of several that determines how long it takes to crack a password. The more complex the password, the greater the number of possible combinations that need to be tested before the password is compromised.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-86541","V-71917"],"ccis":["CCI-000195"],"reference_identifier":"2899","uuid":"ea8e0b75-5f2f-4323-bb67-e848421370c0","stig_uuid":"aa379772-3679-4074-8a4e-5b09f41d3e8e","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_Dom0_RHEL7_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 2\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nThe automated check found that maxclassrepeat is not configured or set above 4 in /etc/security/pwquality.conf. Remediation: Set maxclassrepeat = 4 in /etc/security/pwquality.conf. Finding: Open.\n        \n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_Dom0_RHEL7_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: FC80E40D7B0F4B9C856D660770C7458897A96BD6\n~~~~~\nV-204414 - Password Max Consecutive Same-Class Characters (maxclassrepeat)\n============================================================\n\nCommand: grep maxclassrepeat /etc/security/pwquality.conf\nResult: # maxclassrepeat = 0\n\nFAIL: maxclassrepeat is not configured in /etc/security/pwquality.conf.\nRemediation: Add to /etc/security/pwquality.conf:\n  maxclassrepeat = 4\n"},{"group_id_src":"V-204415","group_tree":[{"id":"V-204415","title":"SRG-OS-000073-GPOS-00041","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-204415","severity":"medium","group_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must be configured so that the PAM system service is configured to store only encrypted representations of passwords.","rule_id_src":"SV-204415r982199_rule","rule_id":"SV-204415r982199","rule_version":"RHEL-07-010200","rule_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must be configured so that the PAM system service is configured to store only encrypted representations of passwords.","fix_text":"Configure the operating system to store only SHA512 encrypted representations of passwords.\n\nAdd the following line in \"/etc/pam.d/system-auth\":\n     password    sufficient    pam_unix.so sha512 shadow try_first_pass use_authtok\n\nAdd the following line in \"/etc/pam.d/password-auth\":\n     password    sufficient    pam_unix.so sha512 shadow try_first_pass use_authtok\n\nNote: Per requirement RHEL-07-010199, RHEL 7 must be configured to not overwrite custom authentication configuration settings while using the authconfig utility; otherwise, manual changes to the listed files will be overwritten whenever the authconfig utility is used.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the PAM system service is configured to store only encrypted representations of passwords. The strength of encryption that must be used to hash passwords for all accounts is SHA512.\n\nCheck that the system is configured to create SHA512 hashed passwords with the following command:\n\n     # grep password /etc/pam.d/system-auth /etc/pam.d/password-auth\n\nOutcome should look like following:\n     /etc/pam.d/system-auth-ac:password    sufficient    pam_unix.so sha512 shadow try_first_pass use_authtok\n     /etc/pam.d/password-auth:password     sufficient    pam_unix.so sha512 shadow try_first_pass use_authtok\n\nIf the \"/etc/pam.d/system-auth\" and \"/etc/pam.d/password-auth\" configuration files allow for password hashes other than SHA512 to be used, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_7_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Passwords need to be protected at all times, and encryption is the standard method for protecting passwords. If passwords are not encrypted, they can be plainly read (i.e., clear text) and easily compromised. Passwords encrypted with a weak algorithm are no more protected than if they are kept in plain text.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-86543","V-71919"],"ccis":["CCI-000196"],"reference_identifier":"2899","uuid":"8e06c18d-8770-4ece-9114-3475c69f4ebe","stig_uuid":"aa379772-3679-4074-8a4e-5b09f41d3e8e","status":"not_a_finding","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_Dom0_RHEL7_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 1\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nThe automated check verified that PAM is configured to use SHA512 for password hashing in both /etc/pam.d/system-auth and /etc/pam.d/password-auth on this XCP-ng Dom0 system. Finding: Not a Finding.\n        \n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_Dom0_RHEL7_Checks) found this to be NOT A FINDING on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: F81184619A464C227E76413413C8DBEFC39A4B68\n~~~~~\nV-204415 - PAM Must Store Passwords Using SHA512\n============================================================\n\nCommand: grep -i sha512 /etc/pam.d/system-auth\nResult: password    sufficient    pam_unix.so try_first_pass use_authtok nullok sha512 shadow\n\nCommand: grep -i sha512 /etc/pam.d/password-auth\nResult: password    sufficient    pam_unix.so try_first_pass use_authtok nullok sha512 shadow\n\nPASS: PAM is configured to use SHA512 for password hashing in both system-auth and password-auth.\n"},{"group_id_src":"V-204416","group_tree":[{"id":"V-204416","title":"SRG-OS-000073-GPOS-00041","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-204416","severity":"medium","group_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must be configured to use the shadow file to store only encrypted representations of passwords.","rule_id_src":"SV-204416r982199_rule","rule_id":"SV-204416r982199","rule_version":"RHEL-07-010210","rule_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must be configured to use the shadow file to store only encrypted representations of passwords.","fix_text":"Configure the operating system to store only SHA512 encrypted representations of passwords.\n\nAdd or update the following line in \"/etc/login.defs\":\n\nENCRYPT_METHOD SHA512","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the system's shadow file is configured to store only encrypted representations of passwords. The strength of encryption that must be used to hash passwords for all accounts is SHA512.\n\nCheck that the system is configured to create SHA512 hashed passwords with the following command:\n\n# grep -i encrypt /etc/login.defs\nENCRYPT_METHOD SHA512\n\nIf the \"/etc/login.defs\" configuration file does not exist or allows for password hashes other than SHA512 to be used, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_7_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Passwords need to be protected at all times, and encryption is the standard method for protecting passwords. If passwords are not encrypted, they can be plainly read (i.e., clear text) and easily compromised. Passwords encrypted with a weak algorithm are no more protected than if they are kept in plain text.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-86545","V-71921"],"ccis":["CCI-000196"],"reference_identifier":"2899","uuid":"96302e68-756e-4e39-abe1-e21204ca2e63","stig_uuid":"aa379772-3679-4074-8a4e-5b09f41d3e8e","status":"not_a_finding","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_Dom0_RHEL7_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 1\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nThe automated check verified that ENCRYPT_METHOD is set to SHA512 in /etc/login.defs on this XCP-ng Dom0 system, ensuring all shadow file passwords use strong hashing. Finding: Not a Finding.\n        \n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_Dom0_RHEL7_Checks) found this to be NOT A FINDING on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: C7AC683DA3426A5E3AA021F9C5A8395AAB613530\n~~~~~\nV-204416 - Shadow File Must Use SHA512 Hashing\n============================================================\n\nCommand: grep -i encrypt_method /etc/login.defs\nResult: ENCRYPT_METHOD SHA512\n\nPASS: ENCRYPT_METHOD is set to SHA512 in /etc/login.defs.\n"},{"group_id_src":"V-204417","group_tree":[{"id":"V-204417","title":"SRG-OS-000073-GPOS-00041","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-204417","severity":"medium","group_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must be configured so that user and group account administration utilities are configured to store only encrypted representations of passwords.","rule_id_src":"SV-204417r982199_rule","rule_id":"SV-204417r982199","rule_version":"RHEL-07-010220","rule_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must be configured so that user and group account administration utilities are configured to store only encrypted representations of passwords.","fix_text":"Configure the operating system to store only SHA512 encrypted representations of passwords.\n\nAdd or update the following line in \"/etc/libuser.conf\" in the [defaults] section: \n\ncrypt_style = sha512","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the user and group account administration utilities are configured to store only encrypted representations of passwords. The strength of encryption that must be used to hash passwords for all accounts is \"SHA512\".\n\nCheck that the system is configured to create \"SHA512\" hashed passwords with the following command:\n\n# grep -i sha512 /etc/libuser.conf \n\ncrypt_style = sha512\n\nIf the \"crypt_style\" variable is not set to \"sha512\", is not in the defaults section, is commented out, or does not exist, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_7_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Passwords need to be protected at all times, and encryption is the standard method for protecting passwords. If passwords are not encrypted, they can be plainly read (i.e., clear text) and easily compromised. Passwords encrypted with a weak algorithm are no more protected than if they are kept in plain text.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-86547","V-71923"],"ccis":["CCI-000196"],"reference_identifier":"2899","uuid":"2805c5fc-df34-4ded-aad6-9e2437be4bfa","stig_uuid":"aa379772-3679-4074-8a4e-5b09f41d3e8e","status":"not_a_finding","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_Dom0_RHEL7_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 1\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nThe automated check verified that crypt_style is set to sha512 in /etc/libuser.conf on this XCP-ng Dom0 system, ensuring user administration utilities create SHA512 hashed passwords. Finding: Not a Finding.\n        \n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_Dom0_RHEL7_Checks) found this to be NOT A FINDING on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: 7AA750D8FD8BC6B7BA4D622F1C6E38E0257694A6\n~~~~~\nV-204417 - User/Group Admin Utilities Must Use SHA512\n============================================================\n\nCommand: grep -i crypt_style /etc/libuser.conf\nResult: crypt_style = sha512\n\nPASS: crypt_style is set to sha512 in /etc/libuser.conf.\n"},{"group_id_src":"V-204418","group_tree":[{"id":"V-204418","title":"SRG-OS-000075-GPOS-00043","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-204418","severity":"medium","group_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must be configured so that passwords for new users are restricted to a 24 hours/1 day minimum lifetime.","rule_id_src":"SV-204418r982188_rule","rule_id":"SV-204418r982188","rule_version":"RHEL-07-010230","rule_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must be configured so that passwords for new users are restricted to a 24 hours/1 day minimum lifetime.","fix_text":"Configure the operating system to enforce 24 hours/1 day as the minimum password lifetime.\n\nAdd the following line in \"/etc/login.defs\" (or modify the line to have the required value):\n\nPASS_MIN_DAYS     1","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the operating system enforces 24 hours/1 day as the minimum password lifetime for new user accounts.\n\nCheck for the value of \"PASS_MIN_DAYS\" in \"/etc/login.defs\" with the following command: \n\n# grep -i pass_min_days /etc/login.defs\nPASS_MIN_DAYS     1\n\nIf the \"PASS_MIN_DAYS\" parameter value is not \"1\" or greater, or is commented out, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_7_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Enforcing a minimum password lifetime helps to prevent repeated password changes to defeat the password reuse or history enforcement requirement. If users are allowed to immediately and continually change their password, the password could be repeatedly changed in a short period of time to defeat the organization's policy regarding password reuse.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-86549","V-71925"],"ccis":["CCI-000198"],"reference_identifier":"2899","uuid":"8364a8e4-5c17-4346-bd92-0fa473639f7b","stig_uuid":"aa379772-3679-4074-8a4e-5b09f41d3e8e","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_Dom0_RHEL7_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 2\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nThe automated check found that PASS_MIN_DAYS is not configured or set below 1 in /etc/login.defs. Remediation: Set PASS_MIN_DAYS 1 in /etc/login.defs. Finding: Open.\n        \n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_Dom0_RHEL7_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: CC1A8562E4FDE46F7D28853ABED0A83D48B9D0F8\n~~~~~\nV-204418 - Minimum Password Lifetime 24 Hours (PASS_MIN_DAYS)\n============================================================\n\nCommand: grep -i pass_min_days /etc/login.defs\nResult: #\tPASS_MIN_DAYS\tMinimum number of days allowed between password changes.\nPASS_MIN_DAYS\t0\n\nActive PASS_MIN_DAYS value: 0\n\nFAIL: PASS_MIN_DAYS is set to 0 (required: >= 1).\nRemediation: Set PASS_MIN_DAYS 1 in /etc/login.defs\n"},{"group_id_src":"V-204419","group_tree":[{"id":"V-204419","title":"SRG-OS-000075-GPOS-00043","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-204419","severity":"medium","group_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must be configured so that passwords are restricted to a 24 hours/1 day minimum lifetime.","rule_id_src":"SV-204419r982188_rule","rule_id":"SV-204419r982188","rule_version":"RHEL-07-010240","rule_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must be configured so that passwords are restricted to a 24 hours/1 day minimum lifetime.","fix_text":"Configure non-compliant accounts to enforce a 24 hours/1 day minimum password lifetime:\n\n# chage -m 1 [user]","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Check whether the minimum time period between password changes for each user account is one day or greater.\n\n# awk -F: '$4 < 1 {print $1 \" \" $4}' /etc/shadow\n\nIf any results are returned that are not associated with a system account, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_7_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Enforcing a minimum password lifetime helps to prevent repeated password changes to defeat the password reuse or history enforcement requirement. If users are allowed to immediately and continually change their password, the password could be repeatedly changed in a short period of time to defeat the organization's policy regarding password reuse.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-86551","V-71927"],"ccis":["CCI-000198"],"reference_identifier":"2899","uuid":"f3688633-ab18-4845-83dc-6b489674e6c3","stig_uuid":"aa379772-3679-4074-8a4e-5b09f41d3e8e","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_Dom0_RHEL7_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 2\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nThe automated check found non-system accounts with minimum password age less than 1 day in /etc/shadow. Remediation: Run chage -m 1 [username] for each affected account. Finding: Open.\n        \n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_Dom0_RHEL7_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: 8C5951F1C40ABBDA99F9C597D1CD7A4823604CA5\n~~~~~\nV-204419 - Existing Passwords Must Have 24-Hour Minimum Lifetime\n============================================================\n\nCommand: awk -F: ' < 1 {print , }' /etc/shadow\nResult: root 0\nbin 0\ndaemon 0\nadm 0\nlp 0\nsync 0\nshutdown 0\nhalt 0\nmail 0\noperator 0\ngames 0\nftp 0\nnobody 0\nnagios 0\nnrpe 0\ntcpdump \nsystemd-network \ndbus \nrpc 0\nunbound \ntss \nchrony \nsshd \nrpcuser \nnfsnobody \nqemu \nqemu_base \nswtpm_base \nvncterm \nvncterm_base\n\nFAIL: The following non-system accounts have minimum password age less than 1 day:\n  root 0\n  nagios 0\n  nrpe 0\n  tcpdump\n  unbound\n  qemu\n  qemu_base\n  swtpm_base\n  vncterm\n  vncterm_base\nRemediation: chage -m 1 [username] for each affected account\n"},{"group_id_src":"V-204420","group_tree":[{"id":"V-204420","title":"SRG-OS-000076-GPOS-00044","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-204420","severity":"medium","group_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must be configured so that passwords for new users are restricted to a 60-day maximum lifetime.","rule_id_src":"SV-204420r982200_rule","rule_id":"SV-204420r982200","rule_version":"RHEL-07-010250","rule_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must be configured so that passwords for new users are restricted to a 60-day maximum lifetime.","fix_text":"Configure the operating system to enforce a 60-day maximum password lifetime restriction.\n\nAdd the following line in \"/etc/login.defs\" (or modify the line to have the required value):\n\nPASS_MAX_DAYS     60","weight":"10.0","check_content":"If passwords are not being used for authentication, this is Not Applicable.\n\nVerify the operating system enforces a 60-day maximum password lifetime restriction for new user accounts.\n\nCheck for the value of \"PASS_MAX_DAYS\" in \"/etc/login.defs\" with the following command:\n\n# grep -i pass_max_days /etc/login.defs\nPASS_MAX_DAYS 60\n\nIf the \"PASS_MAX_DAYS\" parameter value is not 60 or less, or is commented out, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_7_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Any password, no matter how complex, can eventually be cracked. Therefore, passwords need to be changed periodically. If the operating system does not limit the lifetime of passwords and force users to change their passwords, there is the risk that the operating system passwords could be compromised.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-86553","V-71929"],"ccis":["CCI-000199"],"reference_identifier":"2899","uuid":"f7b356a0-91f9-47d4-961f-a730e9404886","stig_uuid":"aa379772-3679-4074-8a4e-5b09f41d3e8e","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_Dom0_RHEL7_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 2\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nThe automated check found that PASS_MAX_DAYS is not configured or set above 60 in /etc/login.defs. Remediation: Set PASS_MAX_DAYS 60 in /etc/login.defs. Finding: Open.\n        \n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_Dom0_RHEL7_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: C15DC18E85F7FC232B1B8E38BBF9767362007725\n~~~~~\nV-204420 - Maximum Password Lifetime 60 Days (PASS_MAX_DAYS)\n============================================================\n\nCommand: grep -i pass_max_days /etc/login.defs\nResult: #\tPASS_MAX_DAYS\tMaximum number of days a password may be used.\nPASS_MAX_DAYS\t99999\n\nActive PASS_MAX_DAYS value: 99999\n\nFAIL: PASS_MAX_DAYS is set to 99999 (required: <= 60).\nRemediation: Set PASS_MAX_DAYS 60 in /etc/login.defs\n"},{"group_id_src":"V-204421","group_tree":[{"id":"V-204421","title":"SRG-OS-000076-GPOS-00044","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-204421","severity":"medium","group_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must be configured so that existing passwords are restricted to a 60-day maximum lifetime.","rule_id_src":"SV-204421r982200_rule","rule_id":"SV-204421r982200","rule_version":"RHEL-07-010260","rule_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must be configured so that existing passwords are restricted to a 60-day maximum lifetime.","fix_text":"Configure non-compliant accounts to enforce a 60-day maximum password lifetime restriction.\n\n# chage -M 60 [user]","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Check whether the maximum time period for existing passwords is restricted to 60 days.\n\n# awk -F: '$5 > 60 {print $1 \" \" $5}' /etc/shadow\n\nIf any results are returned that are not associated with a system account, this is a finding.\n","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_7_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Any password, no matter how complex, can eventually be cracked. Therefore, passwords need to be changed periodically. If the operating system does not limit the lifetime of passwords and force users to change their passwords, there is the risk that the operating system passwords could be compromised.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-86555","V-71931"],"ccis":["CCI-000199"],"reference_identifier":"2899","uuid":"83b17387-d34a-4a2c-8dbe-12a883fcf354","stig_uuid":"aa379772-3679-4074-8a4e-5b09f41d3e8e","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_Dom0_RHEL7_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 2\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nThe automated check found non-system accounts with maximum password age greater than 60 days in /etc/shadow. Remediation: Run chage -M 60 [username] for each affected account. Finding: Open.\n        \n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_Dom0_RHEL7_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: 25570D87D09B2BA989A3BD5A6A2B36B66BF83EB1\n~~~~~\nV-204421 - Existing Passwords Must Have 60-Day Maximum Lifetime\n============================================================\n\nCommand: awk -F: ' > 60 {print , }' /etc/shadow\nResult: root 99999\nbin 99999\ndaemon 99999\nadm 99999\nlp 99999\nsync 99999\nshutdown 99999\nhalt 99999\nmail 99999\noperator 99999\ngames 99999\nftp 99999\nnobody 99999\nnagios 99999\nnrpe 99999\nrpc 99999\n\nFAIL: The following non-system accounts have maximum password age greater than 60 days:\n  root 99999\n  nagios 99999\n  nrpe 99999\nRemediation: chage -M 60 [username] for each affected account\n"},{"group_id_src":"V-204422","group_tree":[{"id":"V-204422","title":"SRG-OS-000077-GPOS-00045","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-204422","severity":"medium","group_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must be configured so that passwords are prohibited from reuse for a minimum of five generations.","rule_id_src":"SV-204422r982201_rule","rule_id":"SV-204422r982201","rule_version":"RHEL-07-010270","rule_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must be configured so that passwords are prohibited from reuse for a minimum of five generations.","fix_text":"Configure the operating system to prohibit password reuse for a minimum of five generations.\n\nAdd the following line in \"/etc/pam.d/system-auth\" (or modify the line to have the required value):\n\npassword     requisite     pam_pwhistory.so remember=5 retry=3\n\nAdd the following line in \"/etc/pam.d/password-auth\" (or modify the line to have the required value):\n\npassword     requisite     pam_pwhistory.so use_authtok remember=5 retry=3\n   \nNote: Per requirement RHEL-07-010199, RHEL 7 must be configured to not overwrite custom authentication configuration settings while using the authconfig utility; otherwise, manual changes to the listed files will be overwritten whenever the authconfig utility is used.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the operating system prohibits password reuse for a minimum of five generations.\n\nCheck for the value of the \"remember\" argument in \"/etc/pam.d/system-auth\" and \"/etc/pam.d/password-auth\" with the following command:\n\n     # grep -i remember /etc/pam.d/system-auth /etc/pam.d/password-auth\n     password     requisite     pam_pwhistory.so use_authtok remember=5 retry=3\n\nIf the line containing the \"pam_pwhistory.so\" line does not have the \"remember\" module argument set, is commented out, or the value of the \"remember\" module argument is set to less than \"5\", this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_7_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Password complexity, or strength, is a measure of the effectiveness of a password in resisting attempts at guessing and brute-force attacks. If the information system or application allows the user to consecutively reuse their password when that password has exceeded its defined lifetime, the end result is a password that is not changed per policy requirements.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-86557","V-71933"],"ccis":["CCI-000200"],"reference_identifier":"2899","uuid":"4314e952-81a5-4529-a566-2dc6605bdb44","stig_uuid":"aa379772-3679-4074-8a4e-5b09f41d3e8e","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_Dom0_RHEL7_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 2\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nThe automated check found that the remember parameter is not configured or set below 5 in one or both PAM auth files. Remediation: Add remember=5 to pam_unix.so or pam_pwhistory.so in /etc/pam.d/system-auth and /etc/pam.d/password-auth. Finding: Open.\n        \n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_Dom0_RHEL7_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: 38DA99A2AF76F0E039BFBC88021B8CD89665F980\n~~~~~\nV-204422 - Password Reuse Prohibited for 5 Generations (remember)\n============================================================\n\nCommand: grep -i remember /etc/pam.d/system-auth\nResult: \n\nCommand: grep -i remember /etc/pam.d/password-auth\nResult: \n\nsystem-auth remember value: 0\npassword-auth remember value: 0\n\nFAIL: Password reuse must be prohibited for at least 5 generations.\nRemediation: Add remember=5 to pam_unix.so or pam_pwhistory.so in both:\n  /etc/pam.d/system-auth\n  /etc/pam.d/password-auth\n"},{"group_id_src":"V-204423","group_tree":[{"id":"V-204423","title":"SRG-OS-000078-GPOS-00046","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-204423","severity":"medium","group_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must be configured so that passwords are a minimum of 15 characters in length.","rule_id_src":"SV-204423r982202_rule","rule_id":"SV-204423r982202","rule_version":"RHEL-07-010280","rule_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must be configured so that passwords are a minimum of 15 characters in length.","fix_text":"Configure operating system to enforce a minimum 15-character password length.\n\nAdd the following line to \"/etc/security/pwquality.conf\" (or modify the line to have the required value):\n\nminlen = 15","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the operating system enforces a minimum 15-character password length. The \"minlen\" option sets the minimum number of characters in a new password.\n\nCheck for the value of the \"minlen\" option in \"/etc/security/pwquality.conf\" with the following command:\n\n# grep minlen /etc/security/pwquality.conf\nminlen = 15\n\nIf the command does not return a \"minlen\" value of 15 or greater, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_7_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"The shorter the password, the lower the number of possible combinations that need to be tested before the password is compromised.\n\nPassword complexity, or strength, is a measure of the effectiveness of a password in resisting attempts at guessing and brute-force attacks. Password length is one factor of several that helps to determine strength and how long it takes to crack a password. Use of more characters in a password helps to exponentially increase the time and/or resources required to compromise the password.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-86559","V-71935"],"ccis":["CCI-000205"],"reference_identifier":"2899","uuid":"3096e7c4-7540-4c0d-b339-2664cfb79314","stig_uuid":"aa379772-3679-4074-8a4e-5b09f41d3e8e","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_Dom0_RHEL7_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 2\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nThe automated check found that minlen is not configured or set below 15 in /etc/security/pwquality.conf. Remediation: Set minlen = 15 in /etc/security/pwquality.conf. Finding: Open.\n        \n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_Dom0_RHEL7_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: FB1F43D95AE07DFEDA8192AC54FB4025573DF1FF\n~~~~~\nV-204423 - Password Minimum Length 15 Characters (minlen)\n============================================================\n\nCommand: grep minlen /etc/security/pwquality.conf\nResult: # minlen = 9\n\nFAIL: minlen is not configured in /etc/security/pwquality.conf.\nRemediation: Add to /etc/security/pwquality.conf:\n  minlen = 15\n"},{"group_id_src":"V-204424","group_tree":[{"id":"V-204424","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-204424","severity":"high","group_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must not allow accounts configured with blank or null passwords.","rule_id_src":"SV-204424r991589_rule","rule_id":"SV-204424r991589","rule_version":"RHEL-07-010290","rule_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must not allow accounts configured with blank or null passwords.","fix_text":"If an account is configured for password authentication but does not have an assigned password, it may be possible to log on to the account without authenticating.\n\nRemove any instances of the \"nullok\" option in \"/etc/pam.d/system-auth\" and \"/etc/pam.d/password-auth\" to prevent logons with empty passwords.\n\nNote: Per requirement RHEL-07-010199, RHEL 7 must be configured to not overwrite custom authentication configuration settings while using the authconfig utility, otherwise manual changes to the listed files will be overwritten whenever the authconfig utility is used.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"To verify that null passwords cannot be used, run the following command: \n\n     # grep nullok /etc/pam.d/system-auth /etc/pam.d/password-auth\n\nIf this produces any output, it may be possible to log on with accounts with empty passwords.\n\nIf null passwords can be used, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_7_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"If an account has an empty password, anyone could log on and run commands with the privileges of that account. Accounts with empty passwords should never be used in operational environments.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-86561","V-71937"],"ccis":["CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"2899","uuid":"ac822c21-9232-4f21-960f-2916f67e0242","stig_uuid":"aa379772-3679-4074-8a4e-5b09f41d3e8e","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_Dom0_RHEL7_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 2\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nThe automated check found that the XCP-ng Dom0 (RHEL 7-based) system allows accounts with blank or null passwords to authenticate. The scan detected the 'nullok' option in /etc/pam.d/system-auth and/or /etc/pam.d/password-auth, which permits authentication without a password for accounts that have no password set. Per RHEL 7 STIG requirement RHEL-07-010290, the operating system must not allow accounts configured with blank or null passwords. This represents a CAT I (high severity) finding because it could allow unauthorized access to the system. Remediation: (1) Remove all instances of 'nullok' from /etc/pam.d/system-auth. (2) Remove all instances of 'nullok' from /etc/pam.d/password-auth. (3) Verify no accounts exist with empty passwords: awk -F: '($2 == \"\") {print}' /etc/shadow. (4) Set passwords for any accounts found without one. The system administrator must ensure all accounts have valid passwords.\n        \n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_Dom0_RHEL7_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: DC6BB6BDC1CC27D9B9CA042D63C796B877EAD5F3\n~~~~~\nV-204424 - No Blank or Null Passwords Allowed\n============================================================\n\nCheck 1: /etc/pam.d/system-auth\nCommand: grep -i nullok /etc/pam.d/system-auth\nResult: auth        sufficient    pam_unix.so try_first_pass nullok\npassword    sufficient    pam_unix.so try_first_pass use_authtok nullok sha512 shadow\n\nCheck 2: /etc/pam.d/password-auth\nCommand: grep -i nullok /etc/pam.d/password-auth\nResult: auth        sufficient    pam_unix.so try_first_pass nullok\npassword    sufficient    pam_unix.so try_first_pass use_authtok nullok sha512 shadow\n\nFAIL: The nullok option allows accounts with blank passwords to authenticate.\nRemediation: Remove all instances of 'nullok' from\n/etc/pam.d/system-auth and /etc/pam.d/password-auth.\n"},{"group_id_src":"V-204425","group_tree":[{"id":"V-204425","title":"SRG-OS-000106-GPOS-00053","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-204425","severity":"high","group_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must be configured so that the SSH daemon does not allow authentication using an empty password.","rule_id_src":"SV-204425r958486_rule","rule_id":"SV-204425r958486","rule_version":"RHEL-07-010300","rule_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must be configured so that the SSH daemon does not allow authentication using an empty password.","fix_text":"To explicitly disallow remote logon from accounts with empty passwords, add or correct the following line in \"/etc/ssh/sshd_config\":\n\nPermitEmptyPasswords no\n\nThe SSH service must be restarted for changes to take effect.  Any accounts with empty passwords should be disabled immediately, and PAM configuration should prevent users from being able to assign themselves empty passwords.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"To determine how the SSH daemon's \"PermitEmptyPasswords\" option is set, run the following command:\n\n# grep -i PermitEmptyPasswords /etc/ssh/sshd_config\nPermitEmptyPasswords no\n\nIf no line, a commented line, or a line indicating the value \"no\" is returned, the required value is set.\n\nIf the required value is not set, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_7_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Configuring this setting for the SSH daemon provides additional assurance that remote logon via SSH will require a password, even in the event of misconfiguration elsewhere.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-86563","V-71939"],"ccis":["CCI-000766"],"reference_identifier":"2899","uuid":"1131efb3-d53a-490d-aef0-c2f92ce1808b","stig_uuid":"aa379772-3679-4074-8a4e-5b09f41d3e8e","status":"not_a_finding","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_Dom0_RHEL7_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 1\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nThe automated check verified that the SSH daemon on this XCP-ng Dom0 (RHEL 7-based) system does not allow authentication using empty passwords. The scan checked /etc/ssh/sshd_config for the PermitEmptyPasswords directive. The setting was confirmed as 'no' (or defaulting to 'no' when not explicitly set), which prevents SSH clients from authenticating with accounts that have no password configured. This meets the RHEL 7 STIG requirement (RHEL-07-010300) that the SSH daemon must not allow authentication using an empty password. SSH is the primary remote access method for XCP-ng Dom0 administration, making this control critical for preventing unauthorized remote access. Finding: Not a Finding.\n        \n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_Dom0_RHEL7_Checks) found this to be NOT A FINDING on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: 6B670296C33CE9A49DFF9474D78B826E84AE8086\n~~~~~\nV-204425 - SSH Must Not Allow Empty Passwords\n============================================================\n\nCommand: grep -i PermitEmptyPasswords /etc/ssh/sshd_config\nResult: #PermitEmptyPasswords no\n\nPASS: SSH daemon does not allow authentication with empty passwords.\n"},{"group_id_src":"V-204426","group_tree":[{"id":"V-204426","title":"SRG-OS-000118-GPOS-00060","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-204426","severity":"medium","group_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must disable account identifiers (individuals, groups, roles, and devices) if the password expires.","rule_id_src":"SV-204426r982189_rule","rule_id":"SV-204426r982189","rule_version":"RHEL-07-010310","rule_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must disable account identifiers (individuals, groups, roles, and devices) if the password expires.","fix_text":"Configure the operating system to disable account identifiers (individuals, groups, roles, and devices) 35 days after the password has expired.\n\nAdd the following line to \"/etc/default/useradd\" (or modify the line to have the required value):\n\n     INACTIVE=35\n\nDOD recommendation is 35 days, but a lower value is acceptable. The value \"-1\" will disable this feature, and \"0\" will disable the account immediately after the password expires.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"If passwords are not being used for authentication, this is Not Applicable.\n\nVerify the operating system disables account identifiers (individuals, groups, roles, and devices) after the password has expired with the following command:\n\n     # grep -i inactive /etc/default/useradd\n     INACTIVE=35\n\nIf \"INACTIVE\" is set to \"-1\", a value greater than \"35\", is commented out, or is not defined, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_7_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Inactive identifiers pose a risk to systems and applications because attackers may exploit an inactive identifier and potentially obtain undetected access to the system. Owners of inactive accounts will not notice if unauthorized access to their user account has been obtained.\n\nOperating systems need to track periods of inactivity and disable application identifiers after 35 days of inactivity.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-86565","V-71941"],"ccis":["CCI-000795"],"reference_identifier":"2899","uuid":"65fd3b88-cb2e-4f83-a3d0-f6e30bfb7f78","stig_uuid":"aa379772-3679-4074-8a4e-5b09f41d3e8e","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_Dom0_RHEL7_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 2\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nThe automated check found that the INACTIVE parameter in /etc/default/useradd is either not configured or set to a value greater than 35 (or -1 for disabled). Remediation: Run useradd -D -f 35 to set the default inactivity period. Finding: Open.\n        \n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_Dom0_RHEL7_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: 3137979B04DF932C5CC45858E56D10D856661334\n~~~~~\nV-204426 - Disable Account After Password Expiry (INACTIVE)\n============================================================\n\nCommand: grep -i inactive /etc/default/useradd\nResult: INACTIVE=-1\n\nActive INACTIVE value: -1\n\nFAIL: INACTIVE is set to -1 (required: 0-35, not -1).\nRemediation: useradd -D -f 35\n"},{"group_id_src":"V-204427","group_tree":[{"id":"V-204427","title":"SRG-OS-000329-GPOS-00128","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-204427","severity":"medium","group_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must be configured to lock accounts for a minimum of 15 minutes after three unsuccessful logon attempts within a 15-minute timeframe.","rule_id_src":"SV-204427r958736_rule","rule_id":"SV-204427r958736","rule_version":"RHEL-07-010320","rule_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must be configured to lock accounts for a minimum of 15 minutes after three unsuccessful logon attempts within a 15-minute timeframe.","fix_text":"Configure the operating system to lock an account for the maximum period when three unsuccessful logon attempts in 15 minutes are made.\n\nAdd/Modify the appropriate sections of the \"/etc/pam.d/system-auth\" and \"/etc/pam.d/password-auth\" files to match the following lines:\n\nauth        required      pam_faillock.so preauth silent audit deny=3 even_deny_root fail_interval=900 unlock_time=900\nauth        sufficient    pam_unix.so try_first_pass\nauth        [default=die] pam_faillock.so authfail audit deny=3 even_deny_root fail_interval=900 unlock_time=900\naccount     required      pam_faillock.so   \n\nNote: Per requirement RHEL-07-010199, RHEL 7 must be configured to not overwrite custom authentication configuration settings while using the authconfig utility, otherwise manual changes to the listed files will be overwritten whenever the authconfig utility is used.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Check that the system locks an account for a minimum of 15 minutes after three unsuccessful logon attempts within a period of 15 minutes with the following command:\n\n     # grep pam_faillock.so /etc/pam.d/password-auth\n\nauth        required      pam_faillock.so preauth silent audit deny=3 even_deny_root fail_interval=900 unlock_time=900\nauth        [default=die] pam_faillock.so authfail audit deny=3 even_deny_root fail_interval=900 unlock_time=900\naccount     required      pam_faillock.so \n\nIf the \"deny\" parameter is set to \"0\" or a value greater than \"3\" on both \"auth\" lines with the \"pam_faillock.so\" module, or is missing from these lines, this is a finding.\n\nIf the \"even_deny_root\" parameter is not set on both \"auth\" lines with the \"pam_faillock.so\" module, or is missing from these lines, this is a finding.\n\nIf the \"fail_interval\" parameter is set to \"0\" or is set to a value less than \"900\" on both \"auth\" lines with the \"pam_faillock.so\" module, or is missing from these lines, this is a finding.\n\nIf the \"unlock_time\" parameter is not set to \"0\", \"never\", or is set to a value less than \"900\" on both \"auth\" lines with the \"pam_faillock.so\" module, or is missing from these lines, this is a finding.\n\nNote: The maximum configurable value for \"unlock_time\" is \"604800\". \n\nIf any line referencing the \"pam_faillock.so\" module is commented out, this is a finding.\n\n     # grep pam_faillock.so /etc/pam.d/system-auth\n\nauth        required      pam_faillock.so preauth silent audit deny=3 even_deny_root fail_interval=900 unlock_time=900\nauth        [default=die] pam_faillock.so authfail audit deny=3 even_deny_root fail_interval=900 unlock_time=900\naccount     required      pam_faillock.so\n\nIf the \"deny\" parameter is set to \"0\" or a value greater than \"3\" on both \"auth\" lines with the \"pam_faillock.so\" module, or is missing from these lines, this is a finding.\n\nIf the \"even_deny_root\" parameter is not set on both \"auth\" lines with the \"pam_faillock.so\" module, or is missing from these lines, this is a finding.\n\nIf the \"fail_interval\" parameter is set to \"0\" or is set to a value less than \"900\" on both \"auth\" lines with the \"pam_faillock.so\" module, or is missing from these lines, this is a finding.\n\nIf the \"unlock_time\" parameter is not set to \"0\", \"never\", or is set to a value less than \"900\" on both \"auth\" lines with the \"pam_faillock.so\" module or is missing from these lines, this is a finding.\n\nNote: The maximum configurable value for \"unlock_time\" is \"604800\". \n\nIf any line referencing the \"pam_faillock.so\" module is commented out, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_7_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"By limiting the number of failed logon attempts, the risk of unauthorized system access via user password guessing, otherwise known as brute-forcing, is reduced. Limits are imposed by locking the account.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000329-GPOS-00128, SRG-OS-000021-GPOS-00005","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-86567","V-71943"],"ccis":["CCI-000044","CCI-002236","CCI-002237","CCI-002238"],"reference_identifier":"2899","uuid":"3827139c-4168-4d0a-a0d9-85dfcd4c86ee","stig_uuid":"aa379772-3679-4074-8a4e-5b09f41d3e8e","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_Dom0_RHEL7_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 2\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nThe automated check found that pam_faillock.so is not properly configured in /etc/pam.d/password-auth. One or more required parameters (deny, fail_interval, unlock_time) are missing or set to non-compliant values. Remediation: Configure pam_faillock.so in /etc/pam.d/password-auth with deny=3, fail_interval=900, unlock_time=900 (or 0 for permanent lock). Finding: Open.\n        \n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_Dom0_RHEL7_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: A37888FB9128548B1AD8B60456AE8FADD7C5E6AA\n~~~~~\nV-204427 - Lock Accounts After 3 Failed Attempts (pam_faillock)\n============================================================\n\nCommand: grep pam_faillock /etc/pam.d/password-auth\nResult:\n\n\ndeny=0 (required: <= 3)\nfail_interval=0 (required: >= 900)\nunlock_time=0 (required: >= 900 or 0=never)\n\nFAIL: pam_faillock is not properly configured in password-auth.\nRemediation: Configure pam_faillock.so with deny=3 fail_interval=900 unlock_time=900\n"},{"group_id_src":"V-204428","group_tree":[{"id":"V-204428","title":"SRG-OS-000329-GPOS-00128","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-204428","severity":"medium","group_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must lock the associated account after three unsuccessful root logon attempts are made within a 15-minute period.","rule_id_src":"SV-204428r958736_rule","rule_id":"SV-204428r958736","rule_version":"RHEL-07-010330","rule_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must lock the associated account after three unsuccessful root logon attempts are made within a 15-minute period.","fix_text":"Configure the operating system to automatically lock the root account, for a minimum of 15 minutes, when three unsuccessful logon attempts in 15 minutes are made.\n\nModify the first three lines of the auth section and the first line of the account section of the \"/etc/pam.d/system-auth\" and \"/etc/pam.d/password-auth\" files to match the following lines:\n\nauth        required      pam_faillock.so preauth silent audit deny=3 even_deny_root fail_interval=900 unlock_time=900\nauth        sufficient    pam_unix.so try_first_pass\nauth        [default=die] pam_faillock.so authfail audit deny=3 even_deny_root fail_interval=900 unlock_time=900\naccount     required      pam_faillock.so\n\nNote: Per requirement RHEL-07-010199, RHEL 7 must be configured to not overwrite custom authentication configuration settings while using the authconfig utility, otherwise manual changes to the listed files will be overwritten whenever the authconfig utility is used.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the operating system automatically locks the root account, for a minimum of 15 minutes, when three unsuccessful logon attempts in 15 minutes are made.\n\n     # grep pam_faillock.so /etc/pam.d/password-auth\n\nauth        required      pam_faillock.so preauth silent audit deny=3 even_deny_root fail_interval=900 unlock_time=900 \nauth        [default=die] pam_faillock.so authfail audit deny=3 even_deny_root fail_interval=900 unlock_time=900 \naccount     required      pam_faillock.so\n\nIf the \"even_deny_root\" setting is not defined on both lines with the \"pam_faillock.so\" module, is commented out, or is missing from a line, this is a finding.\n\n     # grep pam_faillock.so /etc/pam.d/system-auth\n\nauth        required      pam_faillock.so preauth silent audit deny=3 even_deny_root fail_interval=900 unlock_time=900 \nauth        [default=die] pam_faillock.so authfail audit deny=3 even_deny_root fail_interval=900 unlock_time=900\naccount     required      pam_faillock.so\n\nIf the \"even_deny_root\" setting is not defined on both lines with the \"pam_faillock.so\" module, is commented out, or is missing from a line, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_7_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"By limiting the number of failed logon attempts, the risk of unauthorized system access via user password guessing, otherwise known as brute forcing, is reduced. Limits are imposed by locking the account.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000329-GPOS-00128, SRG-OS-000021-GPOS-00005","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-86569","V-71945"],"ccis":["CCI-002238"],"reference_identifier":"2899","uuid":"c88d2818-d9ed-4611-81d3-34477046e3a8","stig_uuid":"aa379772-3679-4074-8a4e-5b09f41d3e8e","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_Dom0_RHEL7_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 2\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nThe automated check found that pam_faillock.so is not configured with the even_deny_root option in one or both PAM auth files on this XCP-ng Dom0 system. Remediation: Add even_deny_root to the pam_faillock.so line in both /etc/pam.d/system-auth and /etc/pam.d/password-auth. Finding: Open.\n        \n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_Dom0_RHEL7_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: 787E12ED74CCA2E39E33F365C2128BCDBDD6373D\n~~~~~\nV-204428 - Lock Root Account After 3 Failed Attempts\n============================================================\n\nCommand: grep pam_faillock /etc/pam.d/password-auth\nResult:\n\n\nCommand: grep pam_faillock /etc/pam.d/system-auth\nResult:\n\n\nFAIL: pam_faillock does not include even_deny_root.\nRemediation: Add even_deny_root to pam_faillock.so lines in PAM auth files.\n"},{"group_id_src":"V-204429","group_tree":[{"id":"V-204429","title":"SRG-OS-000373-GPOS-00156","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-204429","severity":"medium","group_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must be configured so that users must provide a password for privilege escalation.","rule_id_src":"SV-204429r987879_rule","rule_id":"SV-204429r987879","rule_version":"RHEL-07-010340","rule_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must be configured so that users must provide a password for privilege escalation.","fix_text":"Configure the operating system to require users to supply a password for privilege escalation.\n\nCheck the configuration of the \"/etc/sudoers\" file with the following command:\n$ sudo visudo\n\nRemove any occurrences of \"NOPASSWD\" tags in the file.\n\nCheck the configuration of the /etc/sudoers.d/* files with the following command:\n$ sudo grep -ir nopasswd /etc/sudoers.d\n\nRemove any occurrences of \"NOPASSWD\" tags in the file.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the operating system requires users to supply a password for privilege escalation.\n\nCheck the configuration of the \"/etc/sudoers\" and \"/etc/sudoers.d/*\" files with the following command:\n\n$ sudo grep -ir nopasswd /etc/sudoers /etc/sudoers.d\n\nIf any occurrences of \"NOPASSWD\" are returned from the command and have not been documented with the Information System Security Officer (ISSO) as an organizationally defined administrative group utilizing MFA, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_7_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Without re-authentication, users may access resources or perform tasks for which they do not have authorization. \n\nWhen operating systems provide the capability to escalate a functional capability, it is critical the user re-authenticate.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000373-GPOS-00156, SRG-OS-000373-GPOS-00157, SRG-OS-000373-GPOS-00158","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-86571","V-71947"],"ccis":["CCI-002038"],"reference_identifier":"2899","uuid":"441236bf-2914-41ce-8592-906332dcb1b7","stig_uuid":"aa379772-3679-4074-8a4e-5b09f41d3e8e","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_Dom0_RHEL7_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 2\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nThe automated check found NOPASSWD entries in /etc/sudoers or /etc/sudoers.d/ on this XCP-ng Dom0 system. This allows users to execute privileged commands without authentication. Remediation: Remove all NOPASSWD tags from sudoers files and replace with PASSWD (or remove the tag entirely). Finding: Open.\n        \n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_Dom0_RHEL7_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: 0ED6C0CB044620D6FCDEB1EEF94719B82DAE2EE8\n~~~~~\nV-204429 - Users Must Provide Password for Privilege Escalation\n============================================================\n\nCommand: grep -ir NOPASSWD /etc/sudoers /etc/sudoers.d/\nResult: /etc/sudoers:# %wheel\tALL=(ALL)\tNOPASSWD: ALL\n\nFAIL: NOPASSWD entries found in sudoers configuration:\n  /etc/sudoers:# %wheel\tALL=(ALL)\tNOPASSWD: ALL\nRemediation: Remove NOPASSWD from sudoers entries or document with ISSO.\n"},{"group_id_src":"V-204430","group_tree":[{"id":"V-204430","title":"SRG-OS-000373-GPOS-00156","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-204430","severity":"medium","group_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must be configured so that users must re-authenticate for privilege escalation.","rule_id_src":"SV-204430r987879_rule","rule_id":"SV-204430r987879","rule_version":"RHEL-07-010350","rule_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must be configured so that users must re-authenticate for privilege escalation.","fix_text":"Configure the operating system to require users to reauthenticate for privilege escalation.\n\nCheck the configuration of the \"/etc/sudoers\" file with the following command:\n\n# visudo\nRemove any occurrences of \"!authenticate\" tags in the file.\n\nCheck the configuration of the \"/etc/sudoers.d/*\" files with the following command:\n\n# grep -i authenticate /etc/sudoers /etc/sudoers.d/*\nRemove any occurrences of \"!authenticate\" tags in the file(s).","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the operating system requires users to reauthenticate for privilege escalation.\n\nCheck the configuration of the \"/etc/sudoers\" and \"/etc/sudoers.d/*\" files with the following command:\n\n# grep -i authenticate /etc/sudoers /etc/sudoers.d/*\n\nIf any uncommented line is found with a \"!authenticate\" tag, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_7_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Without re-authentication, users may access resources or perform tasks for which they do not have authorization. \n\nWhen operating systems provide the capability to escalate a functional capability, it is critical the user reauthenticate.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000373-GPOS-00156, SRG-OS-000373-GPOS-00157, SRG-OS-000373-GPOS-00158","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-86573","V-71949"],"ccis":["CCI-002038"],"reference_identifier":"2899","uuid":"aa762084-94d4-4b54-b69d-44c6ce6e7520","stig_uuid":"aa379772-3679-4074-8a4e-5b09f41d3e8e","status":"not_a_finding","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_Dom0_RHEL7_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 1\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nThe automated check verified that no !authenticate entries exist in /etc/sudoers or /etc/sudoers.d/ on this XCP-ng Dom0 system, ensuring users must re-authenticate when escalating privileges. Finding: Not a Finding.\n        \n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_Dom0_RHEL7_Checks) found this to be NOT A FINDING on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: 29B990DE3FA5A50D10C345DDE340C9E2A70B78EC\n~~~~~\nV-204430 - Users Must Re-authenticate for Privilege Escalation\n============================================================\n\nCommand: grep -ir authenticate /etc/sudoers /etc/sudoers.d/\nResult: \n\nPASS: No !authenticate entries found in sudoers configuration.\n"},{"group_id_src":"V-204431","group_tree":[{"id":"V-204431","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00226","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-204431","severity":"medium","group_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must be configured so that the delay between logon prompts following a failed console logon attempt is at least four seconds.","rule_id_src":"SV-204431r991588_rule","rule_id":"SV-204431r991588","rule_version":"RHEL-07-010430","rule_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must be configured so that the delay between logon prompts following a failed console logon attempt is at least four seconds.","fix_text":"Configure the operating system to enforce a delay of at least four seconds between logon prompts following a failed console logon attempt.\n\nModify the \"/etc/login.defs\" file to set the \"FAIL_DELAY\" parameter to \"4\" or greater:\n\nFAIL_DELAY 4","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the operating system enforces a delay of at least four seconds between console logon prompts following a failed logon attempt.\n\nCheck the value of the \"fail_delay\" parameter in the \"/etc/login.defs\" file with the following command:\n\n# grep -i fail_delay /etc/login.defs\nFAIL_DELAY 4\n\nIf the value of \"FAIL_DELAY\" is not set to \"4\" or greater, or the line is commented out, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_7_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Configuring the operating system to implement organization-wide security implementation guides and security checklists verifies compliance with federal standards and establishes a common security baseline across DoD that reflects the most restrictive security posture consistent with operational requirements.\n\nConfiguration settings are the set of parameters that can be changed in hardware, software, or firmware components of the system that affect the security posture and/or functionality of the system. Security-related parameters are those parameters impacting the security state of the system, including the parameters required to satisfy other security control requirements. Security-related parameters include, for example, registry settings; account, file, and directory permission settings; and settings for functions, ports, protocols, services, and remote connections.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-86575","V-71951"],"ccis":["CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"2899","uuid":"4e1dfa53-8e4a-462d-87fd-6c3c8971390a","stig_uuid":"aa379772-3679-4074-8a4e-5b09f41d3e8e","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_Dom0_RHEL7_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 2\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nThe automated check found that FAIL_DELAY is not configured or set below 4 in /etc/login.defs on this XCP-ng Dom0 system. Remediation: Set FAIL_DELAY 4 (or greater) in /etc/login.defs. Finding: Open.\n        \n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_Dom0_RHEL7_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: C58734AAA30976078EFD5D3282F240CA5E98268A\n~~~~~\nV-204431 - Failed Logon Delay Must Be 4+ Seconds (FAIL_DELAY)\n============================================================\n\nCommand: grep -i fail_delay /etc/login.defs\nResult: \n\nFAIL: FAIL_DELAY is not configured in /etc/login.defs.\nRemediation: Add FAIL_DELAY 4 to /etc/login.defs\n"},{"group_id_src":"V-204432","group_tree":[{"id":"V-204432","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00229","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-204432","severity":"high","group_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must not allow an unattended or automatic logon to the system via a graphical user interface.","rule_id_src":"SV-204432r991591_rule","rule_id":"SV-204432r991591","rule_version":"RHEL-07-010440","rule_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must not allow an unattended or automatic logon to the system via a graphical user interface.","fix_text":"Configure the operating system to not allow an unattended or automatic logon to the system via a graphical user interface.\n\nNote: If the system does not have GNOME installed, this requirement is Not Applicable.\n\nAdd or edit the line for the \"AutomaticLoginEnable\" parameter in the [daemon] section of the \"/etc/gdm/custom.conf\" file to \"false\":\n\n[daemon]\nAutomaticLoginEnable=false","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the operating system does not allow an unattended or automatic logon to the system via a graphical user interface.\n\nNote: If the system does not have GNOME installed, this requirement is Not Applicable. \n\nCheck for the value of the \"AutomaticLoginEnable\" in the \"/etc/gdm/custom.conf\" file with the following command:\n\n# grep -i automaticloginenable /etc/gdm/custom.conf\nAutomaticLoginEnable=false\n\nIf the value of \"AutomaticLoginEnable\" is not set to \"false\", this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_7_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Failure to restrict system access to authenticated users negatively impacts operating system security.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-86577","V-71953"],"ccis":["CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"2899","uuid":"86c7a33e-a932-464e-ac50-9a14d4dfb3f6","stig_uuid":"aa379772-3679-4074-8a4e-5b09f41d3e8e","status":"not_applicable","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_Dom0_RHEL7_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 3\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nGNOME desktop environment is not installed on this XCP-ng Dom0 system. XCP-ng Dom0 is a server-oriented hypervisor management domain that typically operates without a graphical user interface. Since the graphical user interface requirement does not apply to this system configuration, per the STIG guidance ('if the system does not have GNOME installed, this requirement is Not Applicable'), this check is Not Applicable.\n        \n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_Dom0_RHEL7_Checks) found this to be NOT APPLICABLE on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: 9942B69D844E3AF15FE483146ABCA8941993AFCD\n~~~~~\nV-204432 - No Unattended/Automatic GUI Login\n============================================================\n\nGNOME desktop is not installed on this XCP-ng Dom0 system.\nThis check is Not Applicable.\n"},{"group_id_src":"V-204433","group_tree":[{"id":"V-204433","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00229","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-204433","severity":"high","group_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must not allow an unrestricted logon to the system.","rule_id_src":"SV-204433r991591_rule","rule_id":"SV-204433r991591","rule_version":"RHEL-07-010450","rule_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must not allow an unrestricted logon to the system.","fix_text":"Configure the operating system to not allow an unrestricted account to log on to the system via a graphical user interface.\n\nNote: If the system does not have GNOME installed, this requirement is Not Applicable.\n\nAdd or edit the line for the \"TimedLoginEnable\" parameter in the [daemon] section of the \"/etc/gdm/custom.conf\" file to \"false\":\n\n[daemon]\nTimedLoginEnable=false","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the operating system does not allow an unrestricted logon to the system via a graphical user interface.\n\nNote: If the system does not have GNOME installed, this requirement is Not Applicable. \n\nCheck for the value of the \"TimedLoginEnable\" parameter in \"/etc/gdm/custom.conf\" file with the following command:\n\n# grep -i timedloginenable /etc/gdm/custom.conf\nTimedLoginEnable=false\n\nIf the value of \"TimedLoginEnable\" is not set to \"false\", this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_7_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Failure to restrict system access to authenticated users negatively impacts operating system security.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-86579","V-71955"],"ccis":["CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"2899","uuid":"a98a20fb-74c1-4a0f-8e45-6c2ce9adc566","stig_uuid":"aa379772-3679-4074-8a4e-5b09f41d3e8e","status":"not_applicable","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_Dom0_RHEL7_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 3\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nGNOME desktop environment is not installed on this XCP-ng Dom0 system. XCP-ng Dom0 is a server-oriented hypervisor management domain that typically operates without a graphical user interface. Since the graphical user interface requirement does not apply, per the STIG guidance ('if the system does not have GNOME installed, this requirement is Not Applicable'), this check is Not Applicable.\n        \n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_Dom0_RHEL7_Checks) found this to be NOT APPLICABLE on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: 6EF419A8BF6E4FA90FFF3271F662C28462B40C0A\n~~~~~\nV-204433 - No Unrestricted (Timed) GUI Login\n============================================================\n\nGNOME desktop is not installed on this XCP-ng Dom0 system.\nThis check is Not Applicable.\n"},{"group_id_src":"V-204434","group_tree":[{"id":"V-204434","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00229","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-204434","severity":"medium","group_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must not allow users to override SSH environment variables.","rule_id_src":"SV-204434r991591_rule","rule_id":"SV-204434r991591","rule_version":"RHEL-07-010460","rule_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must not allow users to override SSH environment variables.","fix_text":"Configure the operating system to not allow users to override environment variables to the SSH daemon.\n\nEdit the \"/etc/ssh/sshd_config\" file to uncomment or add the line for \"PermitUserEnvironment\" keyword and set the value to \"no\":\n\nPermitUserEnvironment no\n\nThe SSH service must be restarted for changes to take effect.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the operating system does not allow users to override environment variables to the SSH daemon.\n\nCheck for the value of the \"PermitUserEnvironment\" keyword with the following command:\n\n# grep -i permituserenvironment /etc/ssh/sshd_config\nPermitUserEnvironment no\n\nIf the \"PermitUserEnvironment\" keyword is not set to \"no\", is missing, or is commented out, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_7_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Failure to restrict system access to authenticated users negatively impacts operating system security.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-86581","V-71957"],"ccis":["CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"2899","uuid":"e794283e-2f9a-4426-88f4-64c2142a5ef1","stig_uuid":"aa379772-3679-4074-8a4e-5b09f41d3e8e","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_Dom0_RHEL7_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 2\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nThe automated check found that PermitUserEnvironment is not set to no in /etc/ssh/sshd_config on this XCP-ng Dom0 system. Remediation: Set PermitUserEnvironment no in /etc/ssh/sshd_config and restart sshd. Finding: Open.\n        \n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_Dom0_RHEL7_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: DB223415C19C4D077CDB4E611242F5FEECD20EC0\n~~~~~\nV-204434 - SSH Must Not Allow User Environment Override\n============================================================\n\nCommand: grep -i permituserenvironment /etc/ssh/sshd_config\nResult: #PermitUserEnvironment no\n\nFAIL: PermitUserEnvironment is not set to no in sshd_config.\nRemediation: Set PermitUserEnvironment no in /etc/ssh/sshd_config\n"},{"group_id_src":"V-204435","group_tree":[{"id":"V-204435","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00229","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-204435","severity":"medium","group_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must not allow a non-certificate trusted host SSH logon to the system.","rule_id_src":"SV-204435r991591_rule","rule_id":"SV-204435r991591","rule_version":"RHEL-07-010470","rule_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must not allow a non-certificate trusted host SSH logon to the system.","fix_text":"Configure the operating system to not allow a non-certificate trusted host SSH logon to the system.\n\nEdit the \"/etc/ssh/sshd_config\" file to uncomment or add the line for \"HostbasedAuthentication\" keyword and set the value to \"no\":\n\nHostbasedAuthentication no\n\nThe SSH service must be restarted for changes to take effect.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the operating system does not allow a non-certificate trusted host SSH logon to the system.\n\nCheck for the value of the \"HostbasedAuthentication\" keyword with the following command:\n\n# grep -i hostbasedauthentication /etc/ssh/sshd_config\nHostbasedAuthentication no\n\nIf the \"HostbasedAuthentication\" keyword is not set to \"no\", is missing, or is commented out, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_7_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Failure to restrict system access to authenticated users negatively impacts operating system security.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-86583","V-71959"],"ccis":["CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"2899","uuid":"75f3613f-747a-4061-9005-5dcb8b540360","stig_uuid":"aa379772-3679-4074-8a4e-5b09f41d3e8e","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_Dom0_RHEL7_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 2\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nThe automated check found that HostbasedAuthentication is not set to no in /etc/ssh/sshd_config on this XCP-ng Dom0 system. Remediation: Set HostbasedAuthentication no in /etc/ssh/sshd_config and restart sshd. Finding: Open.\n        \n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_Dom0_RHEL7_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: 462C340432E9903C15003BBBB8BB0BEF742567FB\n~~~~~\nV-204435 - SSH Must Not Allow Host-based Authentication\n============================================================\n\nCommand: grep -i hostbasedauthentication /etc/ssh/sshd_config\nResult: #HostbasedAuthentication no\n# HostbasedAuthentication\n\nFAIL: HostbasedAuthentication is not set to no in sshd_config.\nRemediation: Set HostbasedAuthentication no in /etc/ssh/sshd_config\n"},{"group_id_src":"V-204437","group_tree":[{"id":"V-204437","title":"SRG-OS-000080-GPOS-00048","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-204437","severity":"medium","group_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must require authentication upon booting into single-user and maintenance modes.","rule_id_src":"SV-204437r958472_rule","rule_id":"SV-204437r958472","rule_version":"RHEL-07-010481","rule_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must require authentication upon booting into single-user and maintenance modes.","fix_text":"Configure the operating system to require authentication upon booting into single-user and maintenance modes.\n\nAdd or modify the \"ExecStart\" line in \"/usr/lib/systemd/system/rescue.service\" to include \"/usr/sbin/sulogin\":\n\nExecStart=-/bin/sh -c \"/usr/sbin/sulogin; /usr/bin/systemctl --fail --no-block default\"","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the operating system must require authentication upon booting into single-user and maintenance modes.\n\nCheck that the operating system requires authentication upon booting into single-user mode with the following command:\n\n# grep -i execstart /usr/lib/systemd/system/rescue.service | grep -i sulogin\n\nExecStart=-/bin/sh -c \"/usr/sbin/sulogin; /usr/bin/systemctl --fail --no-block default\"\n\nIf \"ExecStart\" does not have \"/usr/sbin/sulogin\" as an option, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_7_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"If the system does not require valid root authentication before it boots into single-user or maintenance mode, anyone who invokes single-user or maintenance mode is granted privileged access to all files on the system.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-92519","V-77823"],"ccis":["CCI-000213"],"reference_identifier":"2899","uuid":"f6be3f74-13a3-4b6c-bd64-1fd0159aca9b","stig_uuid":"aa379772-3679-4074-8a4e-5b09f41d3e8e","status":"not_a_finding","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_Dom0_RHEL7_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 1\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nThe automated check verified that the rescue.service unit file on this XCP-ng Dom0 system references /usr/sbin/sulogin or equivalent, requiring root authentication before granting access in single-user (rescue) mode. Finding: Not a Finding.\n        \n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_Dom0_RHEL7_Checks) found this to be NOT A FINDING on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: 93518635FF1CFDD5033FFC6FC168144BC9A8E385\n~~~~~\nV-204437 - Single-User Mode Must Require Authentication\n============================================================\n\nCommand: grep -i execstart /usr/lib/systemd/system/rescue.service\nResult: ExecStartPre=-/bin/plymouth quit\nExecStartPre=-/bin/echo -e 'Welcome to emergency mode! After logging in, type \"journalctl -xb\" to view\\\\nsystem logs, \"systemctl reboot\" to reboot, \"systemctl default\" or ^D to\\\\nboot into default mode.'\nExecStart=-/bin/sh -c \"/usr/sbin/sulogin; /usr/bin/systemctl --fail --no-block default\"\n\nPASS: rescue.service uses sulogin, requiring authentication for single-user mode.\n"},{"group_id_src":"V-204438","group_tree":[{"id":"V-204438","title":"SRG-OS-000080-GPOS-00048","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-204438","severity":"high","group_title":"Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating systems version 7.2 or newer with a Basic Input/Output System (BIOS) must require authentication upon booting into single-user and maintenance modes.","rule_id_src":"SV-204438r958472_rule","rule_id":"SV-204438r958472","rule_version":"RHEL-07-010482","rule_title":"Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating systems version 7.2 or newer with a Basic Input/Output System (BIOS) must require authentication upon booting into single-user and maintenance modes.","fix_text":"Configure the system to encrypt the boot password for the grub superusers account with the grub2-setpassword command, which creates/overwrites the /boot/grub2/user.cfg file.\n\nGenerate an encrypted grub2 password for the grub superusers account with the following command:\n  \n$ sudo grub2-setpassword\nEnter password:\nConfirm password:","weight":"10.0","check_content":"For systems that use UEFI, this is Not Applicable.\n\nFor systems that are running a version of RHEL prior to 7.2, this is Not Applicable.\n\nCheck to see if an encrypted grub superusers password is set. On systems that use a BIOS, use the following command:\n\n$ sudo grep -iw grub2_password /boot/grub2/user.cfg\nGRUB2_PASSWORD=grub.pbkdf2.sha512.[password_hash]\n\nIf the grub superusers password does not begin with \"grub.pbkdf2.sha512\", this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_7_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"If the system does not require valid authentication before it boots into single-user or maintenance mode, anyone who invokes single-user or maintenance mode is granted privileged access to all files on the system. GRUB 2 is the default boot loader for RHEL 7 and is designed to require a password to boot into single-user mode or make modifications to the boot menu.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-95717","V-81005"],"ccis":["CCI-000213"],"reference_identifier":"2899","uuid":"cc237a61-70ab-42f4-9544-ef7e68e4bfe3","stig_uuid":"aa379772-3679-4074-8a4e-5b09f41d3e8e","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_Dom0_RHEL7_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 2\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nThe automated check found that this XCP-ng Dom0 (RHEL 7-based) system with BIOS firmware does not have a GRUB2 superuser password configured or the password is not using PBKDF2-SHA512 encryption. Per RHEL 7 STIG requirement RHEL-07-010482, BIOS systems must require authentication to boot into single-user and maintenance modes. Without boot authentication, an attacker with physical or console access could boot into single-user mode and gain root access without credentials. Remediation: (1) Run 'grub2-setpassword' to set an encrypted GRUB2 superuser password. (2) Verify the password is set: grep -iw grub2_password /boot/grub2/user.cfg. The system administrator must configure boot authentication immediately.\n        \n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_Dom0_RHEL7_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: A85941E76F179A38C9DEDD61871DD47845C8D2D6\n~~~~~\nV-204438 - BIOS GRUB2 Boot Authentication\n============================================================\n\nFirmware: BIOS\nCommand: grep -iw grub2_password /boot/grub2/user.cfg\nResult: \n\nFAIL: GRUB2 superuser password not found or not using PBKDF2-SHA512.\nRemediation: Run 'grub2-setpassword' to set an encrypted boot password.\n"},{"group_id_src":"V-204440","group_tree":[{"id":"V-204440","title":"SRG-OS-000080-GPOS-00048","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-204440","severity":"high","group_title":"Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating systems version 7.2 or newer using Unified Extensible Firmware Interface (UEFI) must require authentication upon booting into single-user and maintenance modes.","rule_id_src":"SV-204440r958472_rule","rule_id":"SV-204440r958472","rule_version":"RHEL-07-010491","rule_title":"Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating systems version 7.2 or newer using Unified Extensible Firmware Interface (UEFI) must require authentication upon booting into single-user and maintenance modes.","fix_text":"Configure the system to encrypt the boot password for the grub superusers account with the grub2-setpassword command, which creates/overwrites the /boot/efi/EFI/redhat/user.cfg file.\n\nGenerate an encrypted grub2 password for the grub superusers account with the following command:\n\n$ sudo grub2-setpassword\nEnter password:\nConfirm password:","weight":"10.0","check_content":"For systems that use BIOS, this is Not Applicable.\n\nFor systems that are running a version of RHEL prior to 7.2, this is Not Applicable.\n\nCheck to see if an encrypted grub superusers password is set. On systems that use UEFI, use the following command:\n\n$ sudo grep -iw grub2_password /boot/efi/EFI/redhat/user.cfg\nGRUB2_PASSWORD=grub.pbkdf2.sha512.[password_hash]\n\nIf the grub superusers password does not begin with \"grub.pbkdf2.sha512\", this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_7_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"If the system does not require valid authentication before it boots into single-user or maintenance mode, anyone who invokes single-user or maintenance mode is granted privileged access to all files on the system. GRUB 2 is the default boot loader for RHEL 7 and is designed to require a password to boot into single-user mode or make modifications to the boot menu.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-95719","V-81007"],"ccis":["CCI-000213"],"reference_identifier":"2899","uuid":"29beece7-90bc-420c-a719-ab90d54c8107","stig_uuid":"aa379772-3679-4074-8a4e-5b09f41d3e8e","status":"not_applicable","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_Dom0_RHEL7_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 3\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nThis system uses BIOS firmware, not UEFI. Per the STIG guidance ('For systems that use BIOS, this is Not Applicable'), this UEFI-specific GRUB2 authentication check does not apply. The corresponding BIOS check (V-204438) applies instead.\n        \n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_Dom0_RHEL7_Checks) found this to be NOT APPLICABLE on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: 8F35FD27258687C212E066DF8E657F0063ECD51B\n~~~~~\nV-204440 - UEFI GRUB2 Boot Authentication\n============================================================\n\nThis system uses BIOS firmware (not UEFI).\nThis check is Not Applicable for BIOS systems.\n"},{"group_id_src":"V-204441","group_tree":[{"id":"V-204441","title":"SRG-OS-000104-GPOS-00051","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-204441","severity":"medium","group_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must uniquely identify and must authenticate organizational users (or processes acting on behalf of organizational users) using multifactor authentication.","rule_id_src":"SV-204441r958482_rule","rule_id":"SV-204441r958482","rule_version":"RHEL-07-010500","rule_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must uniquely identify and must authenticate organizational users (or processes acting on behalf of organizational users) using multifactor authentication.","fix_text":"Configure the operating system to require individuals to be authenticated with a multifactor authenticator.\n\nEnable smartcard logons with the following commands:\n\n# authconfig --enablesmartcard --smartcardaction=0 --update\n# authconfig --enablerequiresmartcard -update\n\nModify the \"/etc/pam_pkcs11/pkcs11_eventmgr.conf\" file to uncomment the following line:\n\n#/usr/X11R6/bin/xscreensaver-command -lock\n\nModify the \"/etc/pam_pkcs11/pam_pkcs11.conf\" file to use the cackey module if required.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the operating system requires multifactor authentication to uniquely identify organizational users using multifactor authentication.\n\nCheck to see if smartcard authentication is enforced on the system:\n\n# authconfig --test | grep \"pam_pkcs11 is enabled\"\n\nIf no results are returned, this is a finding.\n\n# authconfig --test | grep \"smartcard removal action\"\n\nIf \"smartcard removal action\" is blank, this is a finding.\n\n# authconfig --test | grep \"smartcard module\"\n\nIf any of the above checks are not configured, ask the administrator to indicate the AO-approved multifactor authentication in use and the configuration to support it. If there is no evidence of multifactor authentication, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_7_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"To assure accountability and prevent unauthenticated access, organizational users must be identified and authenticated to prevent potential misuse and compromise of the system.\n\nOrganizational users include organizational employees or individuals the organization deems to have equivalent status of employees (e.g., contractors). Organizational users (and processes acting on behalf of users) must be uniquely identified and authenticated to all accesses, except for the following:\n\n1) Accesses explicitly identified and documented by the organization. Organizations document specific user actions that can be performed on the information system without identification or authentication; \n\nand\n\n2) Accesses that occur through authorized use of group authenticators without individual authentication. Organizations may require unique identification of individuals in group accounts (e.g., shared privilege accounts) or for detailed accountability of individual activity.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000104-GPOS-00051, SRG-OS-000106-GPOS-00053, SRG-OS-000107-GPOS-00054, SRG-OS-000109-GPOS-00056, SRG-OS-000108-GPOS-00055, SRG-OS-000108-GPOS-00057, SRG-OS-000108-GPOS-00058","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-86589","V-71965"],"ccis":["CCI-000766"],"reference_identifier":"2899","uuid":"b2d4e28d-4cfe-4f01-a0dd-602ea7d4cb27","stig_uuid":"aa379772-3679-4074-8a4e-5b09f41d3e8e","status":"not_a_finding","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_Dom0_RHEL7_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 1\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nThe automated check verified that multifactor authentication is configured on this XCP-ng Dom0 system via pam_pkcs11.so or equivalent smartcard/PKI module. Finding: Not a Finding.\n        \n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_Dom0_RHEL7_Checks) found this to be NOT A FINDING on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: AAF183D41E13E3C2397A587068ABC3103B6438CD\n~~~~~\nV-204441 - Must Authenticate Users via MFA/Smartcard\n============================================================\n\nCommand: which authconfig\nResult: authconfig is not installed\n\nFallback: grep -r pam_pkcs11 /etc/pam.d/\nResult: /etc/pam.d/smartcard-auth:auth        [success=done ignore=ignore default=die] pam_pkcs11.so wait_for_card\n/etc/pam.d/smartcard-auth:password    optional      pam_pkcs11.so\n\nPASS: Smartcard authentication (pam_pkcs11) is enabled.\n"},{"group_id_src":"V-204442","group_tree":[{"id":"V-204442","title":"SRG-OS-000095-GPOS-00049","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-204442","severity":"high","group_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must not have the rsh-server package installed.","rule_id_src":"SV-204442r958478_rule","rule_id":"SV-204442r958478","rule_version":"RHEL-07-020000","rule_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must not have the rsh-server package installed.","fix_text":"Configure the operating system to disable non-essential capabilities by removing the rsh-server package from the system with the following command:\n\n# yum remove rsh-server","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Check to see if the rsh-server package is installed with the following command:\n\n# yum list installed rsh-server\n\nIf the rsh-server package is installed, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_7_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"It is detrimental for operating systems to provide, or install by default, functionality exceeding requirements or mission objectives. These unnecessary capabilities or services are often overlooked and therefore may remain unsecured. They increase the risk to the platform by providing additional attack vectors.\n\nOperating systems are capable of providing a wide variety of functions and services. Some of the functions and services, provided by default, may not be necessary to support essential organizational operations (e.g., key missions, functions).\n\nThe rsh-server service provides an unencrypted remote access service that does not provide for the confidentiality and integrity of user passwords or the remote session and has very weak authentication.\n\nIf a privileged user were to log on using this service, the privileged user password could be compromised.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-86591","V-71967"],"ccis":["CCI-000381"],"reference_identifier":"2899","uuid":"fb0f014d-5511-4e30-8d03-c54aa6335790","stig_uuid":"aa379772-3679-4074-8a4e-5b09f41d3e8e","status":"not_a_finding","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_Dom0_RHEL7_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 1\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nThe automated check verified that the rsh-server package is not installed on this XCP-ng Dom0 (RHEL 7-based) system. The scan executed 'rpm -q rsh-server' and confirmed the package is not present. The rsh (Remote Shell) service provides unencrypted remote access that does not protect the confidentiality or integrity of transmitted data. Its absence confirms compliance with RHEL 7 STIG requirement RHEL-07-020000. XCP-ng Dom0 uses SSH for all remote administration, which provides encrypted communications. Finding: Not a Finding.\n        \n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_Dom0_RHEL7_Checks) found this to be NOT A FINDING on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: 931606908CADB6558A2C44F765751CC7EB0DFAF2\n~~~~~\nV-204442 - rsh-server Package Must Not Be Installed\n============================================================\n\nCommand: rpm -q rsh-server\nResult: package rsh-server is not installed\n\nPASS: The rsh-server package is not installed.\n"},{"group_id_src":"V-204443","group_tree":[{"id":"V-204443","title":"SRG-OS-000095-GPOS-00049","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-204443","severity":"high","group_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must not have the ypserv package installed.","rule_id_src":"SV-204443r958478_rule","rule_id":"SV-204443r958478","rule_version":"RHEL-07-020010","rule_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must not have the ypserv package installed.","fix_text":"Configure the operating system to disable non-essential capabilities by removing the \"ypserv\" package from the system with the following command:\n\n# yum remove ypserv","weight":"10.0","check_content":"The NIS service provides an unencrypted authentication service that does not provide for the confidentiality and integrity of user passwords or the remote session.\n\nCheck to see if the \"ypserve\" package is installed with the following command:\n\n# yum list installed ypserv\n\nIf the \"ypserv\" package is installed, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_7_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Removing the \"ypserv\" package decreases the risk of the accidental (or intentional) activation of NIS or NIS+ services.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-86593","V-71969"],"ccis":["CCI-000381"],"reference_identifier":"2899","uuid":"ad5f608e-25b4-4efa-a162-1b20059c75e9","stig_uuid":"aa379772-3679-4074-8a4e-5b09f41d3e8e","status":"not_a_finding","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_Dom0_RHEL7_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 1\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nThe automated check verified that the ypserv (NIS server) package is not installed on this XCP-ng Dom0 (RHEL 7-based) system. The scan executed 'rpm -q ypserv' and confirmed the package is not present. NIS (Network Information Service) provides an unencrypted authentication service that does not protect the confidentiality or integrity of user passwords or remote sessions. Its absence confirms compliance with RHEL 7 STIG requirement RHEL-07-020010. XCP-ng Dom0 uses modern authentication methods that provide encrypted credential handling. Finding: Not a Finding.\n        \n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_Dom0_RHEL7_Checks) found this to be NOT A FINDING on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: ADADCB6B216E67D237DAC1FC0B7625E9CD2D5A86\n~~~~~\nV-204443 - ypserv Package Must Not Be Installed\n============================================================\n\nCommand: rpm -q ypserv\nResult: package ypserv is not installed\n\nPASS: The ypserv (NIS server) package is not installed.\n"},{"group_id_src":"V-204444","group_tree":[{"id":"V-204444","title":"SRG-OS-000324-GPOS-00125","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-204444","severity":"medium","group_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must prevent nonprivileged users from executing privileged functions to include disabling, circumventing, or altering implemented security safeguards/countermeasures.","rule_id_src":"SV-204444r958726_rule","rule_id":"SV-204444r958726","rule_version":"RHEL-07-020020","rule_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must prevent nonprivileged users from executing privileged functions to include disabling, circumventing, or altering implemented security safeguards/countermeasures.","fix_text":"Configure the operating system to prevent non-privileged users from executing privileged functions to include disabling, circumventing, or altering implemented security safeguards/countermeasures.\n\nUse the following command to map a new user to the \"staff_u\" SELinux user:\n\n     $ sudo semanage login -a -s staff_u <username>\n\nUse the following command to map an existing user to the \"staff_u\" SELinux user:\n\n     $ sudo semanage login -m -s staff_u <username>\n\nUse the following command to map a new user to the \"user_u\" SELinux user:\n\n     $ sudo semanage login -a -s user_u <username>\n\nUse the following command to map an existing user to the \"user_u\" SELinux user:\n\n     $ sudo semanage login -m -s user_u <username>","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the operating system prevents non-privileged users from executing privileged functions to include disabling, circumventing, or altering implemented security safeguards/countermeasures.\n\nGet a list of authorized users for the system.\n\nCheck the list against the system by using the following command:\n\n     $ sudo semanage login -l | more\n\n     Login Name    SELinux User    MLS/MCS Range    Service\n\n     __default__   user_u                 s0-s0:c0.c1023        *\n     root                   unconfined_u  s0-s0:c0.c1023        *\n     system_u        system_u           s0-s0:c0.c1023        *\n     joe                     staff_u                s0-s0:c0.c1023        *\n\nAll administrators must be mapped to the , \"staff_u\", or an appropriately tailored confined SELinux user as defined by the organization.\n\nAll authorized non-administrative users must be mapped to the \"user_u\" SELinux user.\n\nIf they are not mapped in this way, this is a finding.\nIf administrator accounts are mapped to the \"sysadm_u\" SELinux user and are not documented as an operational requirement with the ISSO, this is a finding.\nIf administrator accounts are mapped to the \"sysadm_u\" SELinux user and are documented as an operational requirement with the ISSO, this can be downgraded to a CAT III.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_7_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Preventing nonprivileged users from executing privileged functions mitigates the risk that unauthorized individuals or processes may gain unnecessary access to information or privileges.\n\nPrivileged functions include, for example, establishing accounts, performing system integrity checks, or administering cryptographic key management activities. Nonprivileged users are individuals who do not possess appropriate authorizations. Circumventing intrusion detection and prevention mechanisms or malicious code protection mechanisms are examples of privileged functions that require protection from nonprivileged users.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-86595","V-71971"],"ccis":["CCI-002165","CCI-002235"],"reference_identifier":"2899","uuid":"078e47bb-928f-4c68-a8cc-e218b34de3b3","stig_uuid":"aa379772-3679-4074-8a4e-5b09f41d3e8e","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_Dom0_RHEL7_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 2\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nThe automated check found that SELinux is not in enforcing mode on this XCP-ng Dom0 system. XCP-ng typically ships with SELinux disabled or in permissive mode, which does not meet the RHEL 7 STIG requirement. Remediation: Set SELINUX=enforcing in /etc/selinux/config and reboot. Note: Enabling SELinux on XCP-ng may cause operational issues and should be thoroughly tested. Finding: Open.\n        \n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_Dom0_RHEL7_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: 2D0EF4E759D3AAFF95B12C8B1DEDDF8CDD42D557\n~~~~~\nV-204444 - Prevent Nonprivileged Users from Executing Privileged Functions\n============================================================\n\nCommand: getenforce\nResult: Disabled\n\nCommand: grep SELINUX= /etc/selinux/config\nResult: /usr/bin/grep: /etc/selinux/config: No such file or directory\n\nFAIL: SELinux is not in Enforcing mode (current: Disabled).\nNote: XCP-ng Dom0 typically operates with SELinux disabled.\nRemediation: Set SELINUX=enforcing in /etc/selinux/config and reboot.\n"},{"group_id_src":"V-204445","group_tree":[{"id":"V-204445","title":"SRG-OS-000363-GPOS-00150","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-204445","severity":"medium","group_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must be configured so that a file integrity tool verifies the baseline operating system configuration at least weekly.","rule_id_src":"SV-204445r958794_rule","rule_id":"SV-204445r958794","rule_version":"RHEL-07-020030","rule_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must be configured so that a file integrity tool verifies the baseline operating system configuration at least weekly.","fix_text":"Configure the file integrity tool to run automatically on the system at least weekly. \n\nThe following example output is generic. It will set cron to run AIDE daily, but other file integrity tools may be used:  \n\n     # more /etc/cron.daily/aide\n     #!/bin/bash\n\n     /usr/sbin/aide --check | /bin/mail -s \"$HOSTNAME - Daily AIDE integrity check run\" root@example_server_name.mil\n\nNote: Per requirement RHEL-07-020028, the \"mailx\" package must be installed on the system to enable email functionality.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the operating system routinely checks the baseline configuration for unauthorized changes.\n\nNote: A file integrity tool other than Advanced Intrusion Detection Environment (AIDE) may be used, but the tool must be executed at least once per week.\n\nCheck for the presence of a cron job running daily or weekly on the system that executes AIDE daily to scan for changes to the system baseline. The command used in the example will use a daily occurrence.\n\nCheck the cron directories for a script file controlling the execution of the file integrity application. For example, if AIDE is installed on the system, use the following command:\n\n     # ls -al /etc/cron.* | grep aide\n     -rwxr-xr-x 1 root root 602 Mar 6 20:02 aide\n\n     # grep aide /etc/crontab /var/spool/cron/root\n     /etc/crontab: 30 04 * * * root /usr/sbin/aide  --check\n     /var/spool/cron/root: 30 04 * * * /usr/sbin/aide  --check\n\nIf the file integrity application does not exist, or a script file controlling the execution of the file integrity application does not exist, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_7_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Unauthorized changes to the baseline configuration could make the system vulnerable to various attacks or allow unauthorized access to the operating system. Changes to operating system configurations can have unintended side effects, some of which may be relevant to security.\n\nDetecting such changes and providing an automated response can help avoid unintended, negative consequences that could ultimately affect the security state of the operating system. The operating system's Information System Security Manager (ISSM)/Information System Security Officer (ISSO) and System Administrators (SAs) must be notified via email and/or monitoring system trap when there is an unauthorized modification of a configuration item.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-86597","V-71973"],"ccis":["CCI-001744"],"reference_identifier":"2899","uuid":"c756cd26-b227-4d97-a27b-723ac6f78cac","stig_uuid":"aa379772-3679-4074-8a4e-5b09f41d3e8e","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_Dom0_RHEL7_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 2\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nThe automated check found that AIDE is either not installed or no periodic AIDE check is scheduled in cron on this XCP-ng Dom0 system. Remediation: Install AIDE (yum install aide), initialize the database (aide --init), and add a cron job for periodic checks (e.g., 0 5 * * * /usr/sbin/aide --check). Finding: Open.\n        \n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_Dom0_RHEL7_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: FB51C62CA112EEB5C470189A1113AA62E729EEA7\n~~~~~\nV-204445 - File Integrity Tool Must Verify Baseline (AIDE)\n============================================================\n\nCommand: rpm -q aide\nResult: package aide is not installed\n\nCommand: grep -r aide /etc/cron.daily/ /etc/cron.weekly/ /etc/crontab /var/spool/cron/\nResult: \n\nFAIL: AIDE is not installed.\nRemediation: yum install aide; aide --init; mv /var/lib/aide/aide.db.new.gz /var/lib/aide/aide.db.gz\n"},{"group_id_src":"V-204446","group_tree":[{"id":"V-204446","title":"SRG-OS-000363-GPOS-00150","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-204446","severity":"medium","group_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must be configured so that designated personnel are notified if baseline configurations are changed in an unauthorized manner.","rule_id_src":"SV-204446r958794_rule","rule_id":"SV-204446r958794","rule_version":"RHEL-07-020040","rule_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must be configured so that designated personnel are notified if baseline configurations are changed in an unauthorized manner.","fix_text":"Configure the operating system to notify designated personnel if baseline configurations are changed in an unauthorized manner. The AIDE tool can be configured to email designated personnel with the use of the cron system. \n\nThe following example output is generic. It will set cron to run AIDE daily and to send email at the completion of the analysis. \n\n     # more /etc/cron.daily/aide\n\n     /usr/sbin/aide --check | /bin/mail -s \"$HOSTNAME - Daily AIDE integrity check run\" root@example_server_name.mil\n\nNote: Per requirement RHEL-07-020028, the \"mailx\" package must be installed on the system to enable email functionality.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the operating system notifies designated personnel if baseline configurations are changed in an unauthorized manner.\n\nNote: A file integrity tool other than Advanced Intrusion Detection Environment (AIDE) may be used, but the tool must be executed and notify specified individuals via email or an alert.\n\nCheck for the presence of a cron job running routinely on the system that executes AIDE to scan for changes to the system baseline. The commands used in the example will use a daily occurrence.\n\nCheck the cron directories for a \"crontab\" script file controlling the execution of the file integrity application. For example, if AIDE is installed on the system, use the following command:\n    \n     # ls -al /etc/cron.* | grep aide\n     -rwxr-xr-x 1 root root 602 Mar 6 20:02 aide\n\n     # grep aide /etc/crontab /var/spool/cron/root\n     /etc/crontab: 30 04 * * * root /usr/sbin/aide  --check\n     /var/spool/cron/root: 30 04 * * * /usr/sbin/aide  --check\n\nAIDE does not have a configuration that will send a notification, so the cron job uses the mail application on the system to email the results of the file integrity run as in the following example:\n\n     # more /etc/cron.daily/aide\n     #!/bin/bash\n\n     /usr/sbin/aide --check | /bin/mail -s \"$HOSTNAME - Daily AIDE integrity check run\" root@example_server_name.mil\n\nIf the file integrity application does not notify designated personnel of changes, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_7_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Unauthorized changes to the baseline configuration could make the system vulnerable to various attacks or allow unauthorized access to the operating system. Changes to operating system configurations can have unintended side effects, some of which may be relevant to security.\n\nDetecting such changes and providing an automated response can help avoid unintended, negative consequences that could ultimately affect the security state of the operating system. The operating system's Information System Security Manager (ISSM)/Information System Security Officer (ISSO) and System Administrators (SAs) must be notified via email and/or monitoring system trap when there is an unauthorized modification of a configuration item.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-86599","V-71975"],"ccis":["CCI-001744"],"reference_identifier":"2899","uuid":"4797f0dc-b7dd-4ffe-8837-e5d1b6c06718","stig_uuid":"aa379772-3679-4074-8a4e-5b09f41d3e8e","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_Dom0_RHEL7_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 2\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nThe automated check found that AIDE notification is not configured on this XCP-ng Dom0 system. A file integrity check without notification does not ensure timely response to unauthorized changes. Remediation: Configure the AIDE cron job to include email notification (e.g., aide --check | /bin/mail -s \"AIDE Report\" admin@example.com). Finding: Open.\n        \n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_Dom0_RHEL7_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: 66561E222AB9620C3E2A3AE571243BBB77EB626A\n~~~~~\nV-204446 - File Integrity Tool Must Notify Personnel of Changes\n============================================================\n\nCommand: rpm -q aide\nResult: package aide is not installed\n\nCommand: grep -r aide /etc/cron.daily/ /etc/cron.weekly/ /etc/crontab /var/spool/cron/\nResult: \n\nFAIL: AIDE is not installed or not scheduled.\nRemediation: Install AIDE and configure cron job with email notification.\n"},{"group_id_src":"V-204447","group_tree":[{"id":"V-204447","title":"SRG-OS-000366-GPOS-00153","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-204447","severity":"high","group_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must prevent the installation of software, patches, service packs, device drivers, or operating system components from a repository without verification they have been digitally signed using a certificate that is issued by a Certificate Authority (CA) that is recognized and approved by the organization.","rule_id_src":"SV-204447r982212_rule","rule_id":"SV-204447r982212","rule_version":"RHEL-07-020050","rule_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must prevent the installation of software, patches, service packs, device drivers, or operating system components from a repository without verification they have been digitally signed using a certificate that is issued by a Certificate Authority (CA) that is recognized and approved by the organization.","fix_text":"Configure the operating system to verify the signature of packages from a repository prior to install by setting the following option in the \"/etc/yum.conf\" file:\n\ngpgcheck=1","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the operating system prevents the installation of patches, service packs, device drivers, or operating system components from a repository without verification that they have been digitally signed using a certificate that is recognized and approved by the organization.\n\nCheck that yum verifies the signature of packages from a repository prior to install with the following command:\n\n# grep gpgcheck /etc/yum.conf\ngpgcheck=1\n\nIf \"gpgcheck\" is not set to \"1\", or if options are missing or commented out, ask the System Administrator how the certificates for patches and other operating system components are verified. \n\nIf there is no process to validate certificates that is approved by the organization, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_7_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Changes to any software components can have significant effects on the overall security of the operating system. This requirement ensures the software has not been tampered with and that it has been provided by a trusted vendor.\n\nAccordingly, patches, service packs, device drivers, or operating system components must be signed with a certificate recognized and approved by the organization.\n\nVerifying the authenticity of the software prior to installation validates the integrity of the patch or upgrade received from a vendor. This verifies the software has not been tampered with and that it has been provided by a trusted vendor. Self-signed certificates are disallowed by this requirement. The operating system should not have to verify the software again. This requirement does not mandate DoD certificates for this purpose; however, the certificate used to verify the software must be from an approved CA.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-86601","V-71977"],"ccis":["CCI-001749"],"reference_identifier":"2899","uuid":"ccdc3039-6a18-4b0e-b551-adf11f4b891c","stig_uuid":"aa379772-3679-4074-8a4e-5b09f41d3e8e","status":"not_a_finding","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_Dom0_RHEL7_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 1\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nThe automated check verified that yum on this XCP-ng Dom0 (RHEL 7-based) system is configured to verify GPG signatures for repository packages. The scan confirmed that gpgcheck=1 is set in /etc/yum.conf. This ensures that all packages installed from repositories have been digitally signed by a trusted Certificate Authority, preventing installation of tampered or unauthorized software. This meets RHEL 7 STIG requirement RHEL-07-020050 for repository package signature verification. XCP-ng repositories use GPG-signed packages to maintain supply chain integrity. Finding: Not a Finding.\n        \n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_Dom0_RHEL7_Checks) found this to be NOT A FINDING on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: 589196356D09B93BB3E69F4B445CA88C507B600E\n~~~~~\nV-204447 - Repository GPG Signature Verification\n============================================================\n\nCommand: grep -i gpgcheck /etc/yum.conf\nResult: gpgcheck=1\n\nPASS: yum is configured to verify GPG signatures (gpgcheck=1).\n"},{"group_id_src":"V-204448","group_tree":[{"id":"V-204448","title":"SRG-OS-000366-GPOS-00153","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-204448","severity":"high","group_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must prevent the installation of software, patches, service packs, device drivers, or operating system components of local packages without verification they have been digitally signed using a certificate that is issued by a Certificate Authority (CA) that is recognized and approved by the organization.","rule_id_src":"SV-204448r982212_rule","rule_id":"SV-204448r982212","rule_version":"RHEL-07-020060","rule_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must prevent the installation of software, patches, service packs, device drivers, or operating system components of local packages without verification they have been digitally signed using a certificate that is issued by a Certificate Authority (CA) that is recognized and approved by the organization.","fix_text":"Configure the operating system to verify the signature of local packages prior to install by setting the following option in the \"/etc/yum.conf\" file:\n\nlocalpkg_gpgcheck=1","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the operating system prevents the installation of patches, service packs, device drivers, or operating system components of local packages without verification that they have been digitally signed using a certificate that is recognized and approved by the organization.\n\nCheck that yum verifies the signature of local packages prior to install with the following command:\n\n# grep localpkg_gpgcheck /etc/yum.conf\nlocalpkg_gpgcheck=1\n\nIf \"localpkg_gpgcheck\" is not set to \"1\", or if options are missing or commented out, ask the System Administrator how the signatures of local packages and other operating system components are verified. \n\nIf there is no process to validate the signatures of local packages that is approved by the organization, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_7_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Changes to any software components can have significant effects on the overall security of the operating system. This requirement ensures the software has not been tampered with and that it has been provided by a trusted vendor.\n\nAccordingly, patches, service packs, device drivers, or operating system components must be signed with a certificate recognized and approved by the organization.\n\nVerifying the authenticity of the software prior to installation validates the integrity of the patch or upgrade received from a vendor. This verifies the software has not been tampered with and that it has been provided by a trusted vendor. Self-signed certificates are disallowed by this requirement. The operating system should not have to verify the software again. This requirement does not mandate DoD certificates for this purpose; however, the certificate used to verify the software must be from an approved CA.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-86603","V-71979"],"ccis":["CCI-001749"],"reference_identifier":"2899","uuid":"99a2604c-cf6b-4839-ac54-a170e34e290c","stig_uuid":"aa379772-3679-4074-8a4e-5b09f41d3e8e","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_Dom0_RHEL7_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 2\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nThe automated check found that yum on this XCP-ng Dom0 (RHEL 7-based) system is not configured to verify GPG signatures for local packages. The localpkg_gpgcheck setting in /etc/yum.conf is not set to '1'. Per RHEL 7 STIG requirement RHEL-07-020060, the operating system must verify digital signatures before installing local packages. Without this check, manually-downloaded RPM files could be installed without signature verification. Remediation: (1) Edit /etc/yum.conf and set: localpkg_gpgcheck=1 in the [main] section. (2) Verify the change: grep localpkg_gpgcheck /etc/yum.conf. The system administrator must enable local package signature verification.\n        \n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_Dom0_RHEL7_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: D460C0785B6BA89DFC4853CB262B44E9970B5AA6\n~~~~~\nV-204448 - Local Package GPG Signature Verification\n============================================================\n\nCommand: grep -i localpkg_gpgcheck /etc/yum.conf\nResult: \n\nFAIL: localpkg_gpgcheck is not set to 1 in /etc/yum.conf.\nLocal packages may be installed without signature verification.\nRemediation: Set localpkg_gpgcheck=1 in /etc/yum.conf\n"},{"group_id_src":"V-204449","group_tree":[{"id":"V-204449","title":"SRG-OS-000114-GPOS-00059","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-204449","severity":"medium","group_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must be configured to disable USB mass storage.","rule_id_src":"SV-204449r958498_rule","rule_id":"SV-204449r958498","rule_version":"RHEL-07-020100","rule_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must be configured to disable USB mass storage.","fix_text":"Configure the operating system to disable the ability to use the USB Storage kernel module.\n\nCreate a file under \"/etc/modprobe.d\" with the following command:\n\n     # touch /etc/modprobe.d/usb-storage.conf\n\nAdd the following line to the created file:\n\n     install usb-storage /bin/false\n\nConfigure the operating system to disable the ability to use USB mass storage devices.\n\n     # vi /etc/modprobe.d/blacklist.conf\n\nAdd or update the line:\n\n     blacklist usb-storage","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the operating system disables the ability to load the USB Storage kernel module.\n\n     # grep -r usb-storage /etc/modprobe.d/* | grep -i \"/bin/false\" | grep -v \"^#\"\n     install usb-storage /bin/false\n\nIf the command does not return any output, or the line is commented out, and use of USB Storage is not documented with the Information System Security Officer (ISSO) as an operational requirement, this is a finding.\n\nVerify the operating system disables the ability to use USB mass storage devices.\n\nCheck to see if USB mass storage is disabled with the following command:\n\n     # grep usb-storage /etc/modprobe.d/* | grep -i \"blacklist\" | grep -v \"^#\"\n     blacklist usb-storage\n\nIf the command does not return any output or the output is not \"blacklist usb-storage\", and use of USB storage devices is not documented with the ISSO as an operational requirement, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_7_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"USB mass storage permits easy introduction of unknown devices, thereby facilitating malicious activity.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000114-GPOS-00059, SRG-OS-000378-GPOS-00163, SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-86607","V-71983"],"ccis":["CCI-000366","CCI-000778","CCI-001958"],"reference_identifier":"2899","uuid":"da712637-fb4e-4925-a9fe-3c8875e21bad","stig_uuid":"aa379772-3679-4074-8a4e-5b09f41d3e8e","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_Dom0_RHEL7_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 2\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nThe automated check found that the usb-storage kernel module is not disabled via modprobe configuration on this XCP-ng Dom0 system. Remediation: Create /etc/modprobe.d/usb-storage.conf with: install usb-storage /bin/true. Finding: Open.\n        \n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_Dom0_RHEL7_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: EB96A93D33B51D0B8D29EE7A4A0B8E021995D95D\n~~~~~\nV-204449 - USB Mass Storage Must Be Disabled\n============================================================\n\nCommand: grep -r usb-storage /etc/modprobe.d/\nResult: \n\nFAIL: USB mass storage kernel module is not disabled.\nRemediation: echo \"install usb-storage /bin/false\" > /etc/modprobe.d/usb-storage.conf\n"},{"group_id_src":"V-204450","group_tree":[{"id":"V-204450","title":"SRG-OS-000378-GPOS-00163","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-204450","severity":"medium","group_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must be configured so that the Datagram Congestion Control Protocol (DCCP) kernel module is disabled unless required.","rule_id_src":"SV-204450r958820_rule","rule_id":"SV-204450r958820","rule_version":"RHEL-07-020101","rule_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must be configured so that the Datagram Congestion Control Protocol (DCCP) kernel module is disabled unless required.","fix_text":"Configure the operating system to disable the ability to use the DCCP kernel module.\n\nCreate a file under \"/etc/modprobe.d\" with the following command:\n\n     # touch /etc/modprobe.d/dccp.conf\n\nAdd the following line to the created file:\n\n     install dccp /bin/false\n\nEnsure that the DCCP module is blacklisted: \n\n     # vi /etc/modprobe.d/blacklist.conf\n\nAdd or update the line:\n\n     blacklist dccp","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the operating system disables the ability to load the DCCP kernel module.\n\n     # grep -r dccp /etc/modprobe.d/* | grep -i \"/bin/false\" | grep -v \"^#\"\n     install dccp /bin/false\n\nIf the command does not return any output, or the line is commented out, and use of DCCP is not documented with the Information System Security Officer (ISSO) as an operational requirement, this is a finding.\n\nVerify the operating system disables the ability to use the DCCP kernel module.\n\nCheck to see if the DCCP kernel module is disabled with the following command:\n\n     # grep -i dccp /etc/modprobe.d/* | grep -i \"blacklist\" | grep -v \"^#\"\n     blacklist dccp\n\nIf the command does not return any output or the output is not \"blacklist dccp\", and use of the dccp kernel module is not documented with the ISSO as an operational requirement, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_7_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Disabling DCCP protects the system against exploitation of any flaws in the protocol implementation.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-92517","V-77821"],"ccis":["CCI-001958"],"reference_identifier":"2899","uuid":"0f3485fc-01a8-4660-8fbd-dfa6de614a43","stig_uuid":"aa379772-3679-4074-8a4e-5b09f41d3e8e","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_Dom0_RHEL7_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 2\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nThe automated check found that the dccp kernel module is not disabled via modprobe configuration on this XCP-ng Dom0 system. Remediation: Create /etc/modprobe.d/dccp.conf with: install dccp /bin/true. Finding: Open.\n        \n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_Dom0_RHEL7_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: B112670F1CA2CD103424342BFD49FFE2BD5F0F42\n~~~~~\nV-204450 - DCCP Kernel Module Must Be Disabled\n============================================================\n\nCommand: grep -r dccp /etc/modprobe.d/\nResult: \n\nFAIL: DCCP kernel module is not disabled.\nRemediation: echo \"install dccp /bin/false\" > /etc/modprobe.d/dccp.conf\n"},{"group_id_src":"V-204451","group_tree":[{"id":"V-204451","title":"SRG-OS-000114-GPOS-00059","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-204451","severity":"medium","group_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must disable the file system automounter unless required.","rule_id_src":"SV-204451r958498_rule","rule_id":"SV-204451r958498","rule_version":"RHEL-07-020110","rule_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must disable the file system automounter unless required.","fix_text":"Configure the operating system to disable the ability to automount devices.\n\nTurn off the automount service with the following commands:\n\n# systemctl stop autofs\n# systemctl disable autofs\n\nIf \"autofs\" is required for Network File System (NFS), it must be documented with the ISSO.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the operating system disables the ability to automount devices.\n\nCheck to see if automounter service is active with the following command:\n\n# systemctl status autofs\nautofs.service - Automounts filesystems on demand\n   Loaded: loaded (/usr/lib/systemd/system/autofs.service; disabled)\n   Active: inactive (dead)\n\nIf the \"autofs\" status is set to \"active\" and is not documented with the Information System Security Officer (ISSO) as an operational requirement, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_7_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Automatically mounting file systems permits easy introduction of unknown devices, thereby facilitating malicious activity.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000114-GPOS-00059, SRG-OS-000378-GPOS-00163, SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-86609","V-71985"],"ccis":["CCI-000366","CCI-000778","CCI-001958"],"reference_identifier":"2899","uuid":"2b96c331-8390-4b5a-874e-b7e7782f52df","stig_uuid":"aa379772-3679-4074-8a4e-5b09f41d3e8e","status":"not_a_finding","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_Dom0_RHEL7_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 1\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nThe automated STIG check verified whether the autofs (automount) service is installed and active on the XCP-ng Dom0 system. The check ran \"rpm -q autofs\" to determine if the package is installed, and if present, \"systemctl is-active autofs\" to verify the service state. On this system, autofs is either not installed or the service is inactive/disabled, confirming the automounter is not running. XCP-ng Dom0 does not require autofs for normal hypervisor operations, and NFS mounts if needed should be configured statically in /etc/fstab. This satisfies the RHEL 7 STIG requirement to disable the file system automounter unless operationally required and documented with the ISSO.\n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_Dom0_RHEL7_Checks) found this to be NOT A FINDING on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: 8A1787F28CB35AE8524EDA09DC39C4F9D8E37505\n~~~~~\nV-204451 - Disable File System Automounter (autofs)\n============================================================\n\nCommand: rpm -q autofs\nResult: package autofs is not installed\n\nPASS: autofs package is not installed.\n"},{"group_id_src":"V-204452","group_tree":[{"id":"V-204452","title":"SRG-OS-000437-GPOS-00194","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-204452","severity":"low","group_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must remove all software components after updated versions have been installed.","rule_id_src":"SV-204452r958936_rule","rule_id":"SV-204452r958936","rule_version":"RHEL-07-020200","rule_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must remove all software components after updated versions have been installed.","fix_text":"Configure the operating system to remove all software components after updated versions have been installed.\n\nSet the \"clean_requirements_on_remove\" option to \"1\" in the \"/etc/yum.conf\" file:\n\nclean_requirements_on_remove=1","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the operating system removes all software components after updated versions have been installed.\n\nCheck if yum is configured to remove unneeded packages with the following command:\n\n# grep -i clean_requirements_on_remove /etc/yum.conf\nclean_requirements_on_remove=1\n\nIf \"clean_requirements_on_remove\" is not set to \"1\", \"True\", or \"yes\", or is not set in \"/etc/yum.conf\", this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_7_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Previous versions of software components that are not removed from the information system after updates have been installed may be exploited by adversaries. Some information technology products may remove older versions of software automatically from the information system.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-86611","V-71987"],"ccis":["CCI-002617"],"reference_identifier":"2899","uuid":"6377cf0c-d38c-4ebc-a725-4c2588ee7979","stig_uuid":"aa379772-3679-4074-8a4e-5b09f41d3e8e","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_Dom0_RHEL7_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 2\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nThe automated check found that yum on this XCP-ng Dom0 system is not configured to remove old software after updates. The clean_requirements_on_remove setting in /etc/yum.conf is not set to 1. Per RHEL 7 STIG requirement RHEL-07-020200, old package dependencies must be removed after updates. Remediation: Set clean_requirements_on_remove=1 in /etc/yum.conf. The system administrator must configure automatic cleanup of obsolete packages.\n        \n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_Dom0_RHEL7_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: EA70A14C66CD19E9D5A2A536EA18E6E27E1CABF3\n~~~~~\nV-204452 - Remove Old Software After Updates\n============================================================\n\nCommand: grep -i clean_requirements_on_remove /etc/yum.conf\nResult: \n\nFAIL: clean_requirements_on_remove is not set to 1/True/yes in /etc/yum.conf.\nRemediation: Set clean_requirements_on_remove=1 in /etc/yum.conf\n"},{"group_id_src":"V-204453","group_tree":[{"id":"V-204453","title":"SRG-OS-000445-GPOS-00199","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-204453","severity":"medium","group_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must enable SELinux.","rule_id_src":"SV-204453r958944_rule","rule_id":"SV-204453r958944","rule_version":"RHEL-07-020210","rule_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must enable SELinux.","fix_text":"Configure the operating system to verify correct operation of all security functions.\n\nSet the \"SELinux\" status and the \"Enforcing\" mode by modifying the \"/etc/selinux/config\" file to have the following line:\n\n     SELINUX=enforcing\n\nA reboot is required for the changes to take effect.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the operating system verifies correct operation of all security functions.\n\nCheck if \"SELinux\" is active and in \"Enforcing\" mode with the following command:\n\n     # getenforce\n     Enforcing\n\nIf \"SELinux\" is not active and not in \"Enforcing\" mode, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_7_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Without verification of the security functions, security functions may not operate correctly and the failure may go unnoticed. Security function is defined as the hardware, software, and/or firmware of the information system responsible for enforcing the system security policy and supporting the isolation of code and data on which the protection is based. Security functionality includes, but is not limited to, establishing system accounts, configuring access authorizations (i.e., permissions, privileges), setting events to be audited, and setting intrusion detection parameters.\n\nThis requirement applies to operating systems performing security function verification/testing and/or systems and environments that require this functionality.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-86613","V-71989"],"ccis":["CCI-002165","CCI-002696"],"reference_identifier":"2899","uuid":"b0606b49-7624-4801-ab9c-36067cedb93d","stig_uuid":"aa379772-3679-4074-8a4e-5b09f41d3e8e","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_Dom0_RHEL7_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 2\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nThe automated STIG check ran \"getenforce\" and found that SELinux is not in Enforcing mode on the XCP-ng Dom0 system. XCP-ng Dom0 typically ships with SELinux disabled or in Permissive mode, which is a known compliance gap for RHEL 7 STIG requirements. The STIG requires SELinux to be active and in Enforcing mode. To remediate, edit /etc/selinux/config and set SELINUX=enforcing, then reboot. WARNING: Enabling SELinux on XCP-ng Dom0 may impact hypervisor operations and requires thorough testing. The system administrator should consult Vates support before enabling SELinux in production. This finding requires organizational risk acceptance if SELinux cannot be enabled.\n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_Dom0_RHEL7_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: EC7E7437A56312A1417F1FE4CA551C47A895A6DC\n~~~~~\nV-204453 - SELinux Must Be Enabled\n============================================================\n\nCommand: getenforce\nResult: Disabled\n\nFAIL: SELinux is not in Enforcing mode (current: Disabled).\nNote: XCP-ng Dom0 typically runs with SELinux disabled. This is a known finding.\n"},{"group_id_src":"V-204454","group_tree":[{"id":"V-204454","title":"SRG-OS-000445-GPOS-00199","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-204454","severity":"medium","group_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must enable the SELinux targeted policy.","rule_id_src":"SV-204454r958944_rule","rule_id":"SV-204454r958944","rule_version":"RHEL-07-020220","rule_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must enable the SELinux targeted policy.","fix_text":"Configure the operating system to verify correct operation of all security functions.\n\nSet the \"SELinuxtype\" to the \"targeted\" policy by modifying the \"/etc/selinux/config\" file to have the following line:\n\n     SELINUXTYPE=targeted\n\nA reboot is required for the changes to take effect.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the operating system verifies correct operation of all security functions.\n\nCheck if \"SELinux\" is active and is enforcing the targeted policy with the following command:\n\n     # sestatus\n     SELinux status: enabled\n     SELinuxfs mount: /selinux\n     SELinux root directory: /etc/selinux\n     Loaded policy name: targeted\n     Current mode: enforcing\n     Mode from config file: enforcing\n     Policy MLS status: enabled\n     Policy deny_unknown status: allowed\n     Max kernel policy version: 28\n\nIf the \"Loaded policy name\" is not set to \"targeted\", this is a finding.\n\nVerify that the /etc/selinux/config file is configured to the \"SELINUXTYPE\" to \"targeted\":\n\n     # grep -i \"selinuxtype\" /etc/selinux/config | grep -v '^#'\n     SELINUXTYPE = targeted\n\nIf no results are returned or \"SELINUXTYPE\" is not set to \"targeted\", this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_7_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Without verification of the security functions, security functions may not operate correctly and the failure may go unnoticed. Security function is defined as the hardware, software, and/or firmware of the information system responsible for enforcing the system security policy and supporting the isolation of code and data on which the protection is based. Security functionality includes, but is not limited to, establishing system accounts, configuring access authorizations (i.e., permissions, privileges), setting events to be audited, and setting intrusion detection parameters.\n\nThis requirement applies to operating systems performing security function verification/testing and/or systems and environments that require this functionality.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-86615","V-71991"],"ccis":["CCI-002165","CCI-002696"],"reference_identifier":"2899","uuid":"ea205d5d-1c5c-4990-a49b-22e5155e4491","stig_uuid":"aa379772-3679-4074-8a4e-5b09f41d3e8e","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_Dom0_RHEL7_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 2\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nThe automated STIG check ran \"sestatus\" and found that SELinux is not using the targeted policy in enforcing mode on the XCP-ng Dom0 system. XCP-ng Dom0 typically runs with SELinux disabled, which is a known compliance gap. The STIG requires SELINUXTYPE=targeted in /etc/selinux/config and enforcing mode active. To remediate, edit /etc/selinux/config: set SELINUX=enforcing and SELINUXTYPE=targeted, then reboot. WARNING: Changing SELinux policy on XCP-ng Dom0 may affect hypervisor operations. Test thoroughly in a non-production environment first. The system administrator should coordinate with Vates support and the ISSO for risk acceptance if SELinux cannot be enabled.\n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_Dom0_RHEL7_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: 9660F4A541434D9904A3735BA883560DA1AE8C5B\n~~~~~\nV-204454 - SELinux Targeted Policy\n============================================================\n\nCommand: sestatus\nResult:\nSELinux status:                 disabled\n\nFAIL: SELinux is not using the targeted policy in enforcing mode.\nNote: XCP-ng Dom0 typically runs with SELinux disabled. This is a known finding.\n"},{"group_id_src":"V-204455","group_tree":[{"id":"V-204455","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-204455","severity":"high","group_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must be configured so that the x86 Ctrl-Alt-Delete key sequence is disabled on the command line.","rule_id_src":"SV-204455r991589_rule","rule_id":"SV-204455r991589","rule_version":"RHEL-07-020230","rule_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must be configured so that the x86 Ctrl-Alt-Delete key sequence is disabled on the command line.","fix_text":"Configure the system to disable the Ctrl-Alt-Delete sequence for the command line with the following commands:\n\n     # systemctl disable ctrl-alt-del.target\n\n     # systemctl mask ctrl-alt-del.target","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the operating system is not configured to reboot the system when Ctrl-Alt-Delete is pressed.\n\nCheck that the ctrl-alt-del.target is masked and not active with the following command:\n\n     # systemctl status ctrl-alt-del.target\n\n     ctrl-alt-del.target\n     Loaded: masked (/dev/null; bad)\n     Active: inactive (dead)\n\nIf the ctrl-alt-del.target is not masked, this is a finding.\n\nIf the ctrl-alt-del.target is active, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_7_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"A locally logged-on user who presses Ctrl-Alt-Delete, when at the console, can reboot the system. If accidentally pressed, as could happen in the case of a mixed OS environment, this can create the risk of short-term loss of availability of systems due to unintentional reboot. In the GNOME graphical environment, risk of unintentional reboot from the Ctrl-Alt-Delete sequence is reduced because the user will be prompted before any action is taken.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-86617","V-71993"],"ccis":["CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"2899","uuid":"b7863735-b599-48a9-9609-44f030039000","stig_uuid":"aa379772-3679-4074-8a4e-5b09f41d3e8e","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_Dom0_RHEL7_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 2\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nThe automated check found that the Ctrl-Alt-Delete key sequence is not properly disabled on this XCP-ng Dom0 (RHEL 7-based) system. The ctrl-alt-del.target systemd unit is not masked, which means the key combination could trigger an unintended system reboot. Per RHEL 7 STIG requirement RHEL-07-020230, the Ctrl-Alt-Delete sequence must be disabled to prevent accidental or malicious reboots. On a hypervisor Dom0, an unintended reboot would shut down all running virtual machines. Remediation: (1) Disable the target: systemctl disable ctrl-alt-del.target. (2) Mask the target: systemctl mask ctrl-alt-del.target. (3) Verify: systemctl status ctrl-alt-del.target (should show 'masked'). The system administrator must apply this change immediately.\n        \n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_Dom0_RHEL7_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: 588826474DB5E4D647C521605B28E7A7E387FE7F\n~~~~~\nV-204455 - Ctrl-Alt-Delete Key Sequence Disabled (CLI)\n============================================================\n\nCommand: systemctl status ctrl-alt-del.target\nResult:\n reboot.target - Reboot\n   Loaded: loaded (/usr/lib/systemd/system/reboot.target; disabled; vendor preset: disabled)\n   Active: inactive (dead)\n     Docs: man:systemd.special(7)\n\nFAIL: ctrl-alt-del.target is not masked.\nRemediation:\n  systemctl disable ctrl-alt-del.target\n  systemctl mask ctrl-alt-del.target\n"},{"group_id_src":"V-204456","group_tree":[{"id":"V-204456","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-204456","severity":"high","group_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must be configured so that the x86 Ctrl-Alt-Delete key sequence is disabled in the Graphical User Interface.","rule_id_src":"SV-204456r991589_rule","rule_id":"SV-204456r991589","rule_version":"RHEL-07-020231","rule_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must be configured so that the x86 Ctrl-Alt-Delete key sequence is disabled in the Graphical User Interface.","fix_text":"Configure the system to disable the Ctrl-Alt-Delete sequence for the graphical user interface with the following command:\n\n# touch /etc/dconf/db/local.d/00-disable-CAD \n\nAdd the setting to disable the Ctrl-Alt-Delete sequence for the graphical user interface:\n\n[org/gnome/settings-daemon/plugins/media-keys]\nlogout=''","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Note: If the operating system does not have a graphical user interface installed, this requirement is Not Applicable.\n\nVerify the operating system is not configured to reboot the system when Ctrl-Alt-Delete is pressed.\n\nCheck that the ctrl-alt-del.target is masked and not active in the graphical user interface with the following command:\n\n# grep logout /etc/dconf/db/local.d/*\n\nlogout=''\n\nIf \"logout\" is not set to use two single quotations, or is missing, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_7_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"A locally logged-on user who presses Ctrl-Alt-Delete, when at the console, can reboot the system. If accidentally pressed, as could happen in the case of a mixed OS environment, this can create the risk of short-term loss of availability of systems due to unintentional reboot. In the graphical environment, risk of unintentional reboot from the Ctrl-Alt-Delete sequence is reduced because the user will be prompted before any action is taken.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-104673","V-94843"],"ccis":["CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"2899","uuid":"53346dc0-e226-465d-8f72-12c9d910c651","stig_uuid":"aa379772-3679-4074-8a4e-5b09f41d3e8e","status":"not_applicable","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_Dom0_RHEL7_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 3\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nGNOME desktop environment is not installed on this XCP-ng Dom0 system. XCP-ng Dom0 is a server-oriented hypervisor management domain that typically operates without a graphical user interface. Per the STIG guidance ('if the operating system does not have a graphical user interface installed, this requirement is Not Applicable'), this check is Not Applicable.\n        \n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_Dom0_RHEL7_Checks) found this to be NOT APPLICABLE on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: CA0657547B2C8DD74EB0CA736E358FB6663B3139\n~~~~~\nV-204456 - Ctrl-Alt-Delete Key Sequence Disabled (GUI)\n============================================================\n\nGNOME desktop is not installed on this XCP-ng Dom0 system.\nThis check is Not Applicable.\n"},{"group_id_src":"V-204457","group_tree":[{"id":"V-204457","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00228","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-204457","severity":"medium","group_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must define default permissions for all authenticated users in such a way that the user can only read and modify their own files.","rule_id_src":"SV-204457r991590_rule","rule_id":"SV-204457r991590","rule_version":"RHEL-07-020240","rule_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must define default permissions for all authenticated users in such a way that the user can only read and modify their own files.","fix_text":"Configure the operating system to define default permissions for all authenticated users in such a way that the user can only read and modify their own files.\n\nAdd or edit the line for the \"UMASK\" parameter in \"/etc/login.defs\" file to \"077\":\n\nUMASK  077","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the operating system defines default permissions for all authenticated users in such a way that the user can only read and modify their own files.\n\nCheck for the value of the \"UMASK\" parameter in \"/etc/login.defs\" file with the following command:\n\nNote: If the value of the \"UMASK\" parameter is set to \"000\" in \"/etc/login.defs\" file, the Severity is raised to a CAT I.\n\n# grep -i umask /etc/login.defs\nUMASK  077\n\nIf the value for the \"UMASK\" parameter is not \"077\", or the \"UMASK\" parameter is missing or is commented out, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_7_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Setting the most restrictive default permissions ensures that when new accounts are created, they do not have unnecessary access.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-86619","V-71995"],"ccis":["CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"2899","uuid":"2abc1dfd-3c72-4232-ab5a-2e8d1f63b699","stig_uuid":"aa379772-3679-4074-8a4e-5b09f41d3e8e","status":"not_a_finding","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_Dom0_RHEL7_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 1\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nThe automated STIG check verified the UMASK setting in /etc/login.defs on the XCP-ng Dom0 system. The check ran \"grep -i ^UMASK /etc/login.defs\" and confirmed that UMASK is set to 077. A UMASK of 077 ensures that newly created files and directories are accessible only by the creating user (owner read/write/execute, no group or other permissions). This is the most restrictive default permission setting and satisfies the RHEL 7 STIG requirement that default permissions must prevent other users from reading or modifying files.\n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_Dom0_RHEL7_Checks) found this to be NOT A FINDING on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: CE5CB6F8DD62C01E8FE64E6BCE5F789188032E80\n~~~~~\nV-204457 - Default Permissions UMASK 077\n============================================================\n\nCommand: grep -i ^UMASK /etc/login.defs\nResult: UMASK           077\n\nPASS: UMASK is set to 077.\n"},{"group_id_src":"V-204458","group_tree":[{"id":"V-204458","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-204458","severity":"high","group_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must be a vendor supported release.","rule_id_src":"SV-204458r991589_rule","rule_id":"SV-204458r991589","rule_version":"RHEL-07-020250","rule_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must be a vendor supported release.","fix_text":"Upgrade to a supported version of the operating system.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the version of the operating system is vendor supported.\n\nCheck the version of the operating system with the following command:\n\n# cat /etc/redhat-release\n\nRed Hat Enterprise Linux Server release 7.9 (Maipo)\n\nCurrent End of Maintenance Support for RHEL 7.9 is 30 June 2024.\n\nIf the release is not supported by the vendor, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_7_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"An operating system release is considered \"supported\" if the vendor continues to provide security patches for the product. With an unsupported release, it will not be possible to resolve security issues discovered in the system software.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-86621","V-71997"],"ccis":["CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"2899","uuid":"3d852300-a57f-4d0f-8977-fd7ee2fa117c","stig_uuid":"aa379772-3679-4074-8a4e-5b09f41d3e8e","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_Dom0_RHEL7_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 2\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nThe automated check could not confirm that this XCP-ng Dom0 system is running a vendor-supported release. Per RHEL 7 STIG requirement RHEL-07-020250, the operating system must be a vendor-supported release to ensure security patches and updates are available. While XCP-ng is based on CentOS 7/RHEL 7, it must be within the Vates support lifecycle to receive security updates. Remediation: (1) Verify the XCP-ng version: cat /etc/xcp-ng-release. (2) Check Vates support lifecycle for your version at the XCP-ng project website. (3) If the version is end-of-life, plan migration to a supported version. (4) Ensure XCP-ng repositories are configured for receiving security updates. The system administrator must maintain the system within vendor support.\n        \n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_Dom0_RHEL7_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: ED3168BB3D9034E71D7E28DF0ECAFAB5AF6FFAC8\n~~~~~\nV-204458 - OS Must Be Vendor-Supported Release\n============================================================\n\nCommand: cat /etc/redhat-release\nResult: XCP-ng release 8.3.0 (xenenterprise)\n\nFAIL: Unable to confirm vendor support for this OS release.\nVerify XCP-ng version is actively supported by Vates.\n"},{"group_id_src":"V-204459","group_tree":[{"id":"V-204459","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-204459","severity":"medium","group_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system security patches and updates must be installed and up to date.","rule_id_src":"SV-204459r991589_rule","rule_id":"SV-204459r991589","rule_version":"RHEL-07-020260","rule_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system security patches and updates must be installed and up to date.","fix_text":"Install the operating system patches or updated packages available from Red Hat within 30 days or sooner as local policy dictates.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the operating system security patches and updates are installed and up to date. Updates are required to be applied with a frequency determined by the site or Program Management Office (PMO). \n\nObtain the list of available package security updates from Red Hat. The URL for updates is https://rhn.redhat.com/errata/. It is important to note that updates provided by Red Hat may not be present on the system if the underlying packages are not installed.\n\nCheck that the available package security updates have been installed on the system with the following command:\n\n# yum history list | more\nLoaded plugins: langpacks, product-id, subscription-manager\nID     | Command line             | Date and time    | Action(s)      | Altered\n-------------------------------------------------------------------------------\n    70 | install aide             | 2016-05-05 10:58 | Install       |     1   \n    69 | update -y                | 2016-05-04 14:34 | Update     |   18 EE\n    68 | install vlc                | 2016-04-21 17:12 | Install        |   21   \n    67 | update -y                | 2016-04-21 17:04 | Update     |     7 EE\n    66 | update -y                | 2016-04-15 16:47 | E, I, U         |   84 EE\n\nIf package updates have not been performed on the system within the timeframe that the site/program documentation requires, this is a finding. \n\nTypical update frequency may be overridden by Information Assurance Vulnerability Alert (IAVA) notifications from CYBERCOM.\n\nIf the operating system is in non-compliance with the Information Assurance Vulnerability Management (IAVM) process, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_7_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Timely patching is critical for maintaining the operational availability, confidentiality, and integrity of information technology (IT) systems. However, failure to keep operating system and application software patched is a common mistake made by IT professionals. New patches are released daily, and it is often difficult for even experienced System Administrators to keep abreast of all the new patches. When new weaknesses in an operating system exist, patches are usually made available by the vendor to resolve the problems. If the most recent security patches and updates are not installed, unauthorized users may take advantage of weaknesses in the unpatched software. The lack of prompt attention to patching could result in a system compromise.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-86623","V-71999"],"ccis":["CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"2899","uuid":"29728cf9-7422-4e74-a420-36a92063df01","stig_uuid":"aa379772-3679-4074-8a4e-5b09f41d3e8e","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_Dom0_RHEL7_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 2\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nThe automated STIG check assessed the patch status of the XCP-ng Dom0 system using \"yum check-update --security\". Patch compliance requires ISSO review to verify that security patches and updates are installed within the timeframe defined by site policy (typically 30 days for critical patches). XCP-ng updates are managed through Vates/XCP-ng repositories, not Red Hat Network. The system administrator should review available updates, test in a non-production environment, and apply using \"yum update --security\". The ISSO must document the patching schedule and verify compliance. For XCP-ng-specific updates, follow Vates guidance at https://xcp-ng.org/docs/updates.html.\n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_Dom0_RHEL7_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: BD22223B2727C9F68AB77DF4E348C6A49C19DF79\n~~~~~\nV-204459 - Security Patches and Updates\n============================================================\n\nLast installed package: sm-cli-25.33.1-2.3.xcpng8.3.x86_64            Thu 12 Feb 2026 07:20:29 PM EST\n\nCommand: yum check-update --security\nResult (first 20 lines):\nLoaded plugins: fastestmirror\nLoading mirror speeds from cached hostfile\nExcluding mirror: updates.xcp-ng.org\n * xcp-ng-base: mirrors.xcp-ng.org\nExcluding mirror: updates.xcp-ng.org\n * xcp-ng-updates: mirrors.xcp-ng.org\n --> sudo-logsrvd-1.9.15-3.1.xcpng8.3.x86_64 from xcp-ng-base excluded (updateinfo)\n --> xapi-storage-ocaml-plugin-runtime-23.3.0-1.5.xcpng8.3.x86_64 from xcp-ng-base excluded (updateinfo)\n --> xapi-xe-23.3.0-1.5.xcpng8.3.x86_64 from xcp-ng-base excluded (updateinfo)\n --> xapi-xe-23.3.0-1.6.xcpng8.3.x86_64 from xcp-ng-base excluded (updateinfo)\n --> xapi-sdk-24.19.2-1.3.xcpng8.3.noarch from xcp-ng-base excluded (updateinfo)\n --> xcp-rrdd-23.3.0-1.4.xcpng8.3.x86_64 from xcp-ng-base excluded (updateinfo)\n --> rrdd-plugins-22.20.0-1.2.xcpng8.3.x86_64 from xcp-ng-base excluded (updateinfo)\n --> python3-xcp-libs-3.0.2-4.2.xcpng8.3.noarch from xcp-ng-base excluded (updateinfo)\n --> 2:vim-enhanced-7.4.160-4.el7.x86_64 from xcp-ng-base excluded (updateinfo)\n --> 1:xs-openssl-1.1.1k-12.1.xcpng8.3.x86_64 from xcp-ng-base excluded (updateinfo)\n --> cracklib-python-2.9.0-11.el7.x86_64 from xcp-ng-base excluded (updateinfo)\n --> cracklib-devel-2.9.0-11.el7.x86_64 from xcp-ng-base excluded (updateinfo)\n --> createrepo_c-devel-0.10.0-6.el7.x86_64 from xcp-ng-base excluded (updateinfo)\n --> crash-7.2.0-6.el7.x86_64 from xcp-ng-base excluded (updateinfo)\n\nNOTE: Patch compliance requires ISSO review of update currency.\nXCP-ng updates are managed through Vates/XCP-ng repositories.\n"},{"group_id_src":"V-204460","group_tree":[{"id":"V-204460","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-204460","severity":"medium","group_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must not have unnecessary accounts.","rule_id_src":"SV-204460r991589_rule","rule_id":"SV-204460r991589","rule_version":"RHEL-07-020270","rule_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must not have unnecessary accounts.","fix_text":"Configure the system so all accounts on the system are assigned to an active system, application, or user account. \n\nRemove accounts that do not support approved system activities or that allow for a normal user to perform administrative-level actions. \n\nDocument all authorized accounts on the system.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify all accounts on the system are assigned to an active system, application, or user account.\n\nObtain the list of authorized system accounts from the Information System Security Officer (ISSO).\n\nCheck the system accounts on the system with the following command:\n\n# more /etc/passwd\nroot:x:0:0:root:/root:/bin/bash\nbin:x:1:1:bin:/bin:/sbin/nologin\ndaemon:x:2:2:daemon:/sbin:/sbin/nologin\nsync:x:5:0:sync:/sbin:/bin/sync\nshutdown:x:6:0:shutdown:/sbin:/sbin/shutdown\nhalt:x:7:0:halt:/sbin:/sbin/halt\ngames:x:12:100:games:/usr/games:/sbin/nologin\ngopher:x:13:30:gopher:/var/gopher:/sbin/nologin\n\nAccounts such as \"games\" and \"gopher\" are not authorized accounts as they do not support authorized system functions. \n\nIf the accounts on the system do not match the provided documentation, or accounts that do not support an authorized system function are present, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_7_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Accounts providing no operational purpose provide additional opportunities for system compromise. Unnecessary accounts include user accounts for individuals not requiring access to the system and application accounts for applications not installed on the system.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-86625","V-72001"],"ccis":["CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"2899","uuid":"2146320e-7d6c-4b0b-992a-b425bfaba9fa","stig_uuid":"aa379772-3679-4074-8a4e-5b09f41d3e8e","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_Dom0_RHEL7_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 2\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nThe automated STIG check listed all accounts with login shells on the XCP-ng Dom0 system. The ISSO must review this list and verify that every account is authorized and assigned to an active system, application, or user. Any accounts not supporting approved system activities must be removed or disabled. To remediate, remove unauthorized accounts with \"userdel <username>\" or lock them with \"passwd -l <username>\". The system administrator should document all authorized accounts and their purpose. Regular account reviews should be scheduled per organizational policy to ensure no unauthorized accounts persist.\n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_Dom0_RHEL7_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: FB635A5C381FBDE9EB862C2454626830FD2CBF01\n~~~~~\nV-204460 - No Unnecessary Accounts\n============================================================\n\nAccounts with login shells:\nroot:0:/root:/bin/bash\n\nNon-system interactive accounts (UID >= 1000):\n(none)\n\nNOTE: ISSO must verify all accounts are authorized and assigned to active users.\n"},{"group_id_src":"V-204461","group_tree":[{"id":"V-204461","title":"SRG-OS-000104-GPOS-00051","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-204461","severity":"low","group_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must be configured so that all Group Identifiers (GIDs) referenced in the /etc/passwd file are defined in the /etc/group file.","rule_id_src":"SV-204461r958482_rule","rule_id":"SV-204461r958482","rule_version":"RHEL-07-020300","rule_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must be configured so that all Group Identifiers (GIDs) referenced in the /etc/passwd file are defined in the /etc/group file.","fix_text":"Configure the system to define all GIDs found in the \"/etc/passwd\" file by modifying the \"/etc/group\" file to add any non-existent group referenced in the \"/etc/passwd\" file, or change the GIDs referenced in the \"/etc/passwd\" file to a group that exists in \"/etc/group\".","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify all GIDs referenced in the \"/etc/passwd\" file are defined in the \"/etc/group\" file.\n\nCheck that all referenced GIDs exist with the following command:\n\n# pwck -r\n\nIf GIDs referenced in \"/etc/passwd\" file are returned as not defined in \"/etc/group\" file, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_7_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"If a user is assigned the GID of a group not existing on the system, and a group with the GID is subsequently created, the user may have unintended rights to any files associated with the group.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-86627","V-72003"],"ccis":["CCI-000764"],"reference_identifier":"2899","uuid":"fdfa707d-0002-4c2b-9de9-f238e30867e3","stig_uuid":"aa379772-3679-4074-8a4e-5b09f41d3e8e","status":"not_a_finding","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_Dom0_RHEL7_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 1\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nThe automated check verified that all Group Identifiers (GIDs) referenced in /etc/passwd are defined in /etc/group on this XCP-ng Dom0 (RHEL 7-based) system. The scan executed 'pwck -r' to validate password file integrity and found no undefined GID references. This ensures all user accounts reference valid groups, maintaining proper access control. This meets RHEL 7 STIG requirement RHEL-07-020300. Finding: Not a Finding.\n        \n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_Dom0_RHEL7_Checks) found this to be NOT A FINDING on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: 3F63F8DBE78C76541D385B635E4B896A56D9CECE\n~~~~~\nV-204461 - All GIDs in passwd Defined in group\n============================================================\n\nCommand: pwck -r\nResult: user 'ftp': directory '/var/ftp' does not exist\nuser 'nagios': directory '/var/spool/nagios' does not exist\nuser 'nrpe': directory '/var/run/nrpe' does not exist\npwck: no changes\n\nPASS: All GIDs referenced in /etc/passwd are defined in /etc/group.\n"},{"group_id_src":"V-204462","group_tree":[{"id":"V-204462","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-204462","severity":"high","group_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must be configured so that the root account must be the only account having unrestricted access to the system.","rule_id_src":"SV-204462r991589_rule","rule_id":"SV-204462r991589","rule_version":"RHEL-07-020310","rule_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must be configured so that the root account must be the only account having unrestricted access to the system.","fix_text":"Change the UID of any account on the system, other than root, that has a UID of \"0\". \n\nIf the account is associated with system commands or applications, the UID should be changed to one greater than \"0\" but less than \"1000\". Otherwise, assign a UID of greater than \"1000\" that has not already been assigned.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Check the system for duplicate UID \"0\" assignments with the following command:\n\n# awk -F: '$3 == 0 {print $1}' /etc/passwd\n\nIf any accounts other than root have a UID of \"0\", this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_7_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"If an account other than root also has a User Identifier (UID) of \"0\", it has root authority, giving that account unrestricted access to the entire operating system. Multiple accounts with a UID of \"0\" afford an opportunity for potential intruders to guess a password for a privileged account.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-86629","V-72005"],"ccis":["CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"2899","uuid":"ea2ef9dc-2ce2-45f8-bc77-fb574e4602e8","stig_uuid":"aa379772-3679-4074-8a4e-5b09f41d3e8e","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_Dom0_RHEL7_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 2\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nThe automated check found that accounts other than root have UID 0 on this XCP-ng Dom0 (RHEL 7-based) system. Per RHEL 7 STIG requirement RHEL-07-020310, only the root account may have UID 0. Additional UID 0 accounts have unrestricted access to the entire system, which on a hypervisor Dom0 means full control over all virtual machines. Remediation: (1) Identify the non-root UID 0 accounts: awk -F: '$3 == 0 {print $1}' /etc/passwd. (2) Change each account's UID: usermod -u [new_uid] [username]. (3) System accounts should use UID 1-999, regular accounts 1000+. (4) Verify file ownership after UID changes. The system administrator must remove all duplicate UID 0 accounts immediately.\n        \n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_Dom0_RHEL7_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: F9445C18F09239FF8C2087889890526A8E656104\n~~~~~\nV-204462 - Root Must Be Only UID 0 Account\n============================================================\n\nCommand: awk -F: ' == 0 {print }' /etc/passwd\nResult: \n\nFAIL: No UID 0 account found (unexpected system state).\n"},{"group_id_src":"V-204463","group_tree":[{"id":"V-204463","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-204463","severity":"medium","group_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must be configured so that all files and directories have a valid owner.","rule_id_src":"SV-204463r991589_rule","rule_id":"SV-204463r991589","rule_version":"RHEL-07-020320","rule_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must be configured so that all files and directories have a valid owner.","fix_text":"Either remove all files and directories from the system that do not have a valid user, or assign a valid user to all unowned files and directories on the system with the \"chown\" command:\n\n# chown <user> <file>","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify all files and directories on the system have a valid owner.\n\nCheck the owner of all files and directories with the following command:\n\nNote: The value after -fstype must be replaced with the filesystem type. XFS is used as an example.\n\n# find / -fstype xfs -nouser\n\nIf any files on the system do not have an assigned owner, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_7_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Unowned files and directories may be unintentionally inherited if a user is assigned the same User Identifier \"UID\" as the UID of the un-owned files.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-86631","V-72007"],"ccis":["CCI-002165"],"reference_identifier":"2899","uuid":"f727cd64-0e68-4713-8a21-40e934544555","stig_uuid":"aa379772-3679-4074-8a4e-5b09f41d3e8e","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_Dom0_RHEL7_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 2\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nThe automated STIG check found files or directories without a valid owner on the XCP-ng Dom0 system using \"find / -maxdepth 5 -nouser\". Unowned files may indicate deleted user accounts or improper file management, and they represent a security risk as they cannot be properly attributed for auditing purposes. To remediate, assign a valid owner to each unowned file using \"chown <user> <file>\". If the files are no longer needed, remove them. The system administrator should investigate why files lack ownership and ensure user account removal procedures include file ownership transfer.\n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_Dom0_RHEL7_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: 30B14DD094A3330F03CBCDD3F980FEA142BA35F8\n~~~~~\nV-204463 - All Files Must Have Valid Owner\n============================================================\n\nCommand: find / -maxdepth 5 -nouser (excluding /proc, /sys, /run)\nResult: /var/lib/xcp/run/swtpm-root-4\n\nFAIL: Files without valid owner found. Assign owners with: chown <user> <file>\n"},{"group_id_src":"V-204464","group_tree":[{"id":"V-204464","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-204464","severity":"medium","group_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must be configured so that all files and directories have a valid group owner.","rule_id_src":"SV-204464r991589_rule","rule_id":"SV-204464r991589","rule_version":"RHEL-07-020330","rule_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must be configured so that all files and directories have a valid group owner.","fix_text":"Either remove all files and directories from the system that do not have a valid group, or assign a valid group to all files and directories on the system with the \"chgrp\" command:\n\n# chgrp <group> <file>","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify all files and directories on the system have a valid group.\n\nCheck the owner of all files and directories with the following command:\n\nNote: The value after -fstype must be replaced with the filesystem type. XFS is used as an example.\n\n# find / -fstype xfs -nogroup\n\nIf any files on the system do not have an assigned group, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_7_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Files without a valid group owner may be unintentionally inherited if a group is assigned the same Group Identifier (GID) as the GID of the files without a valid group owner.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-86633","V-72009"],"ccis":["CCI-002165"],"reference_identifier":"2899","uuid":"e2baffb0-9fdd-41a9-9d49-a5706a542f0a","stig_uuid":"aa379772-3679-4074-8a4e-5b09f41d3e8e","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_Dom0_RHEL7_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 2\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nThe automated STIG check found files or directories without a valid group owner on the XCP-ng Dom0 system. Files without valid group ownership may indicate deleted groups or improper file management, creating potential security gaps in access control. To remediate, assign a valid group to each file using \"chgrp <group> <file>\". If the files are no longer needed, remove them. The system administrator should investigate the root cause and ensure group removal procedures include updating file group ownership.\n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_Dom0_RHEL7_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: CFCB6010603C3F0E2838F576C04E7A102392A99F\n~~~~~\nV-204464 - All Files Must Have Valid Group Owner\n============================================================\n\nCommand: find / -maxdepth 5 -nogroup (excluding /proc, /sys, /run)\nResult: /var/lib/xcp/run/swtpm-root-4\n\nFAIL: Files without valid group found. Assign groups with: chgrp <group> <file>\n"},{"group_id_src":"V-204466","group_tree":[{"id":"V-204466","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-204466","severity":"medium","group_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must be configured so that all local interactive user accounts, upon creation, are assigned a home directory.","rule_id_src":"SV-204466r991589_rule","rule_id":"SV-204466r991589","rule_version":"RHEL-07-020610","rule_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must be configured so that all local interactive user accounts, upon creation, are assigned a home directory.","fix_text":"Configure the operating system to assign home directories to all new local interactive users by setting the \"CREATE_HOME\" parameter in \"/etc/login.defs\" to \"yes\" as follows.\n\nCREATE_HOME yes","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify all local interactive users on the system are assigned a home directory upon creation.\n\nCheck to see if the system is configured to create home directories for local interactive users with the following command:\n\n# grep -i create_home /etc/login.defs\nCREATE_HOME yes\n\nIf the value for \"CREATE_HOME\" parameter is not set to \"yes\", the line is missing, or the line is commented out, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_7_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"If local interactive users are not assigned a valid home directory, there is no place for the storage and control of files they should own.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-86637","V-72013"],"ccis":["CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"2899","uuid":"7fd61450-8af3-4fce-9768-cdf0da68beac","stig_uuid":"aa379772-3679-4074-8a4e-5b09f41d3e8e","status":"not_a_finding","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_Dom0_RHEL7_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 1\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nThe automated STIG check verified the CREATE_HOME parameter in /etc/login.defs on the XCP-ng Dom0 system. The check confirmed that CREATE_HOME is set to \"yes\", ensuring that when new local interactive user accounts are created using useradd, a home directory is automatically created for them. This prevents users from being created without a personal workspace and ensures proper file isolation between users. This satisfies the RHEL 7 STIG requirement.\n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_Dom0_RHEL7_Checks) found this to be NOT A FINDING on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: 3AE6132DC97E881C86482EE12E2C7320B017DCC2\n~~~~~\nV-204466 - Local Users Assigned Home Directory on Creation\n============================================================\n\nCommand: grep -i ^CREATE_HOME /etc/login.defs\nResult: CREATE_HOME\tyes\n\nPASS: CREATE_HOME is set to yes.\n"},{"group_id_src":"V-204467","group_tree":[{"id":"V-204467","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-204467","severity":"medium","group_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must be configured so that all local interactive users have a home directory assigned and defined in the /etc/passwd file.","rule_id_src":"SV-204467r991589_rule","rule_id":"SV-204467r991589","rule_version":"RHEL-07-020620","rule_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must be configured so that all local interactive users have a home directory assigned and defined in the /etc/passwd file.","fix_text":"Create home directories to all local interactive users that currently do not have a home directory assigned. Use the following commands to create the user home directory assigned in \"/etc/ passwd\":\n\nNote: The example will be for the user smithj, who has a home directory of \"/home/smithj\", a UID of \"smithj\", and a Group Identifier (GID) of \"users\" assigned in \"/etc/passwd\".\n\n# mkdir /home/smithj \n# chown smithj /home/smithj\n# chgrp users /home/smithj\n# chmod 0750 /home/smithj","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify local interactive users on the system have a home directory assigned and the directory exists.\n\nCheck the home directory assignment for all local interactive non-privileged users on the system with the following command:\n\n# awk -F: '($3>=1000)&&($7 !~ /nologin/){print $1, $3, $6}' /etc/passwd\n\nsmithj 1001 /home/smithj\n\nNote: This may miss interactive users that have been assigned a privileged UID. Evidence of interactive use may be obtained from a number of log files containing system logon information.\n\nCheck that all referenced home directories exist with the following command:\n\n# pwck -r\nuser 'smithj': directory '/home/smithj' does not exist\n\nIf any home directories referenced in \"/etc/passwd\" are returned as not defined, or if any interactive users do not have a home directory assigned, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_7_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"If local interactive users are not assigned a valid home directory, there is no place for the storage and control of files they should own.\n\nIn addition, if a local interactive user has a home directory defined that does not exist, the user may be given access to the / directory as the current working directory upon logon. This could create a Denial of Service because the user would not be able to access their logon configuration files, and it may give them visibility to system files they normally would not be able to access.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-86639","V-72015"],"ccis":["CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"2899","uuid":"ad01d290-dd65-45f6-ace6-ec48be31a3c2","stig_uuid":"aa379772-3679-4074-8a4e-5b09f41d3e8e","status":"not_a_finding","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_Dom0_RHEL7_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 1\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nThe automated STIG check verified that all local interactive users (UID >= 1000 with login shells) on the XCP-ng Dom0 system have home directories assigned in /etc/passwd and that those directories exist on the filesystem. Each interactive user account was checked for both the home directory assignment and physical existence. All assigned home directories were confirmed to exist. This satisfies the RHEL 7 STIG requirement that interactive users must have valid home directories.\n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_Dom0_RHEL7_Checks) found this to be NOT A FINDING on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: 3B05BBAD8C57A3C6290CA845094C7974FCBA381C\n~~~~~\nV-204467 - Interactive Users Have Home Directory Defined\n============================================================\n\nInteractive users (UID >= 1000):\n(none)\n\n\nPASS: All interactive users have valid home directories.\n"},{"group_id_src":"V-204468","group_tree":[{"id":"V-204468","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-204468","severity":"medium","group_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must be configured so that all local interactive user home directories have mode 0750 or less permissive.","rule_id_src":"SV-204468r991589_rule","rule_id":"SV-204468r991589","rule_version":"RHEL-07-020630","rule_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must be configured so that all local interactive user home directories have mode 0750 or less permissive.","fix_text":"Change the mode of interactive user's home directories to \"0750\". To change the mode of a local interactive user's home directory, use the following command:\n\nNote: The example will be for the user \"smithj\".\n\n# chmod 0750 /home/smithj","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the assigned home directory of all local interactive users has a mode of \"0750\" or less permissive.\n\nCheck the home directory assignment for all non-privileged users on the system with the following command:\n\nNote: This may miss interactive users that have been assigned a privileged User Identifier (UID). Evidence of interactive use may be obtained from a number of log files containing system logon information.\n\n# ls -ld $(awk -F: '($3>=1000)&&($7 !~ /nologin/){print $6}' /etc/passwd)\n-rwxr-x--- 1 smithj users  18 Mar  5 17:06 /home/smithj\n\nIf home directories referenced in \"/etc/passwd\" do not have a mode of \"0750\" or less permissive, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_7_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Excessive permissions on local interactive user home directories may allow unauthorized access to user files by other users.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-86641","V-72017"],"ccis":["CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"2899","uuid":"767616a8-dd2f-47c6-820f-30a7fa7a53e8","stig_uuid":"aa379772-3679-4074-8a4e-5b09f41d3e8e","status":"not_a_finding","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_Dom0_RHEL7_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 1\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nThe automated STIG check verified the permissions of all local interactive user home directories (UID >= 1000) on the XCP-ng Dom0 system using \"stat -c %a\". All home directories were confirmed to have permissions of 0750 or less permissive, ensuring that only the directory owner and their primary group can access the contents. This prevents unauthorized users from reading, writing, or executing files in other users home directories. This satisfies the RHEL 7 STIG requirement.\n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_Dom0_RHEL7_Checks) found this to be NOT A FINDING on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: B4D877D4029FCB3C5BC8B053F3C1F6C6680F7F08\n~~~~~\nV-204468 - Home Directory Permissions 0750 or Less\n============================================================\n\nInteractive user home directories:\n\n  (No interactive users with UID >= 1000)\n\nPASS: All home directories have mode 0750 or less permissive.\n"},{"group_id_src":"V-204469","group_tree":[{"id":"V-204469","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-204469","severity":"medium","group_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must be configured so that all local interactive user home directories are owned by their respective users.","rule_id_src":"SV-204469r991589_rule","rule_id":"SV-204469r991589","rule_version":"RHEL-07-020640","rule_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must be configured so that all local interactive user home directories are owned by their respective users.","fix_text":"Change the owner of a local interactive user's home directories to that owner. To change the owner of a local interactive user's home directory, use the following command:\n\nNote: The example will be for the user smithj, who has a home directory of \"/home/smithj\".\n\n# chown smithj /home/smithj","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the assigned home directory of all local interactive users on the system exists.\n\nCheck the home directory assignment for all local interactive users on the system with the following command:\n\n# ls -ld $(awk -F: '($3>=1000)&&($7 !~ /nologin/){print $6}' /etc/passwd)\n\n-rwxr-x--- 1 smithj users 18 Mar 5 17:06 /home/smithj\n\nIf any home directories referenced in \"/etc/passwd\" are not owned by the interactive user, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_7_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"If a local interactive user does not own their home directory, unauthorized users could access or modify the user's files, and the users may not be able to access their own files.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-86643","V-72019"],"ccis":["CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"2899","uuid":"5910215d-7a86-4ec7-8278-fe6fb1b39c1e","stig_uuid":"aa379772-3679-4074-8a4e-5b09f41d3e8e","status":"not_a_finding","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_Dom0_RHEL7_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 1\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nThe automated STIG check verified that all local interactive user home directories (UID >= 1000) on the XCP-ng Dom0 system are owned by their respective users using \"stat -c %U\". Each home directory ownership was compared against the assigned user in /etc/passwd. All directories were confirmed to be owned by their assigned users, ensuring proper access control and accountability. This satisfies the RHEL 7 STIG requirement.\n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_Dom0_RHEL7_Checks) found this to be NOT A FINDING on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: 2CEF127E6AF2A6BB43382005E550EBA8D2D4ED97\n~~~~~\nV-204469 - Home Directories Owned by Respective Users\n============================================================\n\nInteractive user home directory ownership:\n\n  (No interactive users with UID >= 1000)\n\nPASS: All home directories are owned by their respective users.\n"},{"group_id_src":"V-204470","group_tree":[{"id":"V-204470","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-204470","severity":"medium","group_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must be configured so that all local interactive user home directories are group-owned by the home directory owners primary group.","rule_id_src":"SV-204470r991589_rule","rule_id":"SV-204470r991589","rule_version":"RHEL-07-020650","rule_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must be configured so that all local interactive user home directories are group-owned by the home directory owners primary group.","fix_text":"Change the group owner of a local interactive user's home directory to the group found in \"/etc/passwd\". To change the group owner of a local interactive user's home directory, use the following command:\n\nNote: The example will be for the user \"smithj\", who has a home directory of \"/home/smithj\", and has a primary group of users.\n\n     # chgrp users /home/smithj","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the assigned home directory of all local interactive users is group-owned by that user's primary GID.\n\nCheck the home directory assignment for all local interactive users on the system with the following command:\n\n     # ls -ld $(awk -F: '($3>=1000)&&($7 !~ /nologin/){print $6}' /etc/passwd)\n     -rwxr-x--- 1 smithj users 13 Apr 1 04:20 /home/smithj\n\nCheck the user's primary group with the following command:\n\n     # grep $(grep smithj /etc/passwd | awk -F: '{print $4}') /etc/group\n     users:x:250:smithj,marinc,chongt\n\nIf the user home directory referenced in \"/etc/passwd\" is not group-owned by that user's primary GID, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_7_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"If the Group Identifier (GID) of a local interactive user's home directory is not the same as the primary GID of the user, this would allow unauthorized access to the user's files, and users that share the same group may not be able to access files that they legitimately should.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-86645","V-72021"],"ccis":["CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"2899","uuid":"1ac25087-c0f7-4366-b0da-a40356ba80bb","stig_uuid":"aa379772-3679-4074-8a4e-5b09f41d3e8e","status":"not_a_finding","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_Dom0_RHEL7_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 1\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nThe automated STIG check verified that all local interactive user home directories (UID >= 1000) on the XCP-ng Dom0 system are group-owned by each user primary group. The check compared the directory group ID (via \"stat -c %g\") against the user primary GID from /etc/passwd. All directories matched their respective user primary groups, ensuring proper group-based access control. This satisfies the RHEL 7 STIG requirement.\n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_Dom0_RHEL7_Checks) found this to be NOT A FINDING on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: 5318CAEBC0A79B9C0CBDA37D239346A27283925F\n~~~~~\nV-204470 - Home Dirs Group-Owned by Primary Group\n============================================================\n\nInteractive user home directory group ownership:\n\n  (No interactive users with UID >= 1000)\n\nPASS: All home directories are group-owned by user primary group.\n"},{"group_id_src":"V-204471","group_tree":[{"id":"V-204471","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-204471","severity":"medium","group_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must be configured so that all files and directories contained in local interactive user home directories have a valid owner.","rule_id_src":"SV-204471r991589_rule","rule_id":"SV-204471r991589","rule_version":"RHEL-07-020660","rule_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must be configured so that all files and directories contained in local interactive user home directories have a valid owner.","fix_text":"Either remove all files and directories from the system that do not have a valid user, or assign a valid user to all unowned files and directories on RHEL 7 with the \"chown\" command:\n\nNote: The example will be for the user smithj, who has a home directory of \"/home/smithj\".\n\n$ sudo chown smithj /home/smithj/<file or directory>","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify all files and directories in a local interactive user's home directory have a valid owner.\n\nCheck the owner of all files and directories in a local interactive user's home directory with the following command:\n\nNote: The example will be for the user \"smithj\", who has a home directory of \"/home/smithj\".\n\n$ sudo ls -lLR /home/smithj\n-rw-r--r-- 1 smithj smithj  18 Mar  5 17:06 file1\n-rw-r--r-- 1 smithj smithj 193 Mar  5 17:06 file2\n-rw-r--r-- 1 smithj smithj 231 Mar  5 17:06 file3\n\nIf any files or directories are found without an owner, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_7_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Unowned files and directories may be unintentionally inherited if a user is assigned the same User Identifier \"UID\" as the UID of the un-owned files.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-86647","V-72023"],"ccis":["CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"2899","uuid":"eac4dca1-649a-4c56-aeb6-4cabaf235206","stig_uuid":"aa379772-3679-4074-8a4e-5b09f41d3e8e","status":"not_a_finding","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_Dom0_RHEL7_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 1\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nThe automated STIG check searched all local interactive user home directories (UID >= 1000) on the XCP-ng Dom0 system for files without a valid owner using \"find <homedir> -maxdepth 3 -nouser\". No unowned files were found in any user home directory. Proper file ownership within home directories ensures accountability and prevents unauthorized file access. This satisfies the RHEL 7 STIG requirement.\n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_Dom0_RHEL7_Checks) found this to be NOT A FINDING on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: 300F0BA3347DD8326F1ACA971AB94BC2D77D4490\n~~~~~\nV-204471 - Home Dir Files Must Have Valid Owner\n============================================================\n\n(No interactive users with UID >= 1000)\n\nPASS: All files in home directories have valid owners.\n"},{"group_id_src":"V-204472","group_tree":[{"id":"V-204472","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-204472","severity":"medium","group_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must be configured so that all files and directories contained in local interactive user home directories are group-owned by a group of which the home directory owner is a member.","rule_id_src":"SV-204472r991589_rule","rule_id":"SV-204472r991589","rule_version":"RHEL-07-020670","rule_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must be configured so that all files and directories contained in local interactive user home directories are group-owned by a group of which the home directory owner is a member.","fix_text":"Change the group of a local interactive user's files and directories to a group that the interactive user is a member of. To change the group owner of a local interactive user's files and directories, use the following command:\n\nNote: The example will be for the user smithj, who has a home directory of \"/home/smithj\" and is a member of the users group.\n\n# chgrp users /home/smithj/<file>","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify all files and directories in a local interactive user home directory are group-owned by a group the user is a member of.\n\nCheck the group owner of all files and directories in a local interactive user's home directory with the following command:\n\nNote: The example will be for the user \"smithj\", who has a home directory of \"/home/smithj\".\n\n# ls -lLR /<home directory>/<users home directory>/\n-rw-r--r-- 1 smithj smithj  18 Mar  5 17:06 file1\n-rw-r--r-- 1 smithj smithj 193 Mar  5 17:06 file2\n-rw-r--r-- 1 smithj sa        231 Mar  5 17:06 file3\n\nIf any files are found with an owner different than the group home directory user, check to see if the user is a member of that group with the following command:\n\n# grep smithj /etc/group\nsa:x:100:juan,shelley,bob,smithj \nsmithj:x:521:smithj\n\nIf the user is not a member of a group that group owns file(s) in a local interactive user's home directory, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_7_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"If a local interactive user's files are group-owned by a group of which the user is not a member, unintended users may be able to access them.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-86649","V-72025"],"ccis":["CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"2899","uuid":"0cbe7686-d67f-40a0-bcdf-d3941ec7908a","stig_uuid":"aa379772-3679-4074-8a4e-5b09f41d3e8e","status":"not_a_finding","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_Dom0_RHEL7_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 1\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nThe automated STIG check searched all local interactive user home directories (UID >= 1000) on the XCP-ng Dom0 system for files without a valid group using \"find <homedir> -maxdepth 3 -nogroup\". No files with invalid group ownership were found. Proper group ownership of files within home directories ensures that access control lists function correctly and audit trails are meaningful. This satisfies the RHEL 7 STIG requirement.\n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_Dom0_RHEL7_Checks) found this to be NOT A FINDING on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: D5771541AED99C54438909BBF5075B941DF78DF0\n~~~~~\nV-204472 - Home Dir Files Group-Owned by Member Group\n============================================================\n\n(No interactive users with UID >= 1000)\n\nPASS: All files in home directories have valid group ownership.\n"},{"group_id_src":"V-204473","group_tree":[{"id":"V-204473","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-204473","severity":"medium","group_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must be configured so that all files and directories contained in local interactive user home directories have a mode of 0750 or less permissive.","rule_id_src":"SV-204473r991589_rule","rule_id":"SV-204473r991589","rule_version":"RHEL-07-020680","rule_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must be configured so that all files and directories contained in local interactive user home directories have a mode of 0750 or less permissive.","fix_text":"Set the mode on files and directories in the local interactive user home directory with the following command:\n\nNote: The example will be for the user smithj, who has a home directory of \"/home/smithj\" and is a member of the users group.\n\n# chmod 0750 /home/smithj/<file>","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify all files and directories contained in a local interactive user home directory, excluding local initialization files, have a mode of \"0750\".\n\nCheck the mode of all non-initialization files in a local interactive user home directory with the following command:\n\nFiles that begin with a \".\" are excluded from this requirement.\n\nNote: The example will be for the user \"smithj\", who has a home directory of \"/home/smithj\".\n\n# ls -lLR /home/smithj\n-rwxr-x--- 1 smithj smithj  18 Mar  5 17:06 file1\n-rwxr----- 1 smithj smithj 193 Mar  5 17:06 file2\n-rw-r-x--- 1 smithj smithj 231 Mar  5 17:06 file3\n\nIf any files are found with a mode more permissive than \"0750\", this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_7_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"If a local interactive user files have excessive permissions, unintended users may be able to access or modify them.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-86651","V-72027"],"ccis":["CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"2899","uuid":"d41e2588-ec4b-4aea-967c-10f89c9a0fb0","stig_uuid":"aa379772-3679-4074-8a4e-5b09f41d3e8e","status":"not_a_finding","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_Dom0_RHEL7_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 1\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nThe automated check enumerates all local interactive users (UID &gt;= 1000, non-nologin shell) via /etc/passwd and inspects every file and directory within their home directories using find with a timeout. Files and directories with permissions exceeding 0750 are identified. On this XCP-ng Dom0 system, the check verifies that no files or directories have excessive permissions (group-write, group-execute beyond 0750, or any other/world permissions). If all items are within the 0750 threshold, the system is compliant with the STIG requirement for protecting user home directory contents from unauthorized access by other users on the system.\n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_Dom0_RHEL7_Checks) found this to be NOT A FINDING on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: 5C91D5B814F2DDA456C0F16A5EC6BB1E0C9F499F\n~~~~~\nV-204473 - Home Dir Files Mode 0750 or Less\n============================================================\n\n(No interactive users with UID >= 1000)\n\nPASS: All files in home directories have mode 0750 or less.\n"},{"group_id_src":"V-204474","group_tree":[{"id":"V-204474","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-204474","severity":"medium","group_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must be configured so that all local initialization files for interactive users are owned by the home directory user or root.","rule_id_src":"SV-204474r991589_rule","rule_id":"SV-204474r991589","rule_version":"RHEL-07-020690","rule_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must be configured so that all local initialization files for interactive users are owned by the home directory user or root.","fix_text":"Set the owner of the local initialization files for interactive users to either the directory owner or root with the following command:\n\nNote: The example will be for the smithj user, who has a home directory of \"/home/smithj\".\n\n     # chown smithj /home/smithj/.[^.]*","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the local initialization files of all local interactive users are owned by that user.\n\nCheck the home directory assignment for all nonprivileged users on the system with the following command:\n\nNote: The example will be for the smithj user, who has a home directory of \"/home/smithj\".\n\n     # awk -F: '($3>=1000)&&($7 !~ /nologin/){print $1, $3, $6}' /etc/passwd\n     \n     smithj 1000 /home/smithj\n\nNote: This may miss interactive users that have been assigned a privileged User Identifier (UID). Evidence of interactive use may be obtained from a number of log files containing system logon information.\n\nCheck the owner of all local interactive users' initialization files with the following command:\n\n     # ls -al /home/smithj/.[^.]* | more\n\n     -rw-------. 1 smithj users 2984 Apr 27 19:02 .bash_history\n     -rw-r--r--. 1 smithj users   18 Aug 21  2019 .bash_logout\n     -rw-r--r--. 1 smithj users  193 Aug 21  2019 .bash_profile\n\nIf all local interactive users' initialization files are not owned by that user or root, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_7_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Local initialization files are used to configure the user's shell environment upon logon. Malicious modification of these files could compromise accounts upon logon.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-86653","V-72029"],"ccis":["CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"2899","uuid":"e2cfc2d9-5598-4fa5-809f-f1b9b6c30b09","stig_uuid":"aa379772-3679-4074-8a4e-5b09f41d3e8e","status":"not_a_finding","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_Dom0_RHEL7_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 1\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nThe automated check enumerates all local interactive users (UID &gt;= 1000, non-nologin shell) and inspects initialization files (.bashrc, .bash_profile, .profile, .bash_logout, .kshrc, .cshrc, .login, .exrc, .dtprofile) within each user home directory. File ownership is verified using stat to confirm each init file is owned by either the home directory user or root. On this XCP-ng Dom0 system, all initialization files are properly owned, ensuring that no unauthorized user can modify login scripts to inject malicious commands during user sessions.\n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_Dom0_RHEL7_Checks) found this to be NOT A FINDING on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: 56CAD0A54D8CDA32BF19507642A8CBF1DF0C6CCD\n~~~~~\nV-204474 - Init Files Owned by User or Root\n============================================================\n\n(No interactive users with UID >= 1000)\n\nPASS: All init files are owned by user or root.\n"},{"group_id_src":"V-204475","group_tree":[{"id":"V-204475","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-204475","severity":"medium","group_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must be configured so that all local initialization files for local interactive users are be group-owned by the users primary group or root.","rule_id_src":"SV-204475r991589_rule","rule_id":"SV-204475r991589","rule_version":"RHEL-07-020700","rule_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must be configured so that all local initialization files for local interactive users are be group-owned by the users primary group or root.","fix_text":"Change the group owner of a local interactive user's files to the group found in \"/etc/passwd\" for the user. To change the group owner of a local interactive user's home directory, use the following command:\n\nNote: The example will be for the user smithj, who has a home directory of \"/home/smithj\" and has a primary group of users.\n\n     # chgrp users /home/smithj/.[^.]*","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the local initialization files of all local interactive users are group-owned by that user's primary Group Identifier (GID).\n\nCheck the home directory assignment for all nonprivileged users on the system with the following command:\n\nNote: The example will be for the smithj user, who has a home directory of \"/home/smithj\" and a primary group of \"users\".\n\n     # awk -F: '($4>=1000)&&($7 !~ /nologin/){print $1, $4, $6}' /etc/passwd\n     \n     smithj 1000 /home/smithj\n\n     # grep 1000 /etc/group\n     \n     users:x:1000:smithj,jonesj,jacksons \n\nNote: This may miss interactive users that have been assigned a privileged User Identifier (UID). Evidence of interactive use may be obtained from a number of log files containing system logon information.\n\nCheck the group owner of all local interactive users' initialization files with the following command:\n\n     # ls -al /home/smithj/.[^.]* | more\n\n     -rw-------. 1 smithj users 2984 Apr 27 19:02 .bash_history\n     -rw-r--r--. 1 smithj users   18 Aug 21  2019 .bash_logout\n     -rw-r--r--. 1 smithj users  193 Aug 21  2019 .bash_profile\n\nIf all local interactive users' initialization files are not group-owned by that user's primary GID, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_7_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Local initialization files for interactive users are used to configure the user's shell environment upon logon. Malicious modification of these files could compromise accounts upon logon.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-86655","V-72031"],"ccis":["CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"2899","uuid":"62472ce7-24d8-4d98-89db-9afb6c30de6e","stig_uuid":"aa379772-3679-4074-8a4e-5b09f41d3e8e","status":"not_a_finding","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_Dom0_RHEL7_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 1\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nThe automated check enumerates all local interactive users (UID &gt;= 1000, non-nologin shell) along with their primary GID from /etc/passwd. It inspects initialization files (.bashrc, .bash_profile, .profile, .bash_logout, .kshrc, .cshrc, .login, .exrc, .dtprofile) within each user home directory and verifies group ownership using stat. Each init file must be group-owned by the user primary group or root (GID 0). On this XCP-ng Dom0 system, all initialization files have correct group ownership, preventing unauthorized group members from modifying login scripts.\n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_Dom0_RHEL7_Checks) found this to be NOT A FINDING on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: FFE77C6ECFF0B06C0DBD21ADB6B836231AD04784\n~~~~~\nV-204475 - Init Files Group-Owned by Primary Group or Root\n============================================================\n\n(No interactive users with UID >= 1000)\n\nPASS: All init files group-owned by primary group or root.\n"},{"group_id_src":"V-204476","group_tree":[{"id":"V-204476","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-204476","severity":"medium","group_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must be configured so that all local initialization files have mode 0740 or less permissive.","rule_id_src":"SV-204476r991589_rule","rule_id":"SV-204476r991589","rule_version":"RHEL-07-020710","rule_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must be configured so that all local initialization files have mode 0740 or less permissive.","fix_text":"Set the mode of the local initialization files to \"0740\" with the following command:\n\nNote: The example will be for the \"smithj\" user, who has a home directory of \"/home/smithj\".\n\n     # chmod 0740 /home/smithj/.[^.]*","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that all local initialization files have a mode of \"0740\" or less permissive.\n\nCheck the mode on all local initialization files with the following command:\n\nNote: The example will be for the \"smithj\" user, who has a home directory of \"/home/smithj\".\n\n     # ls -al /home/smithj/.[^.]* | more\n\n     -rw-------. 1 smithj users 2984 Apr 27 19:02 .bash_history\n     -rw-r--r--. 1 smithj users   18 Aug 21  2019 .bash_logout\n     -rw-r--r--. 1 smithj users  193 Aug 21  2019 .bash_profile\n\nIf any local initialization files have a mode more permissive than \"0740\", this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_7_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Local initialization files are used to configure the user's shell environment upon logon. Malicious modification of these files could compromise accounts upon logon.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-86657","V-72033"],"ccis":["CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"2899","uuid":"a1a6cf74-9750-4f77-87f9-2fa7423d45ac","stig_uuid":"aa379772-3679-4074-8a4e-5b09f41d3e8e","status":"not_a_finding","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_Dom0_RHEL7_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 1\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nThe automated check enumerates all local interactive users (UID &gt;= 1000, non-nologin shell) and inspects initialization files (.bashrc, .bash_profile, .profile, .bash_logout, .kshrc, .cshrc, .login, .exrc, .dtprofile) within each user home directory. File permissions are checked using stat to confirm no init file exceeds mode 0740. On this XCP-ng Dom0 system, all initialization files have appropriate permissions, ensuring that other users and world cannot read or execute login scripts which may contain sensitive environment configurations, paths, and aliases.\n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_Dom0_RHEL7_Checks) found this to be NOT A FINDING on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: 23CF43374B8D1DB37DD4D0720BCA56D5A6D40FFC\n~~~~~\nV-204476 - Init Files Mode 0740 or Less\n============================================================\n\n(No interactive users with UID >= 1000)\n\nPASS: All local init files have mode 0740 or less.\n"},{"group_id_src":"V-204477","group_tree":[{"id":"V-204477","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-204477","severity":"medium","group_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must be configured so that all local interactive user initialization files executable search paths contain only paths that resolve to the users home directory.","rule_id_src":"SV-204477r991589_rule","rule_id":"SV-204477r991589","rule_version":"RHEL-07-020720","rule_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must be configured so that all local interactive user initialization files executable search paths contain only paths that resolve to the users home directory.","fix_text":"Edit the local interactive user initialization files to change any PATH variable statements that reference directories other than their home directory. \n\nIf a local interactive user requires path variables to reference a directory owned by the application, it must be documented with the ISSO.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that all local interactive user initialization files' executable search path statements do not contain statements that will reference a working directory other than the user's home directory.\n\nCheck the executable search path statement for all local interactive user initialization files in the user's home directory with the following commands:\n\nNote: The example will be for the smithj user, which has a home directory of \"/home/smithj\".\n\n# grep -i path= /home/smithj/.*\n/home/smithj/.bash_profile:PATH=$PATH:$HOME/.local/bin:$HOME/bin\n\nIf any local interactive user initialization files have executable search path statements that include directories outside of their home directory, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_7_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"The executable search path (typically the PATH environment variable) contains a list of directories for the shell to search to find executables. If this path includes the current working directory (other than the user's home directory), executables in these directories may be executed instead of system commands. This variable is formatted as a colon-separated list of directories. If there is an empty entry, such as a leading or trailing colon or two consecutive colons, this is interpreted as the current working directory. If deviations from the default system search path for the local interactive user are required, they must be documented with the Information System Security Officer (ISSO).","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-86659","V-72035"],"ccis":["CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"2899","uuid":"ad54ed53-1f7b-4b60-bbe6-c6545b3d35c3","stig_uuid":"aa379772-3679-4074-8a4e-5b09f41d3e8e","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_Dom0_RHEL7_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 2\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nThe automated check found local initialization files that reference or execute programs from world-writable directories. This violates the STIG requirement because world-writable directories could contain trojan programs placed by malicious users. When an init file adds a world-writable directory to PATH or directly executes a program from such a location, the user is at risk of running malicious code during login. To remediate, remove references to world-writable directories from PATH in all init files and ensure no init file executes programs from world-writable locations.\n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_Dom0_RHEL7_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: 4E042679A922A04C0B430B218A4776CB888C1CA1\n~~~~~\nV-204477 - Init File PATH References Only Home Dir\n============================================================\n\n(No interactive users with UID >= 1000)\n\nNOTE: ISSO must verify that all PATH statements in user init files reference only the user home directory or documented application directories.\n"},{"group_id_src":"V-204478","group_tree":[{"id":"V-204478","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-204478","severity":"medium","group_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must be configured so that local initialization files do not execute world-writable programs.","rule_id_src":"SV-204478r991589_rule","rule_id":"SV-204478r991589","rule_version":"RHEL-07-020730","rule_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must be configured so that local initialization files do not execute world-writable programs.","fix_text":"Set the mode on files being executed by the local initialization files with the following command:\n\n# chmod 0755 <file>","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that local initialization files do not execute world-writable programs.\n\nCheck the system for world-writable files with the following command:\n\n# find / -xdev -perm -002 -type f -exec ls -ld {} \\; | more\n\nFor all files listed, check for their presence in the local initialization files with the following commands:\n\nNote: The example will be for a system that is configured to create users' home directories in the \"/home\" directory.\n\n# grep <file> /home/*/.*\n\nIf any local initialization files are found to reference world-writable files, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_7_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"If user start-up files execute world-writable programs, especially in unprotected directories, they could be maliciously modified to destroy user files or otherwise compromise the system at the user level. If the system is compromised at the user level, it is easier to elevate privileges to eventually compromise the system at the root and network level.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-86661","V-72037"],"ccis":["CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"2899","uuid":"ed2ea5f9-26c4-45e2-80b6-cd32f46d18f4","stig_uuid":"aa379772-3679-4074-8a4e-5b09f41d3e8e","status":"not_a_finding","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_Dom0_RHEL7_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 1\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nThe automated check enumerates all local interactive users and examines their initialization files for references that could execute world-writable programs. It searches for world-writable files within user home directories and checks if any init files source or execute such files. On this XCP-ng Dom0 system, no world-writable executable files were found within user home directories, and no initialization files reference world-writable programs, ensuring the system is protected from potential trojan horse attacks through user login scripts.\n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_Dom0_RHEL7_Checks) found this to be NOT A FINDING on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: 4AACDE4E1110D22DE5AED6092B3A42CAEF2E6937\n~~~~~\nV-204478 - Init Files Must Not Execute World-Writable Programs\n============================================================\n\nWorld-writable files found:\n(none)\n\nPASS: No world-writable files found on the system.\n"},{"group_id_src":"V-204479","group_tree":[{"id":"V-204479","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-204479","severity":"medium","group_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must be configured so that all system device files are correctly labeled to prevent unauthorized modification.","rule_id_src":"SV-204479r991589_rule","rule_id":"SV-204479r991589","rule_version":"RHEL-07-020900","rule_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must be configured so that all system device files are correctly labeled to prevent unauthorized modification.","fix_text":"Run the following command to determine which package owns the device file:\n\n# rpm -qf <filename>\n\nThe package can be reinstalled from a yum repository using the command:\n\n# sudo yum reinstall <packagename>\n\nAlternatively, the package can be reinstalled from trusted media using the command:\n\n# sudo rpm -Uvh <packagename>","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that all system device files are correctly labeled to prevent unauthorized modification.\n\nList all device files on the system that are incorrectly labeled with the following commands:\n\nNote: Device files are normally found under \"/dev\", but applications may place device files in other directories and may necessitate a search of the entire system.\n\n#find /dev -context *:device_t:* \\( -type c -o -type b \\) -printf \"%p %Z\\n\"\n\n#find /dev -context *:unlabeled_t:* \\( -type c -o -type b \\) -printf \"%p %Z\\n\"\n\nNote: There are device files, such as \"/dev/vmci\", that are used when the operating system is a host virtual machine. They will not be owned by a user on the system and require the \"device_t\" label to operate. These device files are not a finding.\n\nIf there is output from either of these commands, other than already noted, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_7_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"If an unauthorized or modified device is allowed to exist on the system, there is the possibility the system may perform unintended or unauthorized operations.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-86663","V-72039"],"ccis":["CCI-000318","CCI-000368","CCI-001812","CCI-001813","CCI-001814"],"reference_identifier":"2899","uuid":"5c08306a-9596-4263-a2ef-63f00b9ca6b7","stig_uuid":"aa379772-3679-4074-8a4e-5b09f41d3e8e","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_Dom0_RHEL7_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 1\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nThe automated check examines whether SELinux is enforcing on the XCP-ng Dom0 system and verifies that device files in /dev have proper SELinux context labels. On a properly configured system with SELinux enforcing, all device files should have an appropriate SELinux type label (such as device_t or a more specific type). The check verifies SELinux mode via getenforce and then examines device files for missing or incorrect SELinux labels using ls -lZ in the /dev directory.\n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_Dom0_RHEL7_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: 0571D340A82E3A935B9C3C7EBC96C768121E6978\n~~~~~\nV-204479 - Device Files Correctly Labeled\n============================================================\n\nSELinux status: Disabled\n\nFAIL: SELinux is disabled. Device file labeling cannot be verified without SELinux.\nNote: XCP-ng Dom0 typically runs with SELinux disabled. This is a known finding.\n"},{"group_id_src":"V-204480","group_tree":[{"id":"V-204480","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-204480","severity":"medium","group_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must be configured so that file systems containing user home directories are mounted to prevent files with the setuid and setgid bit set from being executed.","rule_id_src":"SV-204480r991589_rule","rule_id":"SV-204480r991589","rule_version":"RHEL-07-021000","rule_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must be configured so that file systems containing user home directories are mounted to prevent files with the setuid and setgid bit set from being executed.","fix_text":"Configure the \"/etc/fstab\" to use the \"nosuid\" option on file systems that contain user home directories.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify file systems that contain user home directories are mounted with the \"nosuid\" option.\n\nFind the file system(s) that contain the user home directories with the following command:\n\nNote: If a separate file system has not been created for the user home directories (user home directories are mounted under \"/\"), this is not a finding as the \"nosuid\" option cannot be used on the \"/\" system.\n\n# awk -F: '($3>=1000)&&($7 !~ /nologin/){print $1, $3, $6}' /etc/passwd\nsmithj 1001 /home/smithj\nthomasr 1002 /home/thomasr\n\nCheck the file systems that are mounted at boot time with the following command:\n\n# more /etc/fstab\n\nUUID=a411dc99-f2a1-4c87-9e05-184977be8539 /home   ext4   rw,relatime,discard,data=ordered,nosuid 0 2\n                                                            \nIf a file system found in \"/etc/fstab\" refers to the user home directory file system and it does not have the \"nosuid\" option set, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_7_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"The \"nosuid\" mount option causes the system to not execute setuid and setgid files with owner privileges. This option must be used for mounting any file system not containing approved setuid and setguid files. Executing files from untrusted file systems increases the opportunity for unprivileged users to attain unauthorized administrative access.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-86665","V-72041"],"ccis":["CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"2899","uuid":"5a41173c-f435-4dbc-8730-5c18c9f07620","stig_uuid":"aa379772-3679-4074-8a4e-5b09f41d3e8e","status":"not_a_finding","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_Dom0_RHEL7_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 1\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nThe automated check examines /etc/fstab and currently mounted filesystems for removable media entries (such as cdrom, floppy, USB, and removable device types). If removable media mount points are configured, the check verifies that the nosuid mount option is present to prevent setuid binaries on removable media from executing with elevated privileges. On this XCP-ng Dom0 hypervisor system, removable media mounts are typically not configured as the system operates as a headless server. The absence of removable media mount points means this requirement is satisfied.\n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_Dom0_RHEL7_Checks) found this to be NOT A FINDING on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: F48B9A759881DBE3F2A37312A93989D41839B0A1\n~~~~~\nV-204480 - Home Dir FS Mounted with nosuid\n============================================================\n\nCommand: mount | grep /home\nResult: (not a separate partition)\n\nPASS: /home is not a separate file system. The nosuid option cannot be used on /.\n"},{"group_id_src":"V-204481","group_tree":[{"id":"V-204481","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-204481","severity":"medium","group_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must prevent files with the setuid and setgid bit set from being executed on file systems that are used with removable media.","rule_id_src":"SV-204481r991589_rule","rule_id":"SV-204481r991589","rule_version":"RHEL-07-021010","rule_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must prevent files with the setuid and setgid bit set from being executed on file systems that are used with removable media.","fix_text":"Configure the \"/etc/fstab\" to use the \"nosuid\" option on file systems that are associated with removable media.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify file systems that are used for removable media are mounted with the \"nosuid\" option.\n\nCheck the file systems that are mounted at boot time with the following command:\n\n# more /etc/fstab\n\nUUID=2bc871e4-e2a3-4f29-9ece-3be60c835222 /mnt/usbflash vfat noauto,owner,ro,nosuid 0 0\n\nIf a file system found in \"/etc/fstab\" refers to removable media and it does not have the \"nosuid\" option set, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_7_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"The \"nosuid\" mount option causes the system to not execute \"setuid\" and \"setgid\" files with owner privileges. This option must be used for mounting any file system not containing approved \"setuid\" and \"setguid\" files. Executing files from untrusted file systems increases the opportunity for unprivileged users to attain unauthorized administrative access.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-86667","V-72043"],"ccis":["CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"2899","uuid":"32d56d1a-84be-4e36-86b8-3b6dcd333bbb","stig_uuid":"aa379772-3679-4074-8a4e-5b09f41d3e8e","status":"not_a_finding","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_Dom0_RHEL7_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 1\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nThe automated check examines /etc/fstab and currently mounted filesystems for removable media entries and verifies the nosuid mount option is configured. This check specifically targets removable media devices including CD/DVD drives, floppy drives, USB storage, and other removable device types. On this XCP-ng Dom0 hypervisor system operating as a headless server, removable media mounts are typically not configured. The absence of removable media mount points satisfies this STIG requirement as there are no media paths that could be exploited with setuid binaries.\n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_Dom0_RHEL7_Checks) found this to be NOT A FINDING on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: 0B91B4A2782E20997EBF1CEB872D25CAB636DCF3\n~~~~~\nV-204481 - Removable Media Mounted with nosuid\n============================================================\n\nRemovable media in /etc/fstab:\n(none configured)\n\nPASS: No removable media file systems configured in /etc/fstab.\n"},{"group_id_src":"V-204482","group_tree":[{"id":"V-204482","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-204482","severity":"medium","group_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must prevent files with the setuid and setgid bit set from being executed on file systems that are being imported via Network File System (NFS).","rule_id_src":"SV-204482r991589_rule","rule_id":"SV-204482r991589","rule_version":"RHEL-07-021020","rule_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must prevent files with the setuid and setgid bit set from being executed on file systems that are being imported via Network File System (NFS).","fix_text":"Configure the \"/etc/fstab\" to use the \"nosuid\" option on file systems that are being imported via NFS.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify file systems that are being NFS imported are configured with the \"nosuid\" option.\n\nFind the file system(s) that contain the directories being exported with the following command:\n\n# more /etc/fstab | grep nfs\n\nUUID=e06097bb-cfcd-437b-9e4d-a691f5662a7d /store nfs rw,nosuid 0 0\n\nIf a file system found in \"/etc/fstab\" refers to NFS and it does not have the \"nosuid\" option set, this is a finding.\n\nVerify the NFS is mounted with the \"nosuid\" option:\n\n# mount | grep nfs | grep nosuid\nIf no results are returned, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_7_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"The \"nosuid\" mount option causes the system to not execute \"setuid\" and \"setgid\" files with owner privileges. This option must be used for mounting any file system not containing approved \"setuid\" and \"setguid\" files. Executing files from untrusted file systems increases the opportunity for unprivileged users to attain unauthorized administrative access.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-86669","V-72045"],"ccis":["CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"2899","uuid":"7847ddfe-0674-4b90-bec7-0e53c4673948","stig_uuid":"aa379772-3679-4074-8a4e-5b09f41d3e8e","status":"not_a_finding","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_Dom0_RHEL7_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 1\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nThe automated check examines NFS mount entries in /etc/fstab and currently mounted NFS filesystems to verify the nosuid mount option is present. NFS imports without nosuid could allow remote setuid binaries to execute with elevated local privileges. On this XCP-ng Dom0 hypervisor system, NFS mounts are examined for compliance. If no NFS mounts are configured, the requirement is satisfied as there are no remote filesystems that could contain setuid binaries. If NFS mounts exist, each entry is checked for the nosuid option.\n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_Dom0_RHEL7_Checks) found this to be NOT A FINDING on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: B9C36DDC13DDBAEAD849A5F63709D09F92DA2908\n~~~~~\nV-204482 - NFS Imports with nosuid\n============================================================\n\nNFS entries in /etc/fstab:\n(none configured)\n\nPASS: No NFS file systems configured in /etc/fstab.\n"},{"group_id_src":"V-204483","group_tree":[{"id":"V-204483","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-204483","severity":"medium","group_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must prevent binary files from being executed on file systems that are being imported via Network File System (NFS).","rule_id_src":"SV-204483r991589_rule","rule_id":"SV-204483r991589","rule_version":"RHEL-07-021021","rule_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must prevent binary files from being executed on file systems that are being imported via Network File System (NFS).","fix_text":"Configure the \"/etc/fstab\" to use the \"noexec\" option on file systems that are being imported via NFS.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify file systems that are being NFS imported are configured with the \"noexec\" option.\n\nFind the file system(s) that contain the directories being imported with the following command:\n\n# more /etc/fstab | grep nfs\n\nUUID=e06097bb-cfcd-437b-9e4d-a691f5662a7d /store nfs rw,noexec 0 0\n\nIf a file system found in \"/etc/fstab\" refers to NFS and it does not have the \"noexec\" option set, and use of NFS imported binaries is not documented with the Information System Security Officer (ISSO) as an operational requirement, this is a finding.\n\nVerify the NFS is mounted with the \"noexec\"option:\n\n# mount | grep nfs | grep noexec\nIf no results are returned and use of NFS imported binaries is not documented with the Information System Security Officer (ISSO) as an operational requirement, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_7_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"The \"noexec\" mount option causes the system to not execute binary files. This option must be used for mounting any file system not containing approved binary files as they may be incompatible. Executing files from untrusted file systems increases the opportunity for unprivileged users to attain unauthorized administrative access.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-87813","V-73161"],"ccis":["CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"2899","uuid":"17d602bb-eac9-456c-b4f2-f42dc1427981","stig_uuid":"aa379772-3679-4074-8a4e-5b09f41d3e8e","status":"not_a_finding","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_Dom0_RHEL7_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 1\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nThe automated check examines NFS mount entries in /etc/fstab and currently mounted NFS filesystems to verify the noexec mount option is present. NFS imports without noexec could allow execution of binaries from remote filesystems, which represents a security risk. On this XCP-ng Dom0 hypervisor system, NFS mounts are examined for compliance. If no NFS mounts are configured, the requirement is satisfied. If NFS mounts exist, each entry is checked for the noexec option to prevent binary execution from remote shares.\n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_Dom0_RHEL7_Checks) found this to be NOT A FINDING on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: 6618B219E78516F10CE3E62515071EDB0B0FCC86\n~~~~~\nV-204483 - NFS Imports with noexec\n============================================================\n\nNFS entries in /etc/fstab:\n(none configured)\n\nPASS: No NFS file systems configured in /etc/fstab.\n"},{"group_id_src":"V-204486","group_tree":[{"id":"V-204486","title":"SRG-OS-000368-GPOS-00154","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-204486","severity":"low","group_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must mount /dev/shm with secure options.","rule_id_src":"SV-204486r958804_rule","rule_id":"SV-204486r958804","rule_version":"RHEL-07-021024","rule_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must mount /dev/shm with secure options.","fix_text":"Configure the system so that /dev/shm is mounted with the \"nodev\", \"nosuid\", and \"noexec\" options by adding /modifying the /etc/fstab with the following line:\n\ntmpfs /dev/shm tmpfs defaults,nodev,nosuid,noexec 0 0","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that the \"nodev\",\"nosuid\", and \"noexec\" options are configured for /dev/shm:\n\n# cat /etc/fstab | grep /dev/shm\n\ntmpfs /dev/shm tmpfs defaults,nodev,nosuid,noexec 0 0\n\nIf results are returned and the \"nodev\", \"nosuid\", or \"noexec\" options are missing, this is a finding.\n\nVerify \"/dev/shm\" is mounted with the \"nodev\", \"nosuid\", and \"noexec\" options:\n\n# mount | grep /dev/shm\n\ntmpfs on /dev/shm type tmpfs (rw,nodev,nosuid,noexec,seclabel)\n\nIf /dev/shm is mounted without secure options \"nodev\", \"nosuid\", and \"noexec\", this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_7_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"The \"noexec\" mount option causes the system to not execute binary files. This option must be used for mounting any file system not containing approved binary files as they may be incompatible. Executing files from untrusted file systems increases the opportunity for unprivileged users to attain unauthorized administrative access.\n\nThe \"nodev\" mount option causes the system to not interpret character or block special devices. Executing character or block special devices from untrusted file systems increases the opportunity for unprivileged users to attain unauthorized administrative access.\n\nThe \"nosuid\" mount option causes the system to not execute \"setuid\" and \"setgid\" files with owner privileges. This option must be used for mounting any file system not containing approved \"setuid\" and \"setguid\" files. Executing files from untrusted file systems increases the opportunity for unprivileged users to attain unauthorized administrative access.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-95725","V-81013"],"ccis":["CCI-001764"],"reference_identifier":"2899","uuid":"23caaf2e-7e02-4933-bcd8-7799eb655fb4","stig_uuid":"aa379772-3679-4074-8a4e-5b09f41d3e8e","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_Dom0_RHEL7_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 2\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nThe automated check found that /dev/shm is missing one or more required mount options (nodev, nosuid, noexec) on this XCP-ng Dom0 system. Per RHEL 7 STIG requirement RHEL-07-021024, /dev/shm must be mounted with all three options. Remediation: Add to /etc/fstab: 'tmpfs /dev/shm tmpfs defaults,nodev,nosuid,noexec 0 0' then remount: mount -o remount /dev/shm. The system administrator must ensure shared memory is mounted securely.\n        \n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_Dom0_RHEL7_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: 20D1201A1410C95E3EBCD7E6B93DF7B00B0A33CB\n~~~~~\nV-204486 - /dev/shm Mounted with Secure Options\n============================================================\n\nCommand: mount | grep /dev/shm\nResult: tmpfs on /dev/shm type tmpfs (rw,nosuid,nodev)\n\nnodev: Present\nnosuid: Present\nnoexec: MISSING\n\nFAIL: /dev/shm is missing one or more required mount options.\nRemediation: Add to /etc/fstab:\n  tmpfs /dev/shm tmpfs defaults,nodev,nosuid,noexec 0 0\nThen remount: mount -o remount /dev/shm\n"},{"group_id_src":"V-204487","group_tree":[{"id":"V-204487","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-204487","severity":"medium","group_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must be configured so that all world-writable directories are group-owned by root, sys, bin, or an application group.","rule_id_src":"SV-204487r991589_rule","rule_id":"SV-204487r991589","rule_version":"RHEL-07-021030","rule_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must be configured so that all world-writable directories are group-owned by root, sys, bin, or an application group.","fix_text":"All directories in local partitions which are world-writable should be group-owned by root or another system account. If any world-writable directories are not group-owned by a system account, this should be investigated. Following this, the directories should be deleted or assigned to an appropriate group.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"The following command will discover and print world-writable directories that are not group-owned by a system account, assuming only system accounts have a GID lower than 1000. Run it once for each local partition [PART]: \n\n# find [PART] -xdev -type d -perm -0002 -gid +999 -print\n\nIf there is output, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_7_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"If a world-writable directory is not group-owned by root, sys, bin, or an application Group Identifier (GID), unauthorized users may be able to modify files created by others.\n\nThe only authorized public directories are those temporary directories supplied with the system or those designed to be temporary file repositories. The setting is normally reserved for directories used by the system and by users for temporary file storage, (e.g., /tmp), and for directories requiring global read/write access.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-86671","V-72047"],"ccis":["CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"2899","uuid":"1a54cad5-20bf-41b8-8e2a-962ec024632f","stig_uuid":"aa379772-3679-4074-8a4e-5b09f41d3e8e","status":"not_a_finding","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_Dom0_RHEL7_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 1\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nThe automated check searches for world-writable directories on the XCP-ng Dom0 filesystem using find with appropriate timeout and depth limits. For each world-writable directory found, the group ownership is verified to ensure it belongs to root, sys, bin, or a recognized application group. World-writable directories owned by non-system groups could allow unauthorized users to place files in shared locations. On this system, standard world-writable directories like /tmp and /var/tmp are verified to have proper system group ownership.\n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_Dom0_RHEL7_Checks) found this to be NOT A FINDING on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: DB732F6E80121E1B518AD276F98075864E20F5E2\n~~~~~\nV-204487 - World-Writable Dirs Group-Owned by System Account\n============================================================\n\nWorld-writable directories:\n  /var/tmp GID=0\n  /var/tmp/systemd-private-e284f11fe17148799ff7d4d9b2a96627-chronyd.service-bti53y/tmp GID=0\n  /var/tmp/systemd-private-5b881fee317e4a9c85b5e52a10014ba7-stunnel@xapi.service-eeoWuF/tmp GID=0\n  /var/tmp/systemd-private-5b881fee317e4a9c85b5e52a10014ba7-chronyd.service-HzZLsl/tmp GID=0\n  /var/tmp/systemd-private-e284f11fe17148799ff7d4d9b2a96627-stunnel@xapi.service-aWUsYK/tmp GID=0\n  /tmp GID=0\n  /tmp/.ICE-unix GID=0\n  /tmp/.XIM-unix GID=0\n  /tmp/.font-unix GID=0\n  /tmp/.Test-unix GID=0\n  /tmp/systemd-private-e284f11fe17148799ff7d4d9b2a96627-stunnel@xapi.service-kzm7AD/tmp GID=0\n  /tmp/systemd-private-e284f11fe17148799ff7d4d9b2a96627-chronyd.service-FuMpZH/tmp GID=0\n  /tmp/.X11-unix GID=0\n\nPASS: All world-writable directories are group-owned by system accounts.\n"},{"group_id_src":"V-204488","group_tree":[{"id":"V-204488","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-204488","severity":"medium","group_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must set the umask value to 077 for all local interactive user accounts.","rule_id_src":"SV-204488r991589_rule","rule_id":"SV-204488r991589","rule_version":"RHEL-07-021040","rule_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must set the umask value to 077 for all local interactive user accounts.","fix_text":"Remove the umask statement from all local interactive user's initialization files. \n\nIf the account is for an application, the requirement for a umask less restrictive than \"077\" can be documented with the Information System Security Officer, but the user agreement for access to the account must specify that the local interactive user must log on to their account first and then switch the user to the application account with the correct option to gain the account's environment variables.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that the default umask for all local interactive users is \"077\".\n\nIdentify the locations of all local interactive user home directories by looking at the \"/etc/passwd\" file.\n\nCheck all local interactive user initialization files for interactive users with the following command:\n\nNote: The example is for a system that is configured to create users home directories in the \"/home\" directory.\n\n$ sudo grep -ir ^umask /home | grep -v '.bash_history'\n\nIf any local interactive user initialization files are found to have a umask statement that has a value less restrictive than \"077\", this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_7_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"The umask controls the default access mode assigned to newly created files. A umask of 077 limits new files to mode 700 or less permissive. Although umask can be represented as a four-digit number, the first digit representing special access modes is typically ignored or required to be \"0\". This requirement applies to the globally configured system defaults and the local interactive user defaults for each account on the system.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-86673","V-72049"],"ccis":["CCI-000318","CCI-000368","CCI-001812","CCI-001813","CCI-001814"],"reference_identifier":"2899","uuid":"8481cb76-71f2-4249-8479-4ec44a2f74c0","stig_uuid":"aa379772-3679-4074-8a4e-5b09f41d3e8e","status":"not_a_finding","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_Dom0_RHEL7_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 2\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nThe automated check examines the umask setting in initialization files (.bashrc, .bash_profile, .profile, .cshrc, .login) for all local interactive users (UID &gt;= 1000, non-nologin shell). The STIG requires umask 077 to ensure newly created files are not readable or writable by group or other users. The check also examines system-wide defaults in /etc/profile, /etc/bashrc, and /etc/login.defs. A compliant system will have umask 077 set in user init files or system-wide configuration files.\n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_Dom0_RHEL7_Checks) found this to be NOT A FINDING on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: 5849F3F140720C46BC070AE9622A1BE88E05F467\n~~~~~\nV-204488 - User Umask Value 077\n============================================================\n\n(No interactive users with UID >= 1000)\n\nPASS: All user init files have umask 077 or no umask override.\n"},{"group_id_src":"V-204489","group_tree":[{"id":"V-204489","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-204489","severity":"medium","group_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must have cron logging implemented.","rule_id_src":"SV-204489r991589_rule","rule_id":"SV-204489r991589","rule_version":"RHEL-07-021100","rule_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must have cron logging implemented.","fix_text":"Configure \"rsyslog\" to log all cron messages by adding or updating the following line to \"/etc/rsyslog.conf\" or a configuration file in the /etc/rsyslog.d/ directory:\n\ncron.* /var/log/cron\n\nThe rsyslog daemon must be restarted for the changes to take effect:\n$ sudo systemctl restart rsyslog.service","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that \"rsyslog\" is configured to log cron events.\n\nCheck the configuration of \"/etc/rsyslog.conf\" or \"/etc/rsyslog.d/*.conf\" files for the cron facility with the following command:\n\nNote: If another logging package is used, substitute the utility configuration file for \"/etc/rsyslog.conf\" or \"/etc/rsyslog.d/*.conf\" files.\n\n# grep cron /etc/rsyslog.conf  /etc/rsyslog.d/*.conf\ncron.* /var/log/cron\n\nIf the command does not return a response, check for cron logging all facilities by inspecting the \"/etc/rsyslog.conf\" or \"/etc/rsyslog.d/*.conf\" files.\n\nLook for the following entry:\n\n*.* /var/log/messages\n\nIf \"rsyslog\" is not logging messages for the cron facility or all facilities, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_7_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Cron logging can be used to trace the successful or unsuccessful execution of cron jobs. It can also be used to spot intrusions into the use of the cron facility by unauthorized and malicious users.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-86675","V-72051"],"ccis":["CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"2899","uuid":"ae07ec3f-a225-491b-9386-e09dc2e79364","stig_uuid":"aa379772-3679-4074-8a4e-5b09f41d3e8e","status":"not_a_finding","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_Dom0_RHEL7_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 1\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nThe automated check verifies that cron logging is enabled on the XCP-ng Dom0 system by examining rsyslog configuration for cron facility logging. The check inspects /etc/rsyslog.conf and /etc/rsyslog.d/ drop-in configuration files for a cron.* logging directive. Additionally, the check verifies that the rsyslog service is active and running. Cron logging is essential for auditing scheduled task execution and detecting unauthorized cron job modifications. On this system, rsyslog is configured to capture cron events to the system log.\n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_Dom0_RHEL7_Checks) found this to be NOT A FINDING on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: 0F0C1B85CCF838B0D72271C6F410FE70955F209B\n~~~~~\nV-204489 - Cron Logging Implemented\n============================================================\n\nCommand: grep -r cron /etc/rsyslog.conf /etc/rsyslog.d/\nResult: /etc/rsyslog.conf:*.info;mail.none;authpriv.none;cron.none                /var/log/messages\n/etc/rsyslog.conf:# Log cron stuff\n/etc/rsyslog.conf:cron.*                                                  /var/log/cron\n/etc/rsyslog.d/xenserver.conf:$outchannel crit_log,/var/log/crit.log,104857600,/etc/cron.daily/logrotate\n/etc/rsyslog.d/xenserver.conf:*.crit;mail.none;authpriv.none;cron.none\t\t:omfile:$crit_log\n/etc/rsyslog.d/xenserver.conf:$outchannel xcp_http_disk_server_log,/var/log/xcp-http-nbd-server.log,104857600,/etc/cron.daily/logrotate\n/etc/rsyslog.d/xenserver.conf:$outchannel xcp_nbd_http_server_log,/var/log/xcp-nbd-http-server.log,104857600,/etc/cron.daily/logrotate\n/etc/rsyslog.d/xenserver.conf:$outchannel drbd_kern_log,/var/log/drbd-kern.log,104857600,/etc/cron.daily/logrotate\n/etc/rsyslog.d/xenserver.conf:$outchannel kern_log,/var/log/kern.log,104857600,/etc/cron.daily/logrotate\n/etc/rsyslog.d/xenserver.conf:$outchannel daemon_log,/var/log/daemon.log,104857600,/etc/cron.daily/logrotate\n/etc/rsyslog.d/xenserver.conf:$outchannel user_log,/var/log/user.log,104857600,/etc/cron.daily/logrotate\n/etc/rsyslog.d/xenserver.conf:$outchannel secure_log,/var/log/secure,104857600,/etc/cron.daily/logrotate\n/etc/rsyslog.d/xenserver.conf:$outchannel mail_log,/var/log/maillog,104857600,/etc/cron.daily/logrotate\n/etc/rsyslog.d/xenserver.conf:# Log cron stuff\n/etc/rsyslog.d/xenserver.conf:$outchannel cron_log,/var/log/cron,104857600,/etc/cron.daily/logrotate\n/etc/rsyslog.d/xenserver.conf:cron.*\t\t\t\t\t\t\t:omfile:$cron_log\n/etc/rsyslog.d/xenserver.conf:$outchannel boot_log,/var/log/boot.log,104857600,/etc/cron.daily/logrotate\n/etc/rsyslog.d/xenserver.conf:$outchannel audit_log,/var/log/audit.log,104857600,/etc/cron.daily/logrotate\n/etc/rsyslog.d/xenserver.conf:$outchannel xensource_log,/var/log/xensource.log,104857600,/etc/cron.daily/logrotate\n/etc/rsyslog.d/xenserver.conf:$outchannel xenstored_log,/var/log/xenstored-access.log,104857600,/etc/cron.daily/logrotate\n/etc/rsyslog.d/xenserver.conf:$outchannel sm_log,/var/log/SMlog,104857600,/etc/cron.daily/logrotate\n/etc/rsyslog.d/xenserver.conf:$outchannel vmss_log,/var/log/VMSSlog,104857600,/etc/cron.daily/logrotate\n/etc/rsyslog.d/xenserver.conf:$outchannel xcp_rrdd_log,/var/log/xcp-rrdd-plugins.log,104857600,/etc/cron.daily/logrotate\n\nPASS: Cron logging is configured in rsyslog.\n"},{"group_id_src":"V-204490","group_tree":[{"id":"V-204490","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-204490","severity":"medium","group_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must be configured so that the cron.allow file, if it exists, is owned by root.","rule_id_src":"SV-204490r991589_rule","rule_id":"SV-204490r991589","rule_version":"RHEL-07-021110","rule_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must be configured so that the cron.allow file, if it exists, is owned by root.","fix_text":"Set the owner on the \"/etc/cron.allow\" file to root with the following command:\n\n# chown root /etc/cron.allow","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that the \"cron.allow\" file is owned by root.\n\nCheck the owner of the \"cron.allow\" file with the following command:\n\n# ls -al /etc/cron.allow\n-rw------- 1 root root 6 Mar  5  2011 /etc/cron.allow\n\nIf the \"cron.allow\" file exists and has an owner other than root, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_7_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"If the owner of the \"cron.allow\" file is not set to root, the possibility exists for an unauthorized user to view or to edit sensitive information.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-86677","V-72053"],"ccis":["CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"2899","uuid":"2d5fb769-eb0e-46d1-a044-c108e539d429","stig_uuid":"aa379772-3679-4074-8a4e-5b09f41d3e8e","status":"not_a_finding","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_Dom0_RHEL7_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 1\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nThe automated check verifies ownership of the /etc/cron.allow file on the XCP-ng Dom0 system. If /etc/cron.allow exists, it must be owned by root to prevent unauthorized users from modifying the list of users permitted to run cron jobs. If /etc/cron.allow does not exist, the system relies on /etc/cron.deny for access control, and this specific requirement is not applicable. The check uses stat to determine file ownership and confirms root ownership for compliance.\n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_Dom0_RHEL7_Checks) found this to be NOT A FINDING on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: 65C3ABC1E23640EE563F1A31DF6F45438D47B60E\n~~~~~\nV-204490 - cron.allow Owned by Root\n============================================================\n\nFile: /etc/cron.allow\nExists: missing\n\nPASS: /etc/cron.allow does not exist. No ownership issue.\n"},{"group_id_src":"V-204491","group_tree":[{"id":"V-204491","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-204491","severity":"medium","group_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must be configured so that the cron.allow file, if it exists, is group-owned by root.","rule_id_src":"SV-204491r991589_rule","rule_id":"SV-204491r991589","rule_version":"RHEL-07-021120","rule_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must be configured so that the cron.allow file, if it exists, is group-owned by root.","fix_text":"Set the group owner on the \"/etc/cron.allow\" file to root with the following command:\n\n# chgrp root /etc/cron.allow","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that the \"cron.allow\" file is group-owned by root.\n\nCheck the group owner of the \"cron.allow\" file with the following command:\n\n# ls -al /etc/cron.allow\n-rw------- 1 root root 6 Mar  5  2011 /etc/cron.allow\n\nIf the \"cron.allow\" file exists and has a group owner other than root, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_7_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"If the group owner of the \"cron.allow\" file is not set to root, sensitive information could be viewed or edited by unauthorized users.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-86679","V-72055"],"ccis":["CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"2899","uuid":"eb6e6747-777c-4d28-85f3-f6713ab3089d","stig_uuid":"aa379772-3679-4074-8a4e-5b09f41d3e8e","status":"not_a_finding","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_Dom0_RHEL7_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 1\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nThe automated check verifies group ownership of /etc/cron.allow on the XCP-ng Dom0 system. If /etc/cron.allow exists, it must be group-owned by root to prevent unauthorized modification of the approved cron user list. The check uses stat to determine group ownership. If /etc/cron.allow does not exist, the system relies on /etc/cron.deny for cron access control and this requirement is satisfied. On this XCP-ng Dom0 hypervisor, the cron.allow file is either absent or properly group-owned by root, meeting the STIG requirement.\n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_Dom0_RHEL7_Checks) found this to be NOT A FINDING on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: 1973B268B8D5E21B7E0AFC7B969749C506DD0971\n~~~~~\nV-204491 - cron.allow Group Ownership\n============================================================\n\nFile /etc/cron.allow does not exist.\nSystem uses /etc/cron.deny for access control.\n\nRESULT: PASS - cron.allow not present, requirement not applicable\n"},{"group_id_src":"V-204492","group_tree":[{"id":"V-204492","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-204492","severity":"medium","group_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must disable Kernel core dumps unless needed.","rule_id_src":"SV-204492r991589_rule","rule_id":"SV-204492r991589","rule_version":"RHEL-07-021300","rule_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must disable Kernel core dumps unless needed.","fix_text":"If kernel core dumps are not required, disable the \"kdump\" service with the following command:\n\n# systemctl disable kdump.service\n\nIf kernel core dumps are required, document the need with the ISSO.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that kernel core dumps are disabled unless needed.\n\nCheck the status of the \"kdump\" service with the following command:\n\n# systemctl status kdump.service\nkdump.service - Crash recovery kernel arming\n   Loaded: loaded (/usr/lib/systemd/system/kdump.service; enabled)\n   Active: active (exited) since Wed 2015-08-26 13:08:09 EDT; 43min ago\n Main PID: 1130 (code=exited, status=0/SUCCESS)\nkernel arming.\n\nIf the \"kdump\" service is active, ask the System Administrator if the use of the service is required and documented with the Information System Security Officer (ISSO).\n\nIf the service is active and is not documented, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_7_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Kernel core dumps may contain the full contents of system memory at the time of the crash. Kernel core dumps may consume a considerable amount of disk space and may result in denial of service by exhausting the available space on the target file system partition.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-86681","V-72057"],"ccis":["CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"2899","uuid":"59e3d6ee-e7ab-4e5b-9e61-a60f66a3e8e3","stig_uuid":"aa379772-3679-4074-8a4e-5b09f41d3e8e","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_Dom0_RHEL7_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 2\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nThe automated check found that the kdump service is active on the system. This violates the STIG requirement to disable kernel core dumps unless specifically needed and documented. Active kernel core dumps consume disk space and may expose sensitive memory contents. To remediate, disable the kdump service: systemctl disable kdump.service and systemctl stop kdump.service. If kernel core dumps are required for operational purposes, document the need with the ISSO and retain evidence of approval.\n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_Dom0_RHEL7_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: 0FEA50B21E2A3E70E72C639102ED39A92735B000\n~~~~~\nV-204492 - Kernel Core Dumps (kdump)\n============================================================\n\nkdump.service status: active\nkdump.service enabled: enabled\n\nRESULT: FAIL - kdump service is active\nIf kernel core dumps are required, document with the ISSO.\n"},{"group_id_src":"V-204493","group_tree":[{"id":"V-204493","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-204493","severity":"low","group_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must be configured so that a separate file system is used for user home directories (such as /home or an equivalent).","rule_id_src":"SV-204493r991589_rule","rule_id":"SV-204493r991589","rule_version":"RHEL-07-021310","rule_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must be configured so that a separate file system is used for user home directories (such as /home or an equivalent).","fix_text":"Migrate the \"/home\" directory onto a separate file system/partition.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that a separate file system/partition has been created for non-privileged local interactive user home directories.\n\nCheck the home directory assignment for all non-privileged users (those with a UID of 1000 or greater) on the system with the following command:\n\n# awk -F: '($3>=1000)&&($7 !~ /nologin/){print $1, $3, $6, $7}' /etc/passwd\n\nadamsj 1000 /home/adamsj /bin/bash\njacksonm 1001 /home/jacksonm /bin/bash\nsmithj 1002 /home/smithj /bin/bash\n\nThe output of the command will give the directory/partition that contains the home directories for the non-privileged users on the system (in this example, /home) and users' shell. All accounts with a valid shell (such as /bin/bash) are considered interactive users.\n\nCheck that a file system/partition has been created for the non-privileged interactive users with the following command:\n\nNote: The partition of /home is used in the example.\n\n# grep /home /etc/fstab\nUUID=333ada18    /home                   ext4    noatime,nobarrier,nodev  1 2\n\nIf a separate entry for the file system/partition that contains the non-privileged interactive users' home directories does not exist, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_7_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"The use of separate file systems for different paths can protect the system from failures resulting from a file system becoming full or failing.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-86683","V-72059"],"ccis":["CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"2899","uuid":"61fb1d3d-2cf3-4b2e-85cd-c270d5ad3aac","stig_uuid":"aa379772-3679-4074-8a4e-5b09f41d3e8e","status":"not_a_finding","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_Dom0_RHEL7_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 1\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nThe automated check verified the /home directory configuration on this XCP-ng Dom0 (RHEL 7-based) system. XCP-ng Dom0 is a hypervisor management domain that typically has no non-privileged interactive user accounts (UID >= 1000). The scan confirmed either that /home is on a separate filesystem or that no interactive users exist, making a separate /home partition unnecessary. This meets RHEL 7 STIG requirement RHEL-07-021310. Finding: Not a Finding.\n        \n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_Dom0_RHEL7_Checks) found this to be NOT A FINDING on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: DD7B6C9E97ED03FB77FF4B41734B20A3E16AC7B8\n~~~~~\nV-204493 - Separate Filesystem for /home\n============================================================\n\nmount | grep /home: (not mounted separately)\nfstab /home entry: (not found)\n\nInteractive users (UID >= 1000): (none)\n\nPASS: No non-privileged interactive users exist on this XCP-ng Dom0.\nA separate /home partition is not required.\n"},{"group_id_src":"V-204494","group_tree":[{"id":"V-204494","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-204494","severity":"low","group_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must use a separate file system for /var.","rule_id_src":"SV-204494r991589_rule","rule_id":"SV-204494r991589","rule_version":"RHEL-07-021320","rule_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must use a separate file system for /var.","fix_text":"Migrate the \"/var\" path onto a separate file system.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that a separate file system/partition has been created for \"/var\".\n\nCheck that a file system/partition has been created for \"/var\" with the following command:\n\n# grep /var /etc/fstab\nUUID=c274f65f    /var                    ext4    noatime,nobarrier        1 2\n\nIf a separate entry for \"/var\" is not in use, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_7_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"The use of separate file systems for different paths can protect the system from failures resulting from a file system becoming full or failing.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-86685","V-72061"],"ccis":["CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"2899","uuid":"41159f44-7d77-4b49-8389-5b694b5bdcef","stig_uuid":"aa379772-3679-4074-8a4e-5b09f41d3e8e","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_Dom0_RHEL7_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 2\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nThe automated check found that /var is not on a separate filesystem on this XCP-ng Dom0 system. Per RHEL 7 STIG requirement RHEL-07-021320, /var must use a separate partition to prevent variable data from consuming root filesystem space. Remediation: Migrate /var to a separate partition or logical volume. The system administrator must ensure proper filesystem separation.\n        \n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_Dom0_RHEL7_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: 1F2EA037D6CCB46DC357EA9FAC6FEE9A5799450B\n~~~~~\nV-204494 - Separate Filesystem for /var\n============================================================\n\nmount | grep /var: (not mounted separately)\nfstab /var entry: (not found)\n\nFAIL: /var is not on a separate filesystem.\nRemediation: Migrate /var to a separate partition.\n"},{"group_id_src":"V-204495","group_tree":[{"id":"V-204495","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-204495","severity":"low","group_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must use a separate file system for the system audit data path.","rule_id_src":"SV-204495r991589_rule","rule_id":"SV-204495r991589","rule_version":"RHEL-07-021330","rule_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must use a separate file system for the system audit data path.","fix_text":"Migrate the system audit data path onto a separate file system.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Determine if the operating system is configured to have the \"/var/log/audit\" path is on a separate file system.\n\n# grep /var/log/audit /etc/fstab\n\nIf no result is returned, or the operating system is not configured to have \"/var/log/audit\" on a separate file system, this is a finding.\n\nVerify that \"/var/log/audit\" is mounted on a separate file system:\n\n# mount | grep \"/var/log/audit\"\n\nIf no result is returned, or \"/var/log/audit\" is not on a separate file system, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_7_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"The use of separate file systems for different paths can protect the system from failures resulting from a file system becoming full or failing.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-86687","V-72063"],"ccis":["CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"2899","uuid":"e5b9c125-3e91-4ee8-906f-c80583d85c08","stig_uuid":"aa379772-3679-4074-8a4e-5b09f41d3e8e","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_Dom0_RHEL7_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 2\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nThe automated check found that /var/log/audit is not on a separate filesystem on this XCP-ng Dom0 system. Per RHEL 7 STIG requirement RHEL-07-021330, the audit data path must use a separate partition to ensure audit logs are preserved. Remediation: Create a separate partition for /var/log/audit and update /etc/fstab. The system administrator must ensure audit data has dedicated storage.\n        \n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_Dom0_RHEL7_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: 0E7BCECA51266C403763CFB6CDBE0AC1312A3006\n~~~~~\nV-204495 - Separate Filesystem for /var/log/audit\n============================================================\n\nmount | grep /var/log/audit: (not mounted separately)\nfstab entry: (not found)\n\nFAIL: /var/log/audit is not on a separate filesystem.\nRemediation: Migrate /var/log/audit to a separate partition.\n"},{"group_id_src":"V-204496","group_tree":[{"id":"V-204496","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-204496","severity":"low","group_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must use a separate file system for /tmp (or equivalent).","rule_id_src":"SV-204496r991589_rule","rule_id":"SV-204496r991589","rule_version":"RHEL-07-021340","rule_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must use a separate file system for /tmp (or equivalent).","fix_text":"Start the \"tmp.mount\" service with the following command:\n\n# systemctl enable tmp.mount\n   \nOR\n\nEdit the \"/etc/fstab\" file and ensure the \"/tmp\" directory is defined in the fstab with a device and mount point.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that a separate file system/partition has been created for \"/tmp\".\n\nCheck that a file system/partition has been created for \"/tmp\" with the following command:\n\n# systemctl is-enabled tmp.mount\nenabled\n\nIf the \"tmp.mount\" service is not enabled, check to see if \"/tmp\" is defined in the fstab with a device and mount point:\n\n# grep -i /tmp /etc/fstab\nUUID=a411dc99-f2a1-4c87-9e05-184977be8539 /tmp   ext4   rw,relatime,discard,data=ordered,nosuid,noexec, 0 0\n\nIf \"tmp.mount\" service is not enabled or the \"/tmp\" directory is not defined in the fstab with a device and mount point, this is a finding. ","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_7_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"The use of separate file systems for different paths can protect the system from failures resulting from a file system becoming full or failing.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-86689","V-72065"],"ccis":["CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"2899","uuid":"460fb4c4-3feb-4491-8ba2-e3e58148b04c","stig_uuid":"aa379772-3679-4074-8a4e-5b09f41d3e8e","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_Dom0_RHEL7_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 2\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nThe automated check found that /tmp is not configured as a separate filesystem on this XCP-ng Dom0 system. Per RHEL 7 STIG requirement RHEL-07-021340, /tmp must use a separate partition. Remediation: Enable tmp.mount: systemctl enable tmp.mount, or add /tmp to /etc/fstab with a dedicated device. The system administrator must ensure /tmp has separate storage.\n        \n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_Dom0_RHEL7_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: 24CFC320F84DA3B5D677FD31B319A4BDD1E372BB\n~~~~~\nV-204496 - Separate Filesystem for /tmp\n============================================================\n\nCommand: systemctl is-enabled tmp.mount\nResult: disabled\n\nfstab /tmp entry: (not found)\nmount | grep /tmp: (not mounted separately)\n\nFAIL: /tmp is not on a separate filesystem.\nRemediation: systemctl enable tmp.mount, or add /tmp to /etc/fstab.\n"},{"group_id_src":"V-204497","group_tree":[{"id":"V-204497","title":"SRG-OS-000033-GPOS-00014","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-204497","severity":"high","group_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must implement NIST FIPS-validated cryptography for the following: to provision digital signatures, to generate cryptographic hashes, and to protect data requiring data-at-rest protections in accordance with applicable federal laws, Executive Orders, directives, policies, regulations, and standards.","rule_id_src":"SV-204497r958408_rule","rule_id":"SV-204497r958408","rule_version":"RHEL-07-021350","rule_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must implement NIST FIPS-validated cryptography for the following: to provision digital signatures, to generate cryptographic hashes, and to protect data requiring data-at-rest protections in accordance with applicable federal laws, Executive Orders, directives, policies, regulations, and standards.","fix_text":"Configure the operating system to implement DoD-approved encryption by installing the dracut-fips package.\n\nTo enable strict FIPS compliance, the fips=1 kernel option needs to be added to the kernel command line during system installation so key generation is done with FIPS-approved algorithms and continuous monitoring tests in place.\n\nConfigure the operating system to implement DoD-approved encryption by following the steps below: \n\nThe fips=1 kernel option needs to be added to the kernel command line during system installation so that key generation is done with FIPS-approved algorithms and continuous monitoring tests in place. Users should also ensure that the system has plenty of entropy during the installation process by moving the mouse around, or if no mouse is available, ensuring that many keystrokes are typed. The recommended amount of keystrokes is 256 and more. Less than 256 keystrokes may generate a non-unique key.\n\nInstall the dracut-fips package with the following command:\n\n# yum install dracut-fips\n\nRecreate the \"initramfs\" file with the following command:\n\nNote: This command will overwrite the existing \"initramfs\" file.\n\n# dracut -f\n\nModify the kernel command line of the current kernel in the \"grub.cfg\" file by adding the following option to the GRUB_CMDLINE_LINUX key in the \"/etc/default/grub\" file and then rebuild the \"grub.cfg\" file:\n\nfips=1\n\nChanges to \"/etc/default/grub\" require rebuilding the \"grub.cfg\" file as follows:\n\nOn BIOS-based machines, use the following command:\n\n# grub2-mkconfig -o /boot/grub2/grub.cfg\n\nOn UEFI-based machines, use the following command:\n\n# grub2-mkconfig -o /boot/efi/EFI/redhat/grub.cfg\n\nIf /boot or /boot/efi reside on separate partitions, the kernel parameter boot=<partition of /boot or /boot/efi> must be added to the kernel command line. You can identify a partition by running the df /boot or df /boot/efi command:\n\n# df /boot\nFilesystem 1K-blocks Used Available Use% Mounted on\n/dev/sda1 495844 53780 416464 12% /boot\n\nTo ensure the \"boot=\" configuration option will work even if device naming changes occur between boots, identify the universally unique identifier (UUID) of the partition with the following command:\n\n# blkid /dev/sda1\n/dev/sda1: UUID=\"05c000f1-a213-759e-c7a2-f11b7424c797\" TYPE=\"ext4\"\n\nFor the example above, append the following string to the kernel command line:\n\nboot=UUID=05c000f1-a213-759e-c7a2-f11b7424c797\n\nIf the file /etc/system-fips does not exists, recreate it:\n\n# touch /etc/ system-fips\n\nReboot the system for the changes to take effect.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the operating system implements DoD-approved encryption to protect the confidentiality of remote access sessions.\n\nCheck to see if the \"dracut-fips\" package is installed with the following command:\n\n# yum list installed dracut-fips\n\ndracut-fips-033-360.el7_2.x86_64.rpm\n\nIf a \"dracut-fips\" package is installed, check to see if the kernel command line is configured to use FIPS mode with the following command:\n\nNote: GRUB 2 reads its configuration from the \"/boot/grub2/grub.cfg\" file on traditional BIOS-based machines and from the \"/boot/efi/EFI/redhat/grub.cfg\" file on UEFI machines.\n\n# grep fips /boot/grub2/grub.cfg\n/vmlinuz-3.8.0-0.40.el7.x86_64 root=/dev/mapper/rhel-root ro rd.md=0 rd.dm=0 rd.lvm.lv=rhel/swap crashkernel=auto rd.luks=0 vconsole.keymap=us rd.lvm.lv=rhel/root rhgb fips=1 quiet\n\nIf the kernel command line is configured to use FIPS mode, check to see if the system is in FIPS mode with the following command:\n\n# cat /proc/sys/crypto/fips_enabled \n1\n\nIf a \"dracut-fips\" package is not installed, the kernel command line does not have a fips entry, or the system has a value of \"0\" for \"fips_enabled\" in \"/proc/sys/crypto\", this is a finding.\n\nVerify the file /etc/system-fips exists.\n\n# ls -l /etc/system-fips\n\nIf this file does not exist, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_7_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Use of weak or untested encryption algorithms undermines the purposes of using encryption to protect data. The operating system must implement cryptographic modules adhering to the higher standards approved by the federal government since this provides assurance they have been tested and validated.\r\n\r\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000033-GPOS-00014, SRG-OS-000185-GPOS-00079, SRG-OS-000396-GPOS-00176, SRG-OS-000405-GPOS-00184, SRG-OS-000478-GPOS-00223","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-86691","V-72067"],"ccis":["CCI-000068","CCI-001199","CCI-002450","CCI-002476"],"reference_identifier":"2899","uuid":"d7b0f5c2-027a-452e-8f96-e56d2994d3e7","stig_uuid":"aa379772-3679-4074-8a4e-5b09f41d3e8e","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_Dom0_RHEL7_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 2\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nThe automated check found that this XCP-ng Dom0 (RHEL 7-based) system does not fully implement FIPS-validated cryptography. The scan detected that either the dracut-fips package is not installed, the fips=1 kernel parameter is missing from the boot command line, or FIPS mode is not active at runtime. Per RHEL 7 STIG requirement RHEL-07-021350, the operating system must implement NIST FIPS-validated cryptography. Note: XCP-ng Dom0 may not support FIPS mode due to its custom Xen kernel. This is a known compliance gap requiring Vates vendor resolution. Remediation: (1) Install dracut-fips: yum install dracut-fips. (2) Add fips=1 to GRUB_CMDLINE_LINUX in /etc/default/grub. (3) Regenerate GRUB config: grub2-mkconfig -o /boot/grub2/grub.cfg. (4) Rebuild initramfs: dracut -f. (5) Reboot. Contact Vates for XCP-ng FIPS compatibility guidance.\n        \n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_Dom0_RHEL7_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: 6F0639A99BA1AC42319457FF7470AB1CA97CAC3E\n~~~~~\nV-204497 - FIPS-Validated Cryptography\n============================================================\n\nCheck 1: dracut-fips package\nCommand: rpm -q dracut-fips\nResult: package dracut-fips is not installed\n\nFAIL: dracut-fips package is not installed.\nFIPS mode cannot be enabled without dracut-fips.\n\nNote: XCP-ng Dom0 may not support FIPS mode due to custom kernel.\nThis is a known compliance gap requiring Vates/vendor resolution.\n"},{"group_id_src":"V-204498","group_tree":[{"id":"V-204498","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-204498","severity":"low","group_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must be configured so that the file integrity tool is configured to verify Access Control Lists (ACLs).","rule_id_src":"SV-204498r991589_rule","rule_id":"SV-204498r991589","rule_version":"RHEL-07-021600","rule_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must be configured so that the file integrity tool is configured to verify Access Control Lists (ACLs).","fix_text":"Configure the file integrity tool to check file and directory ACLs. \n\nIf AIDE is installed, ensure the \"acl\" rule is present on all uncommented file and directory selection lists.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the file integrity tool is configured to verify ACLs.\n\nNote: AIDE is highly configurable at install time. These commands assume the \"aide.conf\" file is under the \"/etc\" directory. \n\nUse the following command to determine if the file is in another location:\n\n     # find / -name aide.conf\n\nCheck the \"aide.conf\" file to determine if the \"acl\" rule has been added to the rule list being applied to the files and directories selection lists.\n\nAn example rule that includes the \"acl\" rule is below:\n\n     All= p+i+n+u+g+s+m+S+sha512+acl+xattrs+selinux\n     /bin All # apply the custom rule to the files in bin \n     /sbin All # apply the same custom rule to the files in sbin \n\nIf the \"acl\" rule is not being used on all uncommented selection lines in the \"/etc/aide.conf\" file, or ACLs are not being checked by another file integrity tool, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_7_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"ACLs can provide permissions beyond those permitted through the file mode and must be verified by file integrity tools.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-86693","V-72069"],"ccis":["CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"2899","uuid":"ba64a5d5-e2a3-4596-9f3c-ec49927af38e","stig_uuid":"aa379772-3679-4074-8a4e-5b09f41d3e8e","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_Dom0_RHEL7_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 2\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nThe automated check found that the file integrity tool is not properly configured to verify ACLs on this XCP-ng Dom0 system. Either AIDE is not installed or the 'acl' rule is not in the aide.conf configuration. Per RHEL 7 STIG requirement RHEL-07-021600, the integrity tool must verify ACLs. Remediation: (1) Install AIDE: yum install aide. (2) Add 'acl' to rule definitions in /etc/aide.conf. (3) Initialize database: aide --init. The system administrator must configure ACL verification.\n        \n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_Dom0_RHEL7_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: 1E31AF9A3813A9168D08553602332A9F605AD569\n~~~~~\nV-204498 - File Integrity Tool Verifies ACLs\n============================================================\n\nAIDE package: package aide is not installed\n\nFAIL: AIDE (file integrity tool) is not installed.\nRemediation: yum install aide, then configure aide.conf with acl rule.\n"},{"group_id_src":"V-204499","group_tree":[{"id":"V-204499","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-204499","severity":"low","group_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must be configured so that the file integrity tool is configured to verify extended attributes.","rule_id_src":"SV-204499r991589_rule","rule_id":"SV-204499r991589","rule_version":"RHEL-07-021610","rule_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must be configured so that the file integrity tool is configured to verify extended attributes.","fix_text":"Configure the file integrity tool to check file and directory extended attributes. \n\nIf AIDE is installed, ensure the \"xattrs\" rule is present on all uncommented file and directory selection lists.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the file integrity tool is configured to verify extended attributes.\n\nNote: AIDE is highly configurable at install time. These commands assume the \"aide.conf\" file is under the \"/etc\" directory.\n\nUse the following command to determine if the file is in another location:\n     # find / -name aide.conf\n\nCheck the \"aide.conf\" file to determine if the \"xattrs\" rule has been added to the rule list being applied to the files and directories selection lists.\n\nAn example rule that includes the \"xattrs\" rule follows:\n\n     All= p+i+n+u+g+s+m+S+sha512+acl+xattrs+selinux\n     /bin All # apply the custom rule to the files in bin \n     /sbin All # apply the same custom rule to the files in sbin \n\nIf the \"xattrs\" rule is not being used on all uncommented selection lines in the \"/etc/aide.conf\" file, or extended attributes are not being checked by another file integrity tool, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_7_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Extended attributes in file systems are used to contain arbitrary data and file metadata with security implications.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-86695","V-72071"],"ccis":["CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"2899","uuid":"df21a290-f0a5-464f-a833-a2aeb776779f","stig_uuid":"aa379772-3679-4074-8a4e-5b09f41d3e8e","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_Dom0_RHEL7_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 2\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nThe automated check found that the file integrity tool is not configured to verify extended attributes on this XCP-ng Dom0 system. Either AIDE is not installed or the 'xattrs' rule is missing from aide.conf. Per RHEL 7 STIG requirement RHEL-07-021610, the integrity tool must verify extended attributes. Remediation: (1) Install AIDE: yum install aide. (2) Add 'xattrs' to rule definitions in /etc/aide.conf. (3) Initialize: aide --init. The system administrator must configure xattr verification.\n        \n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_Dom0_RHEL7_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: 3BE040ABCBAE42E2851B973E9DF153E8036B5D8D\n~~~~~\nV-204499 - File Integrity Tool Verifies Extended Attributes\n============================================================\n\nAIDE package: package aide is not installed\n\nFAIL: AIDE (file integrity tool) is not installed.\nRemediation: yum install aide, then configure aide.conf with xattrs rule.\n"},{"group_id_src":"V-204500","group_tree":[{"id":"V-204500","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-204500","severity":"medium","group_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must use a file integrity tool that is configured to use FIPS 140-2 approved cryptographic hashes for validating file contents and directories.","rule_id_src":"SV-204500r991589_rule","rule_id":"SV-204500r991589","rule_version":"RHEL-07-021620","rule_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must use a file integrity tool that is configured to use FIPS 140-2 approved cryptographic hashes for validating file contents and directories.","fix_text":"Configure the file integrity tool to use FIPS 140-2 cryptographic hashes for validating file and directory contents. \n\nIf AIDE is installed, ensure the \"sha512\" rule is present on all uncommented file and directory selection lists. Exclude any log files, or files expected to change frequently, to reduce unnecessary notifications.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the file integrity tool is configured to use FIPS 140-2-approved cryptographic hashes for validating file contents and directories.\n\nNote: AIDE is highly configurable at install time. These commands assume the \"aide.conf\" file is under the \"/etc\" directory. \n\nUse the following command to determine if the file is in another location:\n\n     # find / -name aide.conf\n\nCheck the \"aide.conf\" file to determine if the \"sha512\" rule has been added to the rule list being applied to the files and directories selection lists. Exclude any log files, or files expected to change frequently, to reduce unnecessary notifications.\n\nAn example rule that includes the \"sha512\" rule follows:\n \n     All=p+i+n+u+g+s+m+S+sha512+acl+xattrs+selinux\n     /bin All # apply the custom rule to the files in bin \n     /sbin All # apply the same custom rule to the files in sbin \n\nIf the \"sha512\" rule is not being used on all uncommented selection lines in the \"/etc/aide.conf\" file, or another file integrity tool is not using FIPS 140-2-approved cryptographic hashes for validating file contents and directories, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_7_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"File integrity tools use cryptographic hashes for verifying file contents and directories have not been altered. These hashes must be FIPS 140-2 approved cryptographic hashes.\n\nRed Hat Enterprise Linux operating system installation media ships with an optional file integrity tool called Advanced Intrusion Detection Environment (AIDE). AIDE is highly configurable at install time. This requirement assumes the \"aide.conf\" file is under the \"/etc\" directory.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-86697","V-72073"],"ccis":["CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"2899","uuid":"4302cc8a-c203-4ec6-bd93-99d8356e714c","stig_uuid":"aa379772-3679-4074-8a4e-5b09f41d3e8e","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_Dom0_RHEL7_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 1\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nThe automated check verifies that AIDE (Advanced Intrusion Detection Environment) is installed and configured to use FIPS 140-2 approved cryptographic hashes (sha512) for file integrity validation on the XCP-ng Dom0 system. The check first verifies AIDE installation via rpm, then examines /etc/aide.conf for sha512 hash algorithm configuration. AIDE with sha512 provides cryptographically strong file integrity monitoring that meets FIPS 140-2 requirements for detecting unauthorized changes to system files and directories.\n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_Dom0_RHEL7_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: 6362F59C6B82C70FADCA2582EA417B16FC7B04A0\n~~~~~\nV-204500 - File Integrity Tool (AIDE) FIPS Hashes\n============================================================\n\nAIDE package: package aide is not installed\n\nRESULT: FAIL - AIDE is not installed\nA file integrity tool using FIPS 140-2 hashes is required.\n"},{"group_id_src":"V-204501","group_tree":[{"id":"V-204501","title":"SRG-OS-000364-GPOS-00151","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-204501","severity":"medium","group_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must not allow removable media to be used as the boot loader unless approved.","rule_id_src":"SV-204501r958796_rule","rule_id":"SV-204501r958796","rule_version":"RHEL-07-021700","rule_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must not allow removable media to be used as the boot loader unless approved.","fix_text":"Remove alternate methods of booting the system from removable media or document the configuration to boot from removable media with the ISSO.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the system is not configured to use a boot loader on removable media.\n\nNote: GRUB 2 reads its configuration from the \"/boot/grub2/grub.cfg\" file on traditional BIOS-based machines and from the \"/boot/efi/EFI/redhat/grub.cfg\" file on UEFI machines.\n\nCheck for the existence of alternate boot loader configuration files with the following command:\n\n     # find / -name grub.cfg\n     /boot/efi/EFI/redhat/grub.cfg\n\nIf a \"grub.cfg\" is found in any subdirectories other than \"/boot/grub2/\" and \"/boot/efi/EFI/redhat/\", ask the system administrator (SA) if there is documentation signed by the ISSO to approve the use of removable media as a boot loader. \n\nList the number of menu entries defined in the grub configuration file with the following command (the number will vary between systems):\n\n     # grep -cw menuentry /boot/efi/EFI/redhat/grub.cfg\n     4\n\nCheck that the grub configuration file has the \"set root\" command for each menu entry with the following command (\"set root\" defines the disk and partition or directory where the kernel and GRUB 2 modules are stored):\n\n     # grep 'set root' /boot/efi/EFI/redhat/grub.cfg\n     set root='hd0,gpt2'\n     set root='hd0,gpt2'\n     set root='hd0,gpt2'\n     set root='hd0,gpt2'\n\nIf the system is using an alternate boot loader on removable media, and documentation does not exist approving the alternate configuration, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_7_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Malicious users with removable boot media can gain access to a system configured to use removable media as the boot loader. If removable media is designed to be used as the boot loader, the requirement must be documented with the information system security officer (ISSO).","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-86699","V-72075"],"ccis":["CCI-000318","CCI-000368","CCI-001812","CCI-001813","CCI-001814"],"reference_identifier":"2899","uuid":"e6071d59-983b-4c68-944e-dc6a274f2f35","stig_uuid":"aa379772-3679-4074-8a4e-5b09f41d3e8e","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_Dom0_RHEL7_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 2\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nThe automated check found grub.cfg boot loader configuration files in non-standard locations that may indicate removable media boot capability. This violates the STIG requirement because booting from removable media bypasses system security controls and could allow unauthorized operating system loading. To remediate, remove alternate boot loader configurations from removable media paths. If booting from removable media is operationally required, document the configuration with ISSO approval.\n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_Dom0_RHEL7_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: 6A5193655B41A51B66A7F1C2A16C5019B8BB6113\n~~~~~\nV-204501 - Boot Loader on Removable Media\n============================================================\n\ngrub.cfg locations found:\n/boot/grub/grub.cfg\n/etc/grub.cfg\n\nNon-standard grub.cfg locations:\n  /boot/grub/grub.cfg\n  /etc/grub.cfg\n\nRESULT: FAIL - Boot loader found on potential removable media\n"},{"group_id_src":"V-204502","group_tree":[{"id":"V-204502","title":"SRG-OS-000095-GPOS-00049","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-204502","severity":"high","group_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must not have the telnet-server package installed.","rule_id_src":"SV-204502r958478_rule","rule_id":"SV-204502r958478","rule_version":"RHEL-07-021710","rule_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must not have the telnet-server package installed.","fix_text":"Configure the operating system to disable non-essential capabilities by removing the telnet-server package from the system with the following command:\n\n# yum remove telnet-server","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the operating system is configured to disable non-essential capabilities. The most secure way of ensuring a non-essential capability is disabled is to not have the capability installed.\n\nThe telnet service provides an unencrypted remote access service that does not provide for the confidentiality and integrity of user passwords or the remote session.\n\nIf a privileged user were to log on using this service, the privileged user password could be compromised. \n\nCheck to see if the telnet-server package is installed with the following command:\n\n# yum list installed telnet-server\n\nIf the telnet-server package is installed, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_7_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"It is detrimental for operating systems to provide, or install by default, functionality exceeding requirements or mission objectives. These unnecessary capabilities or services are often overlooked and therefore may remain unsecured. They increase the risk to the platform by providing additional attack vectors.\n\nOperating systems are capable of providing a wide variety of functions and services. Some of the functions and services, provided by default, may not be necessary to support essential organizational operations (e.g., key missions, functions).\n\nExamples of non-essential capabilities include, but are not limited to, games, software packages, tools, and demonstration software not related to requirements or providing a wide array of functionality not required for every mission, but which cannot be disabled.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-86701","V-72077"],"ccis":["CCI-000381"],"reference_identifier":"2899","uuid":"c9a413dc-72fd-4f04-931f-790ffe3e91d0","stig_uuid":"aa379772-3679-4074-8a4e-5b09f41d3e8e","status":"not_a_finding","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_Dom0_RHEL7_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 1\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nThe automated check verified that the telnet-server package is not installed on this XCP-ng Dom0 (RHEL 7-based) system. The scan executed 'rpm -q telnet-server' and confirmed the package is not present. Telnet provides an unencrypted remote access service that transmits credentials and session data in cleartext, making it unsuitable for DoD environments. Its absence confirms compliance with RHEL 7 STIG requirement RHEL-07-021710. XCP-ng Dom0 uses SSH for all remote administration. Finding: Not a Finding.\n        \n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_Dom0_RHEL7_Checks) found this to be NOT A FINDING on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: C7440019A5D5DF7B7AB568AEC6B3037A2D05754B\n~~~~~\nV-204502 - telnet-server Package Must Not Be Installed\n============================================================\n\nCommand: rpm -q telnet-server\nResult: package telnet-server is not installed\n\nPASS: The telnet-server package is not installed.\n"},{"group_id_src":"V-204503","group_tree":[{"id":"V-204503","title":"SRG-OS-000038-GPOS-00016","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-204503","severity":"medium","group_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must be configured so that auditing is configured to produce records containing information to establish what type of events occurred, where the events occurred, the source of the events, and the outcome of the events. These audit records must also identify individual identities of group account users.","rule_id_src":"SV-204503r958414_rule","rule_id":"SV-204503r958414","rule_version":"RHEL-07-030000","rule_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must be configured so that auditing is configured to produce records containing information to establish what type of events occurred, where the events occurred, the source of the events, and the outcome of the events. These audit records must also identify individual identities of group account users.","fix_text":"Configure the operating system to produce audit records containing information to establish when (date and time) the events occurred.\n\nEnable the auditd service with the following command:\n\n# systemctl start auditd.service","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the operating system produces audit records containing information to establish when (date and time) the events occurred.\n\nCheck to see if auditing is active by issuing the following command:\n\n# systemctl is-active auditd.service\nactive\n\nIf the \"auditd\" status is not active, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_7_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Without establishing what type of events occurred, it would be difficult to establish, correlate, and investigate the events leading up to an outage or attack.\n\nAudit record content that may be necessary to satisfy this requirement includes, for example, time stamps, source and destination addresses, user/process identifiers, event descriptions, success/fail indications, filenames involved, and access control or flow control rules invoked.\n\nAssociating event types with detected events in the operating system audit logs provides a means of investigating an attack; recognizing resource utilization or capacity thresholds; or identifying an improperly configured operating system.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000038-GPOS-00016, SRG-OS-000039-GPOS-00017, SRG-OS-000042-GPOS-00021, SRG-OS-000254-GPOS-00095, SRG-OS-000255-GPOS-00096","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-86703","V-72079"],"ccis":["CCI-000126","CCI-000131"],"reference_identifier":"2899","uuid":"cd655e68-f9d1-45b1-9c63-987e6b06d9a2","stig_uuid":"aa379772-3679-4074-8a4e-5b09f41d3e8e","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_Dom0_RHEL7_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 2\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nThe automated check found that the auditd service is not active. This violates the STIG requirement for audit record generation. Without auditd, the system cannot produce records establishing event types, locations, sources, and outcomes. To remediate, start and enable the audit service: systemctl start auditd.service and systemctl enable auditd.service. Verify activation: systemctl is-active auditd.service should return active.\n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_Dom0_RHEL7_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: F01E5522A8A77B3F1A2DE34C126D6208C429F78B\n~~~~~\nV-204503 - Audit Service (auditd) Active\n============================================================\n\nauditd.service status: inactive\n\nRESULT: FAIL - auditd service is not active\n"},{"group_id_src":"V-204504","group_tree":[{"id":"V-204504","title":"SRG-OS-000046-GPOS-00022","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-204504","severity":"medium","group_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must shut down upon audit processing failure, unless availability is an overriding concern. If availability is a concern, the system must alert the designated staff (System Administrator [SA] and Information System Security Officer [ISSO] at a minimum) in the event of an audit processing failure.","rule_id_src":"SV-204504r958424_rule","rule_id":"SV-204504r958424","rule_version":"RHEL-07-030010","rule_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must shut down upon audit processing failure, unless availability is an overriding concern. If availability is a concern, the system must alert the designated staff (System Administrator [SA] and Information System Security Officer [ISSO] at a minimum) in the event of an audit processing failure.","fix_text":"Configure the operating system to shut down in the event of an audit processing failure.\n\nAdd or correct the option to shut down the operating system with the following command:\n\n     # auditctl -f 2\n\nEdit the \"/etc/audit/rules.d/audit.rules\" file and add the following line:\n\n     -f 2\n\nIf availability has been determined to be more important, and this decision is documented with the ISSO, configure the operating system to notify system administration staff and ISSO staff in the event of an audit processing failure with the following command:\n\n     # auditctl -f 1\n\nEdit the \"/etc/audit/rules.d/audit.rules\" file and add the following line:\n\n     -f 1\n\nKernel log monitoring must also be configured to properly alert designated staff.\n\nThe audit daemon must be restarted for the changes to take effect.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Confirm the audit configuration regarding how auditing processing failures are handled.\n\nCheck to see what level \"auditctl\" is set to with following command: \n\n     # auditctl -s | grep -i \"fail\"\n     failure 2\n\nNote: If the value of \"failure\" is set to \"2\", the system is configured to panic (shut down) in the event of an auditing failure. If the value of \"failure\" is set to \"1\", the system will not shut down and instead will record the audit failure in the kernel log. If the system is configured as per requirement RHEL-07-031000, the kernel log will be sent to a log aggregation server and generate an alert.\n\nIf the \"failure\" setting is set to any value other than \"1\" or \"2\", this is a finding.\n\nIf the \"failure\" setting is not set, this should be upgraded to a CAT I finding.\n\nIf the \"failure\" setting is set to \"1\" but the availability concern is not documented or there is no monitoring of the kernel log, this should be downgraded to a CAT III finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_7_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"It is critical for the appropriate personnel to be aware if a system is at risk of failing to process audit logs as required. Without this notification, the security personnel may be unaware of an impending failure of the audit capability, and system operation may be adversely affected.\n\nAudit processing failures include software/hardware errors, failures in the audit capturing mechanisms, and audit storage capacity being reached or exceeded.\n\nThis requirement applies to each audit data storage repository (i.e., distinct information system component where audit records are stored), the centralized audit storage capacity of organizations (i.e., all audit data storage repositories combined), or both.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000046-GPOS-00022, SRG-OS-000047-GPOS-00023","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-86705","V-72081"],"ccis":["CCI-000139"],"reference_identifier":"2899","uuid":"4d2598dd-0337-470a-a9d3-290ec8a82d70","stig_uuid":"aa379772-3679-4074-8a4e-5b09f41d3e8e","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_Dom0_RHEL7_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 2\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nThe automated check found that the audit failure mode is not set to an acceptable value (1 or 2). This violates the STIG requirement for appropriate action on audit processing failure. To remediate, set the failure mode: auditctl -f 2 (for shutdown on failure) or auditctl -f 1 (for logging on failure). Make persistent by adding -f 2 to /etc/audit/rules.d/audit.rules. If availability is an overriding concern, use -f 1 and document the justification with ISSO approval.\n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_Dom0_RHEL7_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: 28D6FB9434B5B8B836EB5FD43CBB54BB005D0811\n~~~~~\nV-204504 - Audit Processing Failure Action\n============================================================\n\nauditctl -s output:\n/usr/bin/timeout: failed to run command auditctl: No such file or directory\n\nRESULT: FAIL - Unable to determine audit failure mode\n"},{"group_id_src":"V-204506","group_tree":[{"id":"V-204506","title":"SRG-OS-000342-GPOS-00133","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-204506","severity":"medium","group_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must be configured to off-load audit logs onto a different system or storage media from the system being audited.","rule_id_src":"SV-204506r958754_rule","rule_id":"SV-204506r958754","rule_version":"RHEL-07-030201","rule_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must be configured to off-load audit logs onto a different system or storage media from the system being audited.","fix_text":"Edit the /etc/audisp/plugins.d/au-remote.conf file and add or update the following values:\n\nactive = yes\ndirection = out\npath = /sbin/audisp-remote\ntype = always\n\nThe audit daemon must be restarted for changes to take effect:\n\n# service auditd restart","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the \"au-remote\" plugin is configured to always off-load audit logs using the audisp-remote daemon:\n\n# cat /etc/audisp/plugins.d/au-remote.conf | grep -v \"^#\"\n\nactive = yes\ndirection = out\npath = /sbin/audisp-remote\ntype = always\nformat = string\n\nIf \"active\" is not set to \"yes\", \"direction\" is not set to \"out\", \"path\" is not set to \"/sbin/audisp-remote\", \"type\" is not set to \"always\", or any of the lines are commented out, ask the System Administrator to indicate how the audit logs are off-loaded to a different system or storage media.\n\nIf there is no evidence that the system is configured to off-load audit logs to a different system or storage media, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_7_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Information stored in one location is vulnerable to accidental or incidental deletion or alteration.\n\nOff-loading is a common process in information systems with limited audit storage capacity.\n\nOne method of off-loading audit logs in Red Hat Enterprise Linux is with the use of the audisp-remote dameon.  Without the configuration of the \"au-remote\" plugin, the audisp-remote daemon will not off load the logs from the system being audited.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000342-GPOS-00133, SRG-OS-000479-GPOS-00224","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-95729","V-81017"],"ccis":["CCI-001851"],"reference_identifier":"2899","uuid":"4ee293b0-745b-4efb-8cc5-be6c546b007e","stig_uuid":"aa379772-3679-4074-8a4e-5b09f41d3e8e","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_Dom0_RHEL7_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 1\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nThe automated check examines /etc/audisp/plugins.d/au-remote.conf to verify the au-remote plugin is configured for audit log off-loading. Required settings: active=yes, direction=out, path=/sbin/audisp-remote, type=always. Audit log off-loading ensures audit records are preserved on a separate system even if the audited system is compromised. On this XCP-ng Dom0 system, the au-remote plugin configuration is examined for all required parameters.\n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_Dom0_RHEL7_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: 69DCFBDAD330654D3D753864EA1D34A67ECA9637\n~~~~~\nV-204506 - Off-load Audit Logs (au-remote plugin)\n============================================================\n\nFile /etc/audisp/plugins.d/au-remote.conf not found.\n\nRESULT: FAIL - au-remote plugin not configured for audit log off-loading\n"},{"group_id_src":"V-204507","group_tree":[{"id":"V-204507","title":"SRG-OS-000342-GPOS-00133","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-204507","severity":"medium","group_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must take appropriate action when the remote logging buffer is full.","rule_id_src":"SV-204507r958754_rule","rule_id":"SV-204507r958754","rule_version":"RHEL-07-030210","rule_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must take appropriate action when the remote logging buffer is full.","fix_text":"Edit the /etc/audisp/audispd.conf file and add or update the \"overflow_action\" option:\n\noverflow_action = syslog\n\nThe audit daemon must be restarted for changes to take effect:\n\n# service auditd restart","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the audisp daemon is configured to take an appropriate action when the internal queue is full:\n\n# grep \"overflow_action\" /etc/audisp/audispd.conf\n\noverflow_action = syslog\n\nIf the \"overflow_action\" option is not \"syslog\", \"single\", or \"halt\", or the line is commented out, ask the System Administrator to indicate how the audit logs are off-loaded to a different system or storage media, and to indicate what action that system takes when the internal queue is full.\n\nIf there is no evidence the system is configured to off-load audit logs to a different system or storage media or, if the configuration does not take appropriate action when the internal queue is full, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_7_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Information stored in one location is vulnerable to accidental or incidental deletion or alteration.\n\nOff-loading is a common process in information systems with limited audit storage capacity.\n\nOne method of off-loading audit logs in Red Hat Enterprise Linux is with the use of the audisp-remote dameon.  When the remote buffer is full, audit logs will not be collected and sent to the central log server.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000342-GPOS-00133, SRG-OS-000479-GPOS-00224","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-95731","V-81019"],"ccis":["CCI-001851"],"reference_identifier":"2899","uuid":"c448047d-ffbd-4395-9258-cc68cd71e1de","stig_uuid":"aa379772-3679-4074-8a4e-5b09f41d3e8e","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_Dom0_RHEL7_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 1\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nThe automated check examines /etc/audisp/audispd.conf for the overflow_action setting on the XCP-ng Dom0 system. Acceptable values are syslog, single, or halt. The overflow_action determines what happens when the audisp dispatcher internal queue is full, which could occur during heavy audit traffic or when the remote audit server is unavailable. Proper configuration ensures audit events are not silently dropped when the buffer fills.\n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_Dom0_RHEL7_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: 14D7F8FC9358D6726E598D58F600FAD8349F4883\n~~~~~\nV-204507 - Audisp Overflow Action\n============================================================\n\nFile /etc/audisp/audispd.conf not found.\n\nRESULT: FAIL - audisp dispatcher not configured\n"},{"group_id_src":"V-204508","group_tree":[{"id":"V-204508","title":"SRG-OS-000342-GPOS-00133","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-204508","severity":"medium","group_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must label all off-loaded audit logs before sending them to the central log server.","rule_id_src":"SV-204508r958754_rule","rule_id":"SV-204508r958754","rule_version":"RHEL-07-030211","rule_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must label all off-loaded audit logs before sending them to the central log server.","fix_text":"Edit the /etc/audisp/audispd.conf file and add or update the \"name_format\" option:\n\nname_format = hostname\n\nThe audit daemon must be restarted for changes to take effect:\n\n# service auditd restart","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the audisp daemon is configured to label all off-loaded audit logs:\n\n# grep \"name_format\" /etc/audisp/audispd.conf\n\nname_format = hostname\n\nIf the \"name_format\" option is not \"hostname\", \"fqd\", or \"numeric\", or the line is commented out, ask the System Administrator to indicate how the audit logs are off-loaded to a different system or storage media, and to indicate if the logs are labeled appropriately.\n\nIf there is no evidence that the system is configured to off-load audit logs to a different system or storage media, or if the configuration does not appropriately label logs before they are off-loaded, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_7_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Information stored in one location is vulnerable to accidental or incidental deletion or alteration.\n\nOff-loading is a common process in information systems with limited audit storage capacity.\n\nOne method of off-loading audit logs in Red Hat Enterprise Linux is with the use of the audisp-remote dameon.  When audit logs are not labeled before they are sent to a central log server, the audit data will not be able to be analyzed and tied back to the correct system.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000342-GPOS-00133, SRG-OS-000479-GPOS-00224","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-95733","V-81021"],"ccis":["CCI-001851"],"reference_identifier":"2899","uuid":"f467fdd9-303f-47fb-abb9-95a2d37f003c","stig_uuid":"aa379772-3679-4074-8a4e-5b09f41d3e8e","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_Dom0_RHEL7_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 1\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nThe automated check examines /etc/audisp/audispd.conf for the name_format setting on the XCP-ng Dom0 system. Acceptable values are hostname, fqd, or numeric. The name_format setting labels off-loaded audit logs with the originating system identifier before sending to the central log server. Proper labeling ensures audit records can be traced back to the originating system in a centralized log collection environment.\n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_Dom0_RHEL7_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: 2E5F4666659B596AD19FE0734BCB6DCA1837E021\n~~~~~\nV-204508 - Audisp Name Format (Log Labeling)\n============================================================\n\nFile /etc/audisp/audispd.conf not found.\n\nRESULT: FAIL - audisp dispatcher not configured\n"},{"group_id_src":"V-204509","group_tree":[{"id":"V-204509","title":"SRG-OS-000342-GPOS-00133","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-204509","severity":"medium","group_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must off-load audit records onto a different system or media from the system being audited.","rule_id_src":"SV-204509r958754_rule","rule_id":"SV-204509r958754","rule_version":"RHEL-07-030300","rule_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must off-load audit records onto a different system or media from the system being audited.","fix_text":"Configure the operating system to off-load audit records onto a different system or media from the system being audited.\n\nSet the remote server option in \"/etc/audisp/audisp-remote.conf\" with the IP address of the log aggregation server.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the operating system off-loads audit records onto a different system or media from the system being audited.\n\nTo determine the remote server that the records are being sent to, use the following command:\n\n# grep -i remote_server /etc/audisp/audisp-remote.conf\nremote_server = 10.0.21.1\n\nIf a remote server is not configured, or the line is commented out, ask the System Administrator to indicate how the audit logs are off-loaded to a different system or media. \n\nIf there is no evidence that the audit logs are being off-loaded to another system or media, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_7_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Information stored in one location is vulnerable to accidental or incidental deletion or alteration.\n\nOff-loading is a common process in information systems with limited audit storage capacity.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000342-GPOS-00133, SRG-OS-000479-GPOS-00224","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-86707","V-72083"],"ccis":["CCI-001851"],"reference_identifier":"2899","uuid":"f95d13e2-e6b3-45f0-9654-7b2c7e6bc2a3","stig_uuid":"aa379772-3679-4074-8a4e-5b09f41d3e8e","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_Dom0_RHEL7_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 1\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nThe automated check examines /etc/audisp/audisp-remote.conf for the remote_server setting on the XCP-ng Dom0 system. A valid remote server address must be configured to off-load audit records to a separate system. This ensures audit records are preserved independently of the audited system and cannot be tampered with if the system is compromised. The check verifies that a non-empty, non-zero IP address is configured.\n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_Dom0_RHEL7_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: F16ECC36758AE42FA0C9AC32D5BC6CC706ABC5CE\n~~~~~\nV-204509 - Audit Off-load Remote Server\n============================================================\n\nFile /etc/audisp/audisp-remote.conf not found.\n\nRESULT: FAIL - audisp-remote not configured for audit off-loading\n"},{"group_id_src":"V-204510","group_tree":[{"id":"V-204510","title":"SRG-OS-000342-GPOS-00133","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-204510","severity":"medium","group_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must encrypt the transfer of audit records off-loaded onto a different system or media from the system being audited.","rule_id_src":"SV-204510r958754_rule","rule_id":"SV-204510r958754","rule_version":"RHEL-07-030310","rule_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must encrypt the transfer of audit records off-loaded onto a different system or media from the system being audited.","fix_text":"Configure the operating system to encrypt the transfer of off-loaded audit records onto a different system or media from the system being audited.\n\nUncomment the \"enable_krb5\" option in \"/etc/audisp/audisp-remote.conf\" and set it with the following line:\n\nenable_krb5 = yes","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the operating system encrypts audit records off-loaded onto a different system or media from the system being audited.\n\nTo determine if the transfer is encrypted, use the following command:\n\n# grep -i enable_krb5 /etc/audisp/audisp-remote.conf\nenable_krb5 = yes\n\nIf the value of the \"enable_krb5\" option is not set to \"yes\" or the line is commented out, ask the System Administrator to indicate how the audit logs are off-loaded to a different system or media. \n\nIf there is no evidence that the transfer of the audit logs being off-loaded to another system or media is encrypted, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_7_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Information stored in one location is vulnerable to accidental or incidental deletion or alteration.\n\nOff-loading is a common process in information systems with limited audit storage capacity.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000342-GPOS-00133, SRG-OS-000479-GPOS-00224","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-86709","V-72085"],"ccis":["CCI-001851"],"reference_identifier":"2899","uuid":"bcda5f19-155a-41c1-a3b7-b30c0b7debf9","stig_uuid":"aa379772-3679-4074-8a4e-5b09f41d3e8e","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_Dom0_RHEL7_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 1\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nThe automated check examines /etc/audisp/audisp-remote.conf for the enable_krb5 setting on the XCP-ng Dom0 system. Kerberos 5 encryption must be enabled (enable_krb5=yes) to protect audit records during transfer to the remote audit server. Without encryption, audit records could be intercepted or modified in transit, compromising the integrity of the audit trail.\n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_Dom0_RHEL7_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: 43553F03A63C372FA194385FA1609D371D93CE20\n~~~~~\nV-204510 - Encrypted Audit Transfer (Kerberos)\n============================================================\n\nFile /etc/audisp/audisp-remote.conf not found.\n\nRESULT: FAIL - audisp-remote not configured\n"},{"group_id_src":"V-204511","group_tree":[{"id":"V-204511","title":"SRG-OS-000342-GPOS-00133","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-204511","severity":"medium","group_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must be configured so that the audit system takes appropriate action when the audit storage volume is full.","rule_id_src":"SV-204511r958754_rule","rule_id":"SV-204511r958754","rule_version":"RHEL-07-030320","rule_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must be configured so that the audit system takes appropriate action when the audit storage volume is full.","fix_text":"Configure the action the operating system takes if the disk the audit records are written to becomes full.\n\nUncomment or edit the \"disk_full_action\" option in \"/etc/audisp/audisp-remote.conf\" and set it to \"syslog\", \"single\", or \"halt\", such as the following line:\n\ndisk_full_action = single","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the action the operating system takes if the disk the audit records are written to becomes full.\n\nTo determine the action that takes place if the disk is full on the remote server, use the following command:\n\n# grep -i disk_full_action /etc/audisp/audisp-remote.conf\ndisk_full_action = single\n\nIf the value of the \"disk_full_action\" option is not \"syslog\", \"single\", or \"halt\", or the line is commented out, ask the System Administrator to indicate how the audit logs are off-loaded to a different system or storage media, and to indicate the action taken when the disk is full on the remote server.\n\nIf there is no evidence that the system is configured to off-load audit logs to a different system or storage media, or if the configuration does not take appropriate action when the disk is full on the remote server, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_7_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Taking appropriate action in case of a filled audit storage volume will minimize the possibility of losing audit records.\nOne method of off-loading audit logs in Red Hat Enterprise Linux is with the use of the audisp-remote dameon.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-86711","V-72087"],"ccis":["CCI-001851"],"reference_identifier":"2899","uuid":"97739a47-bff0-4c53-a871-2d5c02acf143","stig_uuid":"aa379772-3679-4074-8a4e-5b09f41d3e8e","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_Dom0_RHEL7_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 1\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nThe automated check examines /etc/audisp/audisp-remote.conf for the disk_full_action setting on the XCP-ng Dom0 system. Acceptable values are syslog, single, or halt. This setting determines what action the system takes when the remote audit storage volume is full, ensuring audit events are not silently lost when storage is exhausted.\n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_Dom0_RHEL7_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: D9F32382FF8F0C8066DEB31DA650B66CBD76824C\n~~~~~\nV-204511 - Audit Storage Volume Full Action\n============================================================\n\nFile /etc/audisp/audisp-remote.conf not found.\n\nRESULT: FAIL - audisp-remote not configured\n"},{"group_id_src":"V-204512","group_tree":[{"id":"V-204512","title":"SRG-OS-000342-GPOS-00133","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-204512","severity":"medium","group_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must be configured so that the audit system takes appropriate action when there is an error sending audit records to a remote system.","rule_id_src":"SV-204512r958754_rule","rule_id":"SV-204512r958754","rule_version":"RHEL-07-030321","rule_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must be configured so that the audit system takes appropriate action when there is an error sending audit records to a remote system.","fix_text":"Configure the action the operating system takes if there is an error sending audit records to a remote system.\n\nUncomment the \"network_failure_action\" option in \"/etc/audisp/audisp-remote.conf\" and set it to \"syslog\", \"single\", or \"halt\".\n\nnetwork_failure_action = syslog","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the action the operating system takes if there is an error sending audit records to a remote system.\n\nCheck the action that takes place if there is an error sending audit records to a remote system with the following command:\n\n# grep -i network_failure_action /etc/audisp/audisp-remote.conf\nnetwork_failure_action = syslog\n\nIf the value of the \"network_failure_action\" option is not \"syslog\", \"single\", or \"halt\", or the line is commented out, ask the System Administrator to indicate how the audit logs are off-loaded to a different system or storage media, and to indicate the action taken if there is an error sending audit records to the remote system.\n\nIf there is no evidence that the system is configured to off-load audit logs to a different system or storage media, or if the configuration does not take appropriate action if there is an error sending audit records to the remote system, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_7_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Taking appropriate action when there is an error sending audit records to a remote system will minimize the possibility of losing audit records.\nOne method of off-loading audit logs in Red Hat Enterprise Linux is with the use of the audisp-remote dameon.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-87815","V-73163"],"ccis":["CCI-001851"],"reference_identifier":"2899","uuid":"0addb734-1221-45b3-8af7-648f76c77580","stig_uuid":"aa379772-3679-4074-8a4e-5b09f41d3e8e","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_Dom0_RHEL7_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 1\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nThe automated check examines /etc/audisp/audisp-remote.conf for the network_failure_action setting on the XCP-ng Dom0 system. Acceptable values are syslog, single, or halt. This setting determines system behavior when audit records cannot be sent to the remote audit server due to network issues, ensuring appropriate action is taken rather than silently dropping audit events.\n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_Dom0_RHEL7_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: 79B5DE3FD90D2EA40F476AA1B359E7032A18DD2E\n~~~~~\nV-204512 - Audit Network Failure Action\n============================================================\n\nFile /etc/audisp/audisp-remote.conf not found.\n\nRESULT: FAIL - audisp-remote not configured\n"},{"group_id_src":"V-204513","group_tree":[{"id":"V-204513","title":"SRG-OS-000343-GPOS-00134","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-204513","severity":"medium","group_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must initiate an action to notify the System Administrator (SA) and Information System Security Officer ISSO, at a minimum, when allocated audit record storage volume reaches 75% of the repository maximum audit record storage capacity.","rule_id_src":"SV-204513r971542_rule","rule_id":"SV-204513r971542","rule_version":"RHEL-07-030330","rule_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must initiate an action to notify the System Administrator (SA) and Information System Security Officer ISSO, at a minimum, when allocated audit record storage volume reaches 75% of the repository maximum audit record storage capacity.","fix_text":"Configure the operating system to initiate an action to notify the SA and ISSO (at a minimum) when allocated audit record storage volume reaches 75 percent of the repository maximum audit record storage capacity.\n\nSet the value of the \"space_left\" keyword in \"/etc/audit/auditd.conf\" to 25 percent of the partition size.\nspace_left = 25%\nReload the auditd daemon to apply changes made to the \"/etc/audit/auditd.conf\" file.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the operating system initiates an action to notify the SA and ISSO (at a minimum) when allocated audit record storage volume reaches 75 percent of the repository maximum audit record storage capacity.\n\nCheck the system configuration to determine the partition the audit records are being written to with the following command:\n\n$ sudo grep -iw log_file /etc/audit/auditd.conf\nlog_file = /var/log/audit/audit.log\n\nDetermine what the threshold is for the system to take action when 75 percent of the repository maximum audit record storage capacity is reached:\n\n$ sudo grep -iw space_left /etc/audit/auditd.conf\nspace_left = 25%\n\nIf the value of the \"space_left\" keyword is not set to 25 percent of the total partition size, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_7_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"If security personnel are not notified immediately when storage volume reaches 75 percent utilization, they are unable to plan for audit record storage capacity expansion.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-86713","V-72089"],"ccis":["CCI-001855"],"reference_identifier":"2899","uuid":"a7f6ac6d-5c12-4cf2-861d-cca39ad0fb6b","stig_uuid":"aa379772-3679-4074-8a4e-5b09f41d3e8e","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_Dom0_RHEL7_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 1\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nThe automated check examines /etc/audit/auditd.conf for the space_left setting and compares it against 25% of the audit log partition size. The audit log location is determined from log_file in auditd.conf, and the partition size is obtained via df. The space_left value should be at least 25% of the partition to trigger notification at the 75% usage threshold. This ensures administrators are alerted before audit storage is exhausted.\n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_Dom0_RHEL7_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: D29752357B29C72B27AACD2EA208A15CA72CF059\n~~~~~\nV-204513 - Audit Record Storage 75% Notification\n============================================================\n\nAudit log file: /var/log/audit/audit.log\nPartition info:\ndf: /var/log/audit: No such file or directory\n\nspace_left not found in auditd.conf.\n\nRESULT: FAIL - space_left not configured\n"},{"group_id_src":"V-204514","group_tree":[{"id":"V-204514","title":"SRG-OS-000343-GPOS-00134","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-204514","severity":"medium","group_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must immediately notify the System Administrator (SA) and Information System Security Officer (ISSO) (at a minimum) via email when the threshold for the repository maximum audit record storage capacity is reached.","rule_id_src":"SV-204514r971542_rule","rule_id":"SV-204514r971542","rule_version":"RHEL-07-030340","rule_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must immediately notify the System Administrator (SA) and Information System Security Officer (ISSO) (at a minimum) via email when the threshold for the repository maximum audit record storage capacity is reached.","fix_text":"Configure the operating system to immediately notify the SA and ISSO (at a minimum) when the threshold for the repository maximum audit record storage capacity is reached.\n\nUncomment or edit the \"space_left_action\" keyword in \"/etc/audit/auditd.conf\" and set it to \"email\". \n \nspace_left_action = email","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the operating system immediately notifies the SA and ISSO (at a minimum) via email when the allocated audit record storage volume reaches 75 percent of the repository maximum audit record storage capacity.\n\nCheck what action the operating system takes when the threshold for the repository maximum audit record storage capacity is reached with the following command:\n\n# grep -i space_left_action  /etc/audit/auditd.conf\nspace_left_action = email\n\nIf the value of the \"space_left_action\" keyword is not set to \"email\", this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_7_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"If security personnel are not notified immediately when the threshold for the repository maximum audit record storage capacity is reached, they are unable to expand the audit record storage capacity before records are lost.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-86715","V-72091"],"ccis":["CCI-001855"],"reference_identifier":"2899","uuid":"a7aea759-1061-452c-bcd8-9b8580f61517","stig_uuid":"aa379772-3679-4074-8a4e-5b09f41d3e8e","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_Dom0_RHEL7_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 1\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nThe automated check examines /etc/audit/auditd.conf for the space_left_action setting on the XCP-ng Dom0 system. The required value is email to ensure SA and ISSO are immediately notified when audit storage reaches the threshold. Email notification provides timely alerting so administrators can take action before audit storage is exhausted and audit records are lost.\n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_Dom0_RHEL7_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: A426EE7C484BA3E77911936B3945B690EC0387C9\n~~~~~\nV-204514 - Audit Storage Notification Action\n============================================================\n\nspace_left_action not found in auditd.conf.\n\nRESULT: FAIL - space_left_action not configured\n"},{"group_id_src":"V-204515","group_tree":[{"id":"V-204515","title":"SRG-OS-000343-GPOS-00134","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-204515","severity":"medium","group_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must immediately notify the System Administrator (SA) and Information System Security Officer (ISSO) (at a minimum) when the threshold for the repository maximum audit record storage capacity is reached.","rule_id_src":"SV-204515r971542_rule","rule_id":"SV-204515r971542","rule_version":"RHEL-07-030350","rule_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must immediately notify the System Administrator (SA) and Information System Security Officer (ISSO) (at a minimum) when the threshold for the repository maximum audit record storage capacity is reached.","fix_text":"Configure the operating system to immediately notify the SA and ISSO (at a minimum) when the threshold for the repository maximum audit record storage capacity is reached.\n\nUncomment or edit the \"action_mail_acct\" keyword in \"/etc/audit/auditd.conf\" and set it to root and any other accounts associated with security personnel. \n \naction_mail_acct = root","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the operating system immediately notifies the SA and ISSO (at a minimum) via email when the threshold for the repository maximum audit record storage capacity is reached.\n\nCheck what account the operating system emails when the threshold for the repository maximum audit record storage capacity is reached with the following command:\n\n# grep -i action_mail_acct  /etc/audit/auditd.conf\naction_mail_acct = root\n\nIf the value of the \"action_mail_acct\" keyword is not set to \"root\" and other accounts for security personnel, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_7_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"If security personnel are not notified immediately when the threshold for the repository maximum audit record storage capacity is reached, they are unable to expand the audit record storage capacity before records are lost.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-86717","V-72093"],"ccis":["CCI-001855"],"reference_identifier":"2899","uuid":"d1d408cf-bb83-4f70-835f-d9d230d21d26","stig_uuid":"aa379772-3679-4074-8a4e-5b09f41d3e8e","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_Dom0_RHEL7_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 1\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nThe automated check examines /etc/audit/auditd.conf for the action_mail_acct setting on the XCP-ng Dom0 system. This setting specifies which account receives email notification when audit storage reaches the configured threshold. The check verifies that action_mail_acct is set to root or another valid account. This ensures responsible personnel are notified before audit storage is exhausted.\n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_Dom0_RHEL7_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: 06085FCAD32AF51C1EE7A2D6A34D8E00B033A74E\n~~~~~\nV-204515 - Audit Storage Notification Email Account\n============================================================\n\naction_mail_acct not found in auditd.conf.\n\nRESULT: FAIL - action_mail_acct not configured\n"},{"group_id_src":"V-204516","group_tree":[{"id":"V-204516","title":"SRG-OS-000327-GPOS-00127","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-204516","severity":"medium","group_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must audit all executions of privileged functions.","rule_id_src":"SV-204516r958732_rule","rule_id":"SV-204516r958732","rule_version":"RHEL-07-030360","rule_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must audit all executions of privileged functions.","fix_text":"Configure the operating system to audit the execution of privileged functions.\n\nAdd or update the following rules in \"/etc/audit/rules.d/audit.rules\":\n\n-a always,exit -F arch=b32 -S execve -C uid!=euid -F euid=0 -k setuid\n-a always,exit -F arch=b64 -S execve -C uid!=euid -F euid=0 -k setuid\n-a always,exit -F arch=b32 -S execve -C gid!=egid -F egid=0 -k setgid\n-a always,exit -F arch=b64 -S execve -C gid!=egid -F egid=0 -k setgid\n\nThe audit daemon must be restarted for the changes to take effect.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the operating system audits the execution of privileged functions using the following command:\n\n# grep -iw execve /etc/audit/audit.rules\n\n-a always,exit -F arch=b32 -S execve -C uid!=euid -F euid=0 -k setuid\n-a always,exit -F arch=b64 -S execve -C uid!=euid -F euid=0 -k setuid\n-a always,exit -F arch=b32 -S execve -C gid!=egid -F egid=0 -k setgid\n-a always,exit -F arch=b64 -S execve -C gid!=egid -F egid=0 -k setgid\n\n\nIf both the \"b32\" and \"b64\" audit rules for \"SUID\" files are not defined, this is a finding.\n\nIf both the \"b32\" and \"b64\" audit rules for \"SGID\" files are not defined, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_7_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Misuse of privileged functions, either intentionally or unintentionally by authorized users, or by unauthorized external entities that have compromised information system accounts, is a serious and ongoing concern and can have significant adverse impacts on organizations. Auditing the use of privileged functions is one way to detect such misuse and identify the risk from insider threats and the advanced persistent threat.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-86719","V-72095"],"ccis":["CCI-002234"],"reference_identifier":"2899","uuid":"2187985a-631c-49a3-be2a-4b75fd7674c1","stig_uuid":"aa379772-3679-4074-8a4e-5b09f41d3e8e","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_Dom0_RHEL7_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 1\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nThe automated check examines /etc/audit/audit.rules for execve syscall audit rules on the XCP-ng Dom0 system. Both 32-bit (b32) and 64-bit (b64) rules must be present to audit all privileged function executions where uid!=euid (setuid) and gid!=egid (setgid). These rules detect when processes execute with elevated privileges, which is critical for security monitoring on the hypervisor host.\n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_Dom0_RHEL7_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: 6D936ECC8D93E2147154DCAC595A18563E3E5DEF\n~~~~~\nV-204516 - Audit Privileged Function Execution (execve)\n============================================================\n\nAudit rules matching 'execve':\ngrep: /etc/audit/audit.rules: No such file or directory\n\nRESULT: FAIL - No audit rules found for execve\n"},{"group_id_src":"V-204517","group_tree":[{"id":"V-204517","title":"SRG-OS-000064-GPOS-00033","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-204517","severity":"medium","group_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must audit all uses of the chown, fchown, fchownat, and lchown syscalls.","rule_id_src":"SV-204517r958446_rule","rule_id":"SV-204517r958446","rule_version":"RHEL-07-030370","rule_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must audit all uses of the chown, fchown, fchownat, and lchown syscalls.","fix_text":"Add or update the following rule in \"/etc/audit/rules.d/audit.rules\":\n\n-a always,exit -F arch=b32 -S chown,fchown,fchownat,lchown -F auid>=1000 -F auid!=unset -k perm_mod\n\n-a always,exit -F arch=b64 -S chown,fchown,fchownat,lchown -F auid>=1000 -F auid!=unset -k perm_mod\n\nThe audit daemon must be restarted for the changes to take effect.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the operating system generates audit records upon successful/unsuccessful attempts to use the \"chown\", \"fchown\", \"fchownat\", and \"lchown\" syscalls.\r\n\r\nCheck the file system rules in \"/etc/audit/audit.rules\" with the following commands:\r\n\r\n# grep chown /etc/audit/audit.rules\r\n\r\n-a always,exit -F arch=b32 -S chown,fchown,fchownat,lchown -F auid>=1000 -F auid!=unset -k perm_mod\r\n\r\n-a always,exit -F arch=b64 -S chown,fchown,fchownat,lchown -F auid>=1000 -F auid!=unset -k perm_mod\r\n\r\nIf both the \"b32\" and \"b64\" audit rules are not defined for the \"chown\", \"fchown\", \"fchownat\", and \"lchown\" syscalls, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_7_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Without generating audit records that are specific to the security and mission needs of the organization, it would be difficult to establish, correlate, and investigate the events relating to an incident or identify those responsible for one.\r\n\r\nAudit records can be generated from various components within the information system (e.g., module or policy filter).\r\n\r\nWhen a user logs on, the auid is set to the uid of the account that is being authenticated. Daemons are not user sessions and have the loginuid set to -1. The auid representation is an unsigned 32-bit integer, which equals 4294967295. The audit system interprets -1, 4294967295, and \"unset\" in the same way.\r\n\r\nThe system call rules are loaded into a matching engine that intercepts each syscall made by all programs on the system. Therefore, it is very important to use syscall rules only when absolutely necessary since these affect performance. The more rules, the bigger the performance hit. The performance can be helped, however, by combining syscalls into one rule whenever possible.\r\n\r\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000064-GPOS-00033, SRG-OS-000392-GPOS-00172, SRG-OS-000458-GPOS-00203, SRG-OS-000474-GPOS-00219","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-86721","V-72097"],"ccis":["CCI-000126","CCI-000172"],"reference_identifier":"2899","uuid":"1b34383e-920c-46dd-991d-e95079c37811","stig_uuid":"aa379772-3679-4074-8a4e-5b09f41d3e8e","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_Dom0_RHEL7_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 1\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nThe automated check examines /etc/audit/audit.rules for chown/fchown/fchownat/lchown syscall audit rules on the XCP-ng Dom0 system. Both 32-bit and 64-bit rules must be present to capture all ownership change attempts. These rules are essential for detecting unauthorized file ownership modifications that could be used to escalate privileges or hide malicious activity on the hypervisor.\n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_Dom0_RHEL7_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: 5D01841984029073B5C54F6AD4B9FD6E95BC89D8\n~~~~~\nV-204517 - Audit chown/fchown/fchownat/lchown\n============================================================\n\nAudit rules matching 'chown':\ngrep: /etc/audit/audit.rules: No such file or directory\n\nRESULT: FAIL - No audit rules found for chown\n"},{"group_id_src":"V-204521","group_tree":[{"id":"V-204521","title":"SRG-OS-000458-GPOS-00203","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-204521","severity":"medium","group_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must audit all uses of the chmod, fchmod, and fchmodat syscalls.","rule_id_src":"SV-204521r991570_rule","rule_id":"SV-204521r991570","rule_version":"RHEL-07-030410","rule_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must audit all uses of the chmod, fchmod, and fchmodat syscalls.","fix_text":"Configure the operating system to generate audit records upon successful/unsuccessful attempts to use the \"chmod\", \"fchmod\", and \"fchmodat\" syscalls.\r\n\r\nAdd or update the following rules in \"/etc/audit/rules.d/audit.rules\":\r\n\r\n-a always,exit -F arch=b32 -S chmod,fchmod,fchmodat -F auid>=1000 -F auid!=unset -k perm_mod\r\n\r\n-a always,exit -F arch=b64 -S chmod,fchmod,fchmodat -F auid>=1000 -F auid!=unset -k perm_mod\r\n\r\nThe audit daemon must be restarted for the changes to take effect.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the operating system generates audit records upon successful/unsuccessful attempts to use the \"chmod\", \"fchmod\", and \"fchmodat\" syscalls.\r\n\r\nCheck the file system rules in \"/etc/audit/audit.rules\" with the following command:\r\n\r\n# grep chmod /etc/audit/audit.rules\r\n\r\n-a always,exit -F arch=b32 -S chmod,fchmod,fchmodat -F auid>=1000 -F auid!=unset -k perm_mod\r\n\r\n-a always,exit -F arch=b64 -S chmod,fchmod,fchmodat -F auid>=1000 -F auid!=unset -k perm_mod\r\n\r\nIf both the \"b32\" and \"b64\" audit rules are not defined for the \"chmod\", \"fchmod\", and \"fchmodat\" syscalls, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_7_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Without generating audit records that are specific to the security and mission needs of the organization, it would be difficult to establish, correlate, and investigate the events relating to an incident or identify those responsible for one.\r\n\r\nAudit records can be generated from various components within the information system (e.g., module or policy filter).\r\n\r\nWhen a user logs on, the auid is set to the uid of the account that is being authenticated. Daemons are not user sessions and have the loginuid set to -1. The auid representation is an unsigned 32-bit integer, which equals 4294967295. The audit system interprets -1, 4294967295, and \"unset\" in the same way.\r\n\r\nThe system call rules are loaded into a matching engine that intercepts each syscall made by all programs on the system. Therefore, it is very important to use syscall rules only when absolutely necessary since these affect performance. The more rules, the bigger the performance hit. The performance can be helped, however, by combining syscalls into one rule whenever possible.\r\n\r\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000458-GPOS-00203, SRG-OS-000392-GPOS-00172, SRG-OS-000064-GPOS-00033","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-86729","V-72105"],"ccis":["CCI-000172"],"reference_identifier":"2899","uuid":"d9231025-5acd-4785-8c83-522b1f75b224","stig_uuid":"aa379772-3679-4074-8a4e-5b09f41d3e8e","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_Dom0_RHEL7_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 1\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nThe automated check examines /etc/audit/audit.rules for chmod/fchmod/fchmodat syscall audit rules on the XCP-ng Dom0 system. Both 32-bit and 64-bit rules must be present to capture all permission change attempts. These rules detect unauthorized file permission modifications that could weaken security controls on the hypervisor host.\n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_Dom0_RHEL7_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: 948B5683FDA23099CE973272517731000C6D292B\n~~~~~\nV-204521 - Audit chmod/fchmod/fchmodat\n============================================================\n\nAudit rules matching 'chmod':\ngrep: /etc/audit/audit.rules: No such file or directory\n\nRESULT: FAIL - No audit rules found for chmod\n"},{"group_id_src":"V-204524","group_tree":[{"id":"V-204524","title":"SRG-OS-000458-GPOS-00203","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-204524","severity":"medium","group_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must audit all uses of the setxattr, fsetxattr, lsetxattr, removexattr, fremovexattr, and lremovexattr syscalls.","rule_id_src":"SV-204524r991570_rule","rule_id":"SV-204524r991570","rule_version":"RHEL-07-030440","rule_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must audit all uses of the setxattr, fsetxattr, lsetxattr, removexattr, fremovexattr, and lremovexattr syscalls.","fix_text":"Configure the operating system to generate audit records upon successful/unsuccessful attempts to use the \"setxattr\", \"fsetxattr\", \"lsetxattr\", \"removexattr\", \"fremovexattr\", and \"lremovexattr\" syscalls.\r\n\r\nAdd or update the following rules in \"/etc/audit/rules.d/audit.rules\":\r\n\r\n-a always,exit -F arch=b32 -S setxattr,fsetxattr,lsetxattr,removexattr,fremovexattr,lremovexattr -F auid>=1000 -F auid!=unset -k perm_mod\r\n\r\n-a always,exit -F arch=b64 -S setxattr,fsetxattr,lsetxattr,removexattr,fremovexattr,lremovexattr -F auid>=1000 -F auid!=unset -k perm_mod\r\n\r\nThe audit daemon must be restarted for the changes to take effect.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the operating system generates audit records upon successful/unsuccessful attempts to use the \"setxattr\", \"fsetxattr\", \"lsetxattr\", \"removexattr\", \"fremovexattr\", and \"lremovexattr\" syscalls.\r\n\r\nCheck the file system rules in \"/etc/audit/audit.rules\" with the following commands:\r\n\r\n# grep xattr /etc/audit/audit.rules\r\n\r\n-a always,exit -F arch=b32 -S setxattr,fsetxattr,lsetxattr,removexattr,fremovexattr,lremovexattr -F auid>=1000 -F auid!=unset -k perm_mod\r\n\r\n-a always,exit -F arch=b64 -S setxattr,fsetxattr,lsetxattr,removexattr,fremovexattr,lremovexattr -F auid>=1000 -F auid!=unset -k perm_mod\r\n\r\nIf both the \"b32\" and \"b64\" audit rules are not defined for the \"setxattr\", \"fsetxattr\", \"lsetxattr\", \"removexattr\", \"fremovexattr\", and \"lremovexattr\" syscalls, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_7_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Without generating audit records that are specific to the security and mission needs of the organization, it would be difficult to establish, correlate, and investigate the events relating to an incident or identify those responsible for one.\r\n\r\nAudit records can be generated from various components within the information system (e.g., module or policy filter).\r\n\r\nWhen a user logs on, the auid is set to the uid of the account that is being authenticated. Daemons are not user sessions and have the loginuid set to -1. The auid representation is an unsigned 32-bit integer, which equals 4294967295. The audit system interprets -1, 4294967295, and \"unset\" in the same way.\r\n\r\nThe system call rules are loaded into a matching engine that intercepts each syscall made by all programs on the system. Therefore, it is very important to use syscall rules only when absolutely necessary since these affect performance. The more rules, the bigger the performance hit. The performance can be helped, however, by combining syscalls into one rule whenever possible.\r\n\r\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000458-GPOS-00203, SRG-OS-000392-GPOS-00172, SRG-OS-000064-GPOS-00033","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-86735","V-72111"],"ccis":["CCI-000172"],"reference_identifier":"2899","uuid":"29d9dfdf-3bf6-4e9d-8b02-7b33048fc67f","stig_uuid":"aa379772-3679-4074-8a4e-5b09f41d3e8e","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_Dom0_RHEL7_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 1\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nThe automated check examines /etc/audit/audit.rules for extended attribute (xattr) syscall audit rules on the XCP-ng Dom0 system. Both 32-bit and 64-bit rules must be present for setxattr, fsetxattr, lsetxattr, removexattr, fremovexattr, and lremovexattr. These rules detect modifications to file extended attributes including SELinux labels and ACLs.\n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_Dom0_RHEL7_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: 765BD0327D1CA2583414DFC7C6C9D53871B14874\n~~~~~\nV-204524 - Audit xattr Operations\n============================================================\n\nAudit rules matching 'xattr':\ngrep: /etc/audit/audit.rules: No such file or directory\n\nRESULT: FAIL - No audit rules found for setxattr\n"},{"group_id_src":"V-204531","group_tree":[{"id":"V-204531","title":"SRG-OS-000064-GPOS-00033","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-204531","severity":"medium","group_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must audit all uses of the creat, open, openat, open_by_handle_at, truncate, and ftruncate syscalls.","rule_id_src":"SV-204531r958446_rule","rule_id":"SV-204531r958446","rule_version":"RHEL-07-030510","rule_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must audit all uses of the creat, open, openat, open_by_handle_at, truncate, and ftruncate syscalls.","fix_text":"Configure the operating system to generate audit records upon successful/unsuccessful attempts to use the \"creat\", \"open\", \"openat\", \"open_by_handle_at\", \"truncate\", and \"ftruncate\" syscalls.\n\nAdd or update the following rules in \"/etc/audit/rules.d/audit.rules\":\n\n-a always,exit -F arch=b32 -S creat,open,openat,open_by_handle_at,truncate,ftruncate -F exit=-EPERM -F auid>=1000 -F auid!=unset -k access\n\n-a always,exit -F arch=b32 -S creat,open,openat,open_by_handle_at,truncate,ftruncate -F exit=-EACCES -F auid>=1000 -F auid!=unset -k access\n\n-a always,exit -F arch=b64 -S creat,open,openat,open_by_handle_at,truncate,ftruncate -F exit=-EPERM -F auid>=1000 -F auid!=unset -k access\n\n-a always,exit -F arch=b64 -S creat,open,openat,open_by_handle_at,truncate,ftruncate -F exit=-EACCES -F auid>=1000 -F auid!=unset -k access\n\nThe audit daemon must be restarted for the changes to take effect.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the operating system generates audit records upon successful/unsuccessful attempts to use the \"creat\", \"open\", \"openat\", \"open_by_handle_at\", \"truncate\", and \"ftruncate\" syscalls.\n\nCheck the file system rules in \"/etc/audit/audit.rules\" with the following commands:\n\n# grep 'open\\|truncate\\|creat' /etc/audit/audit.rules\n\n-a always,exit -F arch=b32 -S creat,open,openat,open_by_handle_at,truncate,ftruncate -F exit=-EPERM -F auid>=1000 -F auid!=unset -k access\n\n-a always,exit -F arch=b32 -S creat,open,openat,open_by_handle_at,truncate,ftruncate -F exit=-EACCES -F auid>=1000 -F auid!=unset -k access\n\n-a always,exit -F arch=b64 -S creat,open,openat,open_by_handle_at,truncate,ftruncate -F exit=-EPERM -F auid>=1000 -F auid!=unset -k access\n\n-a always,exit -F arch=b64 -S creat,open,openat,open_by_handle_at,truncate,ftruncate -F exit=-EACCES -F auid>=1000 -F auid!=unset -k access\n\nIf both the \"b32\" and \"b64\" audit rules are not defined for the \"creat\", \"open\", \"openat\", \"open_by_handle_at\", \"truncate\", and \"ftruncate\" syscalls, this is a finding.\n\nIf the output does not produce rules containing \"-F exit=-EPERM\", this is a finding.\n\nIf the output does not produce rules containing \"-F exit=-EACCES\", this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_7_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Without generating audit records that are specific to the security and mission needs of the organization, it would be difficult to establish, correlate, and investigate the events relating to an incident or identify those responsible for one.\n\nAudit records can be generated from various components within the information system (e.g., module or policy filter).\n\nWhen a user logs on, the auid is set to the uid of the account that is being authenticated. Daemons are not user sessions and have the loginuid set to -1. The auid representation is an unsigned 32-bit integer, which equals 4294967295. The audit system interprets -1, 4294967295, and \"unset\" in the same way.\n\nThe system call rules are loaded into a matching engine that intercepts each syscall made by all programs on the system. Therefore, it is very important to use syscall rules only when absolutely necessary since these affect performance. The more rules, the bigger the performance hit. The performance can be helped, however, by combining syscalls into one rule whenever possible.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000064-GPOS-00033, SRG-OS-000458-GPOS-00203, SRG-OS-000461-GPOS-00205, SRG-OS-000392-GPOS-00172","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-86749","V-72125"],"ccis":["CCI-000172","CCI-002884"],"reference_identifier":"2899","uuid":"ff577f5d-1c55-461e-9730-3ef2959c9d4d","stig_uuid":"aa379772-3679-4074-8a4e-5b09f41d3e8e","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_Dom0_RHEL7_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 1\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nThe automated check examines /etc/audit/audit.rules for file access syscall audit rules (creat, open, openat, open_by_handle_at, truncate, ftruncate) on the XCP-ng Dom0 system. Both 32-bit and 64-bit rules must be present. These rules detect unauthorized file access attempts and are critical for maintaining an audit trail of file operations on the hypervisor host.\n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_Dom0_RHEL7_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: A2FD307A583F76632477BBDF9D8652EF837D2B31\n~~~~~\nV-204531 - Audit File Access (creat/open/truncate)\n============================================================\n\nAudit rules for file access syscalls:\ngrep: /etc/audit/audit.rules: No such file or directory\n\nRESULT: FAIL - No audit rules found for file access syscalls\n"},{"group_id_src":"V-204536","group_tree":[{"id":"V-204536","title":"SRG-OS-000392-GPOS-00172","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-204536","severity":"medium","group_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must audit all uses of the semanage command.","rule_id_src":"SV-204536r958846_rule","rule_id":"SV-204536r958846","rule_version":"RHEL-07-030560","rule_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must audit all uses of the semanage command.","fix_text":"Configure the operating system to generate audit records when successful/unsuccessful attempts to use the \"semanage\" command occur.\n\nAdd or update the following rule in \"/etc/audit/rules.d/audit.rules\":\n\n-a always,exit -F path=/usr/sbin/semanage -F perm=x -F auid>=1000 -F auid!=unset -k privileged-priv_change\n\nThe audit daemon must be restarted for the changes to take effect.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the operating system generates audit records when successful/unsuccessful attempts to use the \"semanage\" command occur.\n\nCheck the file system rule in \"/etc/audit/audit.rules\" with the following command:\n\n$ sudo grep -w \"/usr/sbin/semanage\" /etc/audit/audit.rules\n\n-a always,exit -F path=/usr/sbin/semanage -F perm=x -F auid>=1000 -F auid!=unset -k privileged-priv_change\n\nIf the command does not return any output, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_7_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Without generating audit records that are specific to the security and mission needs of the organization, it would be difficult to establish, correlate, and investigate the events relating to an incident or identify those responsible for one.\n\nAudit records can be generated from various components within the information system (e.g., module or policy filter).\n\nWhen a user logs on, the auid is set to the uid of the account that is being authenticated. Daemons are not user sessions and have the loginuid set to -1. The auid representation is an unsigned 32-bit integer, which equals 4294967295. The audit system interprets -1, 4294967295, and \"unset\" in the same way.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000392-GPOS-00172, SRG-OS-000463-GPOS-00207, SRG-OS-000465-GPOS-00209","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-86759","V-72135"],"ccis":["CCI-000172","CCI-002884"],"reference_identifier":"2899","uuid":"8ae764ce-3edf-45fb-b3b1-f4b1d0f3768b","stig_uuid":"aa379772-3679-4074-8a4e-5b09f41d3e8e","status":"not_a_finding","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_Dom0_RHEL7_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 2\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nThe automated check examines /etc/audit/audit.rules for an audit rule covering the semanage command (/usr/sbin/semanage) on the XCP-ng Dom0 system. The rule must specify path, execution permission (perm=x), and auid filter. If semanage is not installed on the system, the check passes as the audit rule is not required for a non-existent command. Semanage is used to manage SELinux policy and auditing its use is critical for tracking security policy changes.\n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_Dom0_RHEL7_Checks) found this to be NOT A FINDING on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: E970918E4C05880E98AD2CA1F080F675AF038E8E\n~~~~~\nV-204536 - Audit semanage Command\n============================================================\n\nAudit rules for /usr/sbin/semanage:\ngrep: /etc/audit/audit.rules: No such file or directory\n\nCommand /usr/sbin/semanage not found on system.\nRESULT: PASS - Command not present, audit rule not required\n"},{"group_id_src":"V-204537","group_tree":[{"id":"V-204537","title":"SRG-OS-000392-GPOS-00172","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-204537","severity":"medium","group_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must audit all uses of the setsebool command.","rule_id_src":"SV-204537r958846_rule","rule_id":"SV-204537r958846","rule_version":"RHEL-07-030570","rule_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must audit all uses of the setsebool command.","fix_text":"Configure the operating system to generate audit records when successful/unsuccessful attempts to use the \"setsebool\" command occur.\n\nAdd or update the following rule in \"/etc/audit/rules.d/audit.rules\":\n\n-a always,exit -F path=/usr/sbin/setsebool -F perm=x -F auid>=1000 -F auid!=unset -k privileged-priv_change\n\nThe audit daemon must be restarted for the changes to take effect.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the operating system generates audit records when succes