ecurity label modifications.\n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_Dom0_RHEL7_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: 751D2249B7FBF8EAF274F4B023218E711BB622C8\n~~~~~\nV-204538 - Audit chcon Command\n============================================================\n\nAudit rules for /usr/bin/chcon:\ngrep: /etc/audit/audit.rules: No such file or directory\n\nRESULT: FAIL - No audit rule found for /usr/bin/chcon\n"},{"group_id_src":"V-204539","group_tree":[{"id":"V-204539","title":"SRG-OS-000392-GPOS-00172","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-204539","severity":"medium","group_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must audit all uses of the setfiles command.","rule_id_src":"SV-204539r958846_rule","rule_id":"SV-204539r958846","rule_version":"RHEL-07-030590","rule_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must audit all uses of the setfiles command.","fix_text":"Configure the operating system to generate audit records when successful/unsuccessful attempts to use the \"setfiles\" command occur.\n\nAdd or update the following rule in \"/etc/audit/rules.d/audit.rules\":\n\n-a always,exit -F path=/usr/sbin/setfiles -F perm=x -F auid>=1000 -F auid!=unset -k privileged-priv_change\n\nThe audit daemon must be restarted for the changes to take effect.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the operating system generates audit records when successful/unsuccessful attempts to use the \"setfiles\" command occur.\n\nCheck the file system rule in \"/etc/audit/audit.rules\" with the following command:\n\n$ sudo grep -w \"/usr/sbin/setfiles\" /etc/audit/audit.rules\n\n-a always,exit -F path=/usr/sbin/setfiles -F perm=x -F auid>=1000 -F auid!=unset -k privileged-priv_change\n\nIf the command does not return any output, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_7_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Without generating audit records that are specific to the security and mission needs of the organization, it would be difficult to establish, correlate, and investigate the events relating to an incident or identify those responsible for one.\n\nAudit records can be generated from various components within the information system (e.g., module or policy filter).\n\nWhen a user logs on, the auid is set to the uid of the account that is being authenticated. Daemons are not user sessions and have the loginuid set to -1. The auid representation is an unsigned 32-bit integer, which equals 4294967295. The audit system interprets -1, 4294967295, and \"unset\" in the same way.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000392-GPOS-00172, SRG-OS-000463-GPOS-00207, SRG-OS-000465-GPOS-00209","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-86765","V-72141"],"ccis":["CCI-000172","CCI-002884"],"reference_identifier":"2899","uuid":"889509e7-29b9-405e-b20a-938704122aef","stig_uuid":"aa379772-3679-4074-8a4e-5b09f41d3e8e","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_Dom0_RHEL7_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 1\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nThe automated check examines /etc/audit/audit.rules for an audit rule covering the setfiles command (/usr/sbin/setfiles) on the XCP-ng Dom0 system. If setfiles is not installed, the check passes. Setfiles sets SELinux security contexts on filesystem paths and auditing its use tracks bulk security label changes.\n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_Dom0_RHEL7_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: E2C515D689240DE05311B7FF9A46D8F8FFCE2BEA\n~~~~~\nV-204539 - Audit setfiles Command\n============================================================\n\nAudit rules for /usr/sbin/setfiles:\ngrep: /etc/audit/audit.rules: No such file or directory\n\nRESULT: FAIL - No audit rule found for /usr/sbin/setfiles\n"},{"group_id_src":"V-204540","group_tree":[{"id":"V-204540","title":"SRG-OS-000392-GPOS-00172","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-204540","severity":"medium","group_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must generate audit records for all unsuccessful account access events.","rule_id_src":"SV-204540r958846_rule","rule_id":"SV-204540r958846","rule_version":"RHEL-07-030610","rule_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must generate audit records for all unsuccessful account access events.","fix_text":"Configure the operating system to generate audit records when unsuccessful account access events occur. \n\nAdd or update the following rule in \"/etc/audit/rules.d/audit.rules\": \n\n-w /var/run/faillock -p wa -k logins\n\nThe audit daemon must be restarted for the changes to take effect.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the operating system generates audit records when unsuccessful account access events occur. \n\nCheck the file system rule in \"/etc/audit/audit.rules\" with the following commands: \n\n# grep -i /var/run/faillock /etc/audit/audit.rules\n\n-w /var/run/faillock -p wa -k logins\n\nIf the command does not return any output, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_7_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Without generating audit records that are specific to the security and mission needs of the organization, it would be difficult to establish, correlate, and investigate the events relating to an incident or identify those responsible for one.\n\nAudit records can be generated from various components within the information system (e.g., module or policy filter).\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000392-GPOS-00172, SRG-OS-000470-GPOS-00214, SRG-OS-000473-GPOS-00218","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-86769","V-72145"],"ccis":["CCI-000126","CCI-000172","CCI-002884"],"reference_identifier":"2899","uuid":"b80086a0-ab83-4c82-800a-058501147b82","stig_uuid":"aa379772-3679-4074-8a4e-5b09f41d3e8e","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_Dom0_RHEL7_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 1\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nThe automated check examines /etc/audit/audit.rules for a file watch rule on /var/run/faillock on the XCP-ng Dom0 system. The faillock directory records failed authentication attempts and auditing write/attribute changes to it captures unsuccessful account access events. This is essential for detecting brute force attacks and unauthorized access attempts.\n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_Dom0_RHEL7_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: 38215EB27A417D093960B569DE1BC9CC3CDA4AF7\n~~~~~\nV-204540 - Audit Unsuccessful Account Access (faillock)\n============================================================\n\nAudit rules for /var/run/faillock:\ngrep: /etc/audit/audit.rules: No such file or directory\n\nRESULT: FAIL - No file watch audit rule found for /var/run/faillock\n"},{"group_id_src":"V-204541","group_tree":[{"id":"V-204541","title":"SRG-OS-000392-GPOS-00172","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-204541","severity":"medium","group_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must generate audit records for all successful account access events.","rule_id_src":"SV-204541r958846_rule","rule_id":"SV-204541r958846","rule_version":"RHEL-07-030620","rule_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must generate audit records for all successful account access events.","fix_text":"Configure the operating system to generate audit records when successful account access events occur. \n\nAdd or update the following rule in \"/etc/audit/rules.d/audit.rules\": \n\n-w /var/log/lastlog -p wa -k logins\n\nThe audit daemon must be restarted for the changes to take effect.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the operating system generates audit records when successful account access events occur. \n\nCheck the file system rules in \"/etc/audit/audit.rules\" with the following commands: \n\n# grep -i /var/log/lastlog /etc/audit/audit.rules\n\n-w /var/log/lastlog -p wa -k logins \n\nIf the command does not return any output, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_7_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Without generating audit records that are specific to the security and mission needs of the organization, it would be difficult to establish, correlate, and investigate the events relating to an incident or identify those responsible for one.\n\nAudit records can be generated from various components within the information system (e.g., module or policy filter).\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000392-GPOS-00172, SRG-OS-000470-GPOS-00214, SRG-OS-000473-GPOS-00218","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-86771","V-72147"],"ccis":["CCI-000126","CCI-000172","CCI-002884"],"reference_identifier":"2899","uuid":"46e35877-79e7-4740-b5b0-e79eb67e52db","stig_uuid":"aa379772-3679-4074-8a4e-5b09f41d3e8e","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_Dom0_RHEL7_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 1\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nThe automated check examines /etc/audit/audit.rules for a file watch rule on /var/log/lastlog on the XCP-ng Dom0 system. The lastlog file records successful login events and auditing write/attribute changes to it captures all successful account access events. This provides an audit trail of who logged into the system and when.\n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_Dom0_RHEL7_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: 18E379701C98CA39D5821643A27EC9158A6F264F\n~~~~~\nV-204541 - Audit Successful Account Access (lastlog)\n============================================================\n\nAudit rules for /var/log/lastlog:\ngrep: /etc/audit/audit.rules: No such file or directory\n\nRESULT: FAIL - No file watch audit rule found for /var/log/lastlog\n"},{"group_id_src":"V-204542","group_tree":[{"id":"V-204542","title":"SRG-OS-000042-GPOS-00020","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-204542","severity":"medium","group_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must audit all uses of the passwd command.","rule_id_src":"SV-204542r958422_rule","rule_id":"SV-204542r958422","rule_version":"RHEL-07-030630","rule_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must audit all uses of the passwd command.","fix_text":"Configure the operating system to generate audit records when successful/unsuccessful attempts to use the \"passwd\" command occur.\n\nAdd or update the following rule in \"/etc/audit/rules.d/audit.rules\":\n\n-a always,exit -F path=/usr/bin/passwd -F perm=x -F auid>=1000 -F auid!=unset -k privileged-passwd\n\nThe audit daemon must be restarted for the changes to take effect.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the operating system generates audit records when successful/unsuccessful attempts to use the \"passwd\" command occur.\n\nCheck the file system rule in \"/etc/audit/audit.rules\" with the following command:\n\n$ sudo grep -w \"/usr/bin/passwd\" /etc/audit/audit.rules\n\n-a always,exit -F path=/usr/bin/passwd -F perm=x -F auid>=1000 -F auid!=unset -k privileged-passwd\n\nIf the command does not return any output, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Red_Hat_Enterprise_Linux_7_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Reconstruction of harmful events or forensic analysis is not possible if audit records do not contain enough information.\n\nAt a minimum, the organization must audit the full-text recording of privileged password commands. The organization must maintain audit trails in sufficient detail to reconstruct events to determine the cause and impact of compromise.\n\nWhen a user logs on, the auid is set to the uid of the account that is being authenticated. Daemons are not user sessions and have the loginuid set to -1. The auid representation is an unsigned 32-bit integer, which equals 4294967295. The audit system interprets -1, 4294967295, and \"unset\" in the same way.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000042-GPOS-00020, SRG-OS-000392-GPOS-00172, SRG-OS-000471-GPOS-00215","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-86773","V-72149"],"ccis":["CCI-000135","CCI-000172","CCI-002884"],"reference_identifier":"2899","uuid":"dcca219b-5b3d-46e9-b27c-5ab649f9dd06","stig_uuid":"aa379772-3679-4074-8a4e-5b09f41d3e8e","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_Dom0_RHEL7_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 1\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nThe automated check examines /etc/audit/audit.rules for an audit rule covering the passwd command (/usr/bin/passwd) on the XCP-ng Dom0 system. The passwd command changes user passwords and auditing its use is critical for tracking password management activities and detecting unauthorized password changes on the hypervisor host.\n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_Dom0_RHEL7_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: F8A4B4303661BF18A6BFC9F1DB2731EC72F094FA\n~~~~~\nV-204542 - Audit passwd Command\n============================================================\n\nAudit rules for /usr/bin/passwd:\ngrep: /etc/audit/audit.rules: No such file or directory\n\nRESULT: FAIL - No audit rule found for /usr/bin/passwd\n"},{"group_id_src":"V-204543","group_tree":[{"id":"V-204543","title":"SRG-OS-000042-GPOS-00020","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-204543","severity":"medium","group_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must audit all uses of the unix_chkpwd command.","rule_id_src":"SV-204543r958422_rule","rule_id":"SV-204543r958422","rule_version":"RHEL-07-030640","rule_title":"The Red Hat Enterprise Linux operating system must audit all uses of the unix_chkpwd command.","fix_text":"Configure the operating system to generate audit records when successful/unsuccessful attempts to use the \"unix_chkpwd\" command occur.\n\nAdd or update the following rule in \"/etc/audit/rules.d/audit.rules\":\n\n-a always,exit -F path=/usr/sbin/unix_chkpwd -F perm=x -F auid>=1000 -F auid!=unset -k privileged-passwd\n\nThe audit daemon must be restarted for the changes to take effect.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the operating system generates audit records when successful/unsuccessful attempts to use the \"unix_chkpwd\" command occur.\n\nCheck the file system rule in \"/etc/audit/audit.rules\" with the following command:\n\n$ sudo grep -w \"/usr/sbin/unix_chkpwd\" /etc/audit/audit.rules\n\n-a always,exit -F path=/usr/sbin/unix_chkpwd -F perm=x -F auid>=1000 -F auid!=unset -k privileged-passwd\n\nIf the command does not return any output, this is a finding.","check_conte